<SLUG> BC-Sports-Baseball-Roundup,0520 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mabry, Mouton, Bragg become free agents; Hamilton gets dlrs 17
</HEADLINE>
million deal &QL; 
 &UR; By RONALD BLUM &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ Outfielders John Mabry, James Mouton and Darren
Bragg were among 39 players who became free agents Monday when
their teams failed to offer them 1999 contracts by the tender
deadline.
	   All players on 40-man rosters must be offered contracts by the
Dec. 20 deadline or they immediately go free.
	   Meanwhile, as the baseball's focus began to shift from free
agents to salary arbitration, the Toronto Blue Jays agreed to a
dlrs 17 million, three-year contract with Joey Hamilton, obtained
from the San Diego Padres during the winter meetings.
	   ``I tried over the last couple of years to get something done
with San Diego and they weren't very receptive,'' Hamilton said.
``It's like a big burden lifted off my back. I think being able to
come here and get a fresh start is going to be really good for
me.''
	   Texas outfielder Tom Goodwin agreed to a dlrs 3.25 million,
one-year contract and Mike Simms, another Rangers outfielder,
agreed to a two-year deal worth dlrs 1,725,000.
	   Left-hander Buddy Groom agreed to an dlrs 850,000, one-year deal
with Oakland and right-hander Gil Heredia agreed to a one-year
contract with the Athletics.
	   Among free agents, Baltimore signed utility player Rich Amaral
to a two-year contract and right-hander Ricky Bones to a one-year
contract, and San Diego signed 36-year-old third baseman Dave
Magadan to a one-year contract.
	   The Dec. 20 deadline to tender contracts to players on 40-man
rosters has become increasingly important in recent years, with
some teams reluctant to offer contracts to players with borderline
statistics, many of them eligible for salary arbitration.
	   Not offering a contract _ which removes a player from the 40-man
roster _ often is a way of getting around the 20 percent maximum
cut rule in the collective bargaining agreement. Teams may then
re-sign players as free agents for any amount.
	   Philadelphia did that to right-hander Ken Ryan, who made dlrs
990,000 last season. The Phillies let him go, then re-signed him
for dlrs 600,000, a 29 percent cut.
	   Left-hander Alvin Morman, cut loose by San Francisco, agreed
within hour to a one-year contract with Kansas City.
	   The New York Yankees failed to offer a contract to outfielder
Darryl Strawberry for a different reason. Strawberry is recovering
from colon cancer surgery and may not be ready by opening day in
April. New York intends to re-sign Strawberry to a minor-league
contract _ that way, if he starts the season on the disabled list,
his salary is not subject to the luxury tax.
	   Among others let loose were Anaheim left-hander Allen Watson,
Oakland pitchers Mike Mohler and Mike Oquist, Seattle outfielder
Rob Ducey and Arizona right-hander Willie Banks.
	   Also, there were no new developments in the Roger Clemens trade
talks, agent Randy Hendricks said Monday. The five-time Cy Young
Award winner wants the Toronto Blue Jays to trade him to a
contender or closer to his Houston home. 	   
</TEXT>
