<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-US-Film Fight </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Activists want probe into official who approved Hollywood film
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ A total of 38 Thai environmental and
democracy groups have called for a government investigation of the
forestry chief who is allowing a Hollywood film to be made in a
conservation area, a government official said Tuesday.
	   The groups filed a petition with the Counter Corruption
Commission, saying the forestry chief had violated national law in
granting permission to 20th Century Fox to shoot the Leonardo
DiCaprio film ``The Beach'' in a national park conservation area.
	   ``We will look into the details of the petition and see if it is
in our area of responsibility to investigate it,'' a commission
official said on condition of anonymity.
	   More than two dozen activists had staged a sit-in protest for
two weeks at Maya Beach on Phi Phi Island, the site of the filming.
The island, part of Krabi province, 550 kilometers (340 miles)
southwest of Bangkok, is in the Andaman Sea.
	   The activists opposed plans by the film crew to remove the
natural vegetation in the beach area and plant 92 palm trees,
saying that would severely degrade the beach's ecosystem.
	   They have also alleged that film crews have damaged fragile
coral reefs.
	   Last week the protesters were forced to end their sit-in when
they were surrounded by a group of over 100 thugs led by the deputy
governor of Krabi and a local headman.
	   Reporters were warned to keep away and the activists said they
were threatened with bodily harm if they did not end their protest.
	   They said the pro-film group leaders were ``influential
people,'' a code phrase in Thailand for politicians or businessmen
with dual identities as crime bosses.
	   In a roundtable on implications of shooting the film on Maya
Beach held by The Nation newspaper, many island residents and hotel
owners voiced strong opposition to the project.
	   Dr. Panom Ieamprayoon, Dean of the Law Faculty at Thammasat
University, said Forestry Chief Plodprasop Suraswadi had violated
the 1961 National Park Act by approving the film shoot.
	   He said the law only allowed alterations to the environment to
facilitate research and conservation of tourism.
	   The Counter Corruption Commission official said it usually takes
several weeks for the agency to determine whether to accept or
reject a complaint.
	   ``We will investigate the request only when it concerns
corruption, bribery among civil servants, or abuse of authority
that involves some monetary or other interest,'' he said. 	   
</TEXT>
