<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-Guilty as Charged </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Protesters charged with ``causing peace''
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ A mistake in a court summons against arrested
pro-democracy activists said that rather than disturbing society,
they were likely to improve it, a newspaper reported Tuesday.
	   The summons, written in Chinese, said the four activists, who
were charged with behaving in a disorderly manner at a July
protest, ``would probably cause society peace,'' the South China
Morning Post reported.
	   The English version, however, stated that ``a breach of the
peace was likely to be caused,'' the report said.
	   ``I was very happy when I received the summons. I thought the
(Hong Kong) government recognized that what we are doing will cause
society peace,'' defendant Tsang Kin-shing, a veteran activist and
a former legislator, told a district court Monday, according to the
Post.
	   ``I would plead guilty to the original summons.''
	   The court amended the Chinese document to conform with the
English version on Monday, and the four defendants pleaded not
guilty, the report said.
	   Tsang, Leung Kwok-hung, Lau Shan-ching and Koo Sze-yiu were
arrested on July 1 at a protest to mark the first anniversary of
the transfer of Hong Kong's sovereignty to Chinese rule.
	   The court adjourned their case until February. 	   
</TEXT>
