w1026 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Malaysia-AnwarTrial     12-22 0541
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Anwar Trial </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Defense alleges main prosecution witness a spurned lover
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos available
 &UR; By R. MAGESWARY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Lawyers defending Anwar Ibrahim on
Tuesday accused a main prosecution witness of acting in a jealous
rage because the former deputy prime minister spurned her
overtures.
	   ``I put it to you that you had confessed to a number of people
that you were crazy about Dato Seri Anwar Ibrahim,'' Christopher
Fernando, the lawyer, asked of Ummi Hafilda Ali.
	   The 31-year-old advertising executive, who claims Anwar had
sexual relations with her brother's wife, glowered as Fernando
persisted in this line of cross examination.
	   ``Did you write a few love letters to Dato Seri Anwar Ibrahim?''
he asked.
	   ``I think I can sue you for making such an allegation,'' Ummi
retorted, before denying the claim.
	   Ummi, a Malay woman who often poses for photographers outside
the courthouse in Western-style suits and designer handbags, sent a
letter to Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad last year that set off an
avalanche of events leading to Anwar's firing and arrest in
September.
	   Ummi alleged that Anwar, 51, was sleeping with the wife of her
brother, the then-deputy prime minister's former private secretary.
	   She also helped Azizan Ali Bakar, a driver in the Anwar
household, to come forward with allegations that he had been
repeatedly sodomized by the politician.
	   When the cross-examination delved further into Ummi's alleged
passion for Anwar, there were snickers and giggles from the public
gallery.
	   Trial judge Augustine Paul was not amused.
	   ``I think this line of questioning should be properly backed up,
otherwise it is highly scandalous,'' Paul said.
	   Fernando assured him there were solid grounds.
	   He then dove further by asking if she kept a picture of Anwar on
her pillow.
	   ``Have you been to my room?'' she snapped back from the witness
stand.
	   Fernando: ``Answer the question. I don't want to come to your
room.''
	   She denied having a photo of Anwar in her room.
	   During questioning, the defense also asked if Ummi's advertising
company, Karisma, was winning huge government contracts. She
admitted to getting large contracts and said she was negotiating
for the advertising account of the company that manages the Kuala
Lumpur International Airport.
	   Ummi had retracted all the allegations she made against Anwar
last year. But prosecutors say she was coerced to do so by police,
acting at the behest of the then-deputy prime minister.
	   On Monday, Ummi testified that her original allegations made in
the letter to Mahathir were true and that police had threatened to
send her to jail for two years if she didn't retract her claims
against Anwar.
	   Anwar has denied all the accusations against him, saying they
were cooked up to eliminate his challenge to Mahathir's
17-year-rule. The ousted politician, whose wife has formed a
political reform party on his behalf, claims a high-level
government conspiracy is out to ruin his career.
	   Anwar is now being tried on four counts of abuse of power.
Separate trials will be held for another count of corruption and
five of illegal sex. 	   
</TEXT>
