r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKorea-US-Samsung     12-22 0242
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKorea-US-Samsung </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Samsung sells part of non-memory chip operation to Fairchild
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ Samsung Electronics Co., the world's
largest memory chip maker, said Tuesday it has sold one-third of
its non-memory chip operations to a U.S. firm for dlrs 455 million.
	   The deal calls for Fairchild Semiconductor Co. to take over one
of Samsung's two non-memory chip plants in South Korea and its
1,500 workers as of Jan. 1, 1999. Located in Puchon west of Seoul,
the plant produces power devices, transistors and linear integrated
circuits.
	   The Puchon plant recorded net profit of 19.6 billion won (dlrs
15.3 million) on 420 billion won (dlrs 350 million) in total sales
in 1997.
	   Before the sale, non-memory chips accounted for 30 percent of
Samsung's total semiconductor operations.
	   Samsung said the deal is part of its restructuring efforts to
concentrate on more advanced chips for use in communications or
digital televisions.
	   Samsung Electronics, the flagship unit of the Samsung group,
South Korea's second largest conglomerate, produces semiconductors,
telecommunications products, home appliances and computer products.
	   A number of local companies have been selling off their assets
and units to foreign investors in a bid to streamline their
businesses and improve their financial positions.
	   Based in South Portland, Maine, Fairchild specializes in
non-memory chip production. 	   
</TEXT>
