<SLUG> BC-Balloon Quest, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
British embassy says balloon team told by Chinese to head south
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES thruout to CLARIFY that British embassy in Beijing
says balloonists will not be asked to leave airspace immediately
but must head south before official permission granted; ADDS
comments from balloon's support team in London; EDITS overline to
conform; no UPPICK &QL; 
 &UR; By EMMA ROSS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Three men hoping to be the first to circle the
world by balloon may still get their chance despite crossing into
Chinese air space without permission, prompting fears that their
adventure would be forced to come to an early end.
	   The British Embassy in Beijing said the Chinese are not
demanding the balloonists leave Chinese airspace immediately, but
want the crew ``to continue their efforts to reach the area south
of latitude 26,'' the official said, speaking with customary
anonymity.
	   The Chinese will only grant official flight permission as soon
as the balloon gets into the originally agreed upon flight corridor
_ below 26 degrees north latitude, the embassy official said.
	   Contacted separately, the Chinese Foreign Ministry, the
government information office and official sports associations
refused to comment. The balloon's support team in London said the
Chinese were ''being reasonable'' and every effort was being made
to comply with their demands.
	   Piloted by British tycoon Richard Branson, American Steve
Fossett and Sweden's Per Linstrand, the balloon crossed from Nepal
into Chinese-ruled Tibet late Monday.
	   China had given permission for the ICO Global balloon to travel
in its airspace south of 26 degrees north latitude. But because of
diversions around Mediterranean storms and Iraq, the balloon
crossed the Himalayas further north than planned and entered China
250 miles north of the agreed airspace corridor.
	   Project director Mike Kendrick said Chinese air traffic
controllers were informed the moment the balloon passed over the
border, with an apology added to the communication. The balloon
team continued to contact them every 15 minutes to keep the Chinese
informed about their position.
	   ''A balloon goes wherever the wind takes it,'' project manager
David Partridge said Tuesday. ''Unfortunately, it took us where we
weren't supposed to go. But we are basically using our best
endeavors to get further south.''
	   The British Embassy official said the Chinese recognize that the
balloon can't be turned around quickly.
	   In February, China withheld permission for a European balloon
team to fly through its airspace, ending their around-the-world
bid.
	   As it became apparent early Monday that the balloon would
inevitably cross into unauthorized Chinese territory, frantic
diplomatic negotiations were launched by the British government.
Prime Minister Tony Blair sent a message to Chinese Premier Zhu
Rongji asking for China's help, the British embassy official said.
	   The ICO Global balloon had already run into trouble on its trip.
Libya unexpectedly revoked permission to enter its airspace, but
the situation was resolved shortly before the three-man crew flew
over the country on Saturday.
	   Then, in conditions marred by thunderstorms, the crew had to
maneuver the 270-foot (82-meter) craft through narrow gaps between
no-fly territories, including war-torn Iraq.
	   On Monday night, the crew were flying through pitch darkness
over some of the world's highest peaks, where landing _ if China
demands it _ would be dangerous and difficult. Landing also would
mean an end to their bid.
	   The crew members estimate the trip could last from eight days to
nearly three weeks. They hope to touch down somewhere in western
Europe at the end of a 24,000-mile (38,000 kms) flight, which will
take them over India, the South China sea, the Pacific and the
United States.
	   The team secured permission from 97 countries for overflights
and initially had only four refusals _ Iran, Iraq, Russia and North
Korea.
	   (rb-em-mb) 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Balloon Quest, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
