<SLUG> BC-Sports-Ice Hockey-NHL Roundup, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0437 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hasek, Sabres down Hurricanes 4-1
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: CORRECTS Dallas record in Canadiens-Stars &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   GREENSBORO, North Carolina (AP) _ Jason Woolley had a goal and
two assists and Dominik Hasek made 19 saves to lead the Buffalo
Sabres to a 4-1 win over the Carolina Hurricanes on Monday night.
	   Miroslav Satan and Michael Peca also scored for the Sabres, who
won for the eighth time in their last 10 games.
	   Robert Kron scored for Carolina, which lost for only the second
time in its last eight home games. Trevor Kidd made 29 saves after
making 38 in the Hurricanes' 3-2 win at Buffalo on Saturday.
	   Buffalo improved to 14-0-0 when leading after two periods as
Hasek earned his league-best 17th win.
 &UR; Canadiens 2, Stars 2
	   In Montreal, Darryl Sydor's goal at 13:54 of the third period
lifted the Dallas Stars into a tie with Montreal as the Canadiens
equalled a 50-year-old team winless mark.
	   The Canadiens remained winless in December at 0-5-5 _ equalling
the club's 10-game winless streak from the 1947-48 season. The team
record is 12 games without a win set in 1926 and equalled in 1935.
	   Sydor beat Jeff Hackett for his ninth goal as the Stars _ first
overall in the NHL with a 19-5-6 record _ kept alive a nine-game
unbeaten streak.
	   Benoit Brunet and Patrick Poulin scored in the second for
Montreal (8-17-7) before Sergei Zubov responded with only 30
seconds left in the period.
 &UR; Bruins 3, Lightning 2
	   In Boston, Kyle McLaren scored twice and Hal Gill had the
tie-breaking goal with 8:31 left in the third period as the Boston
Bruins beat the Tampa Bay Lightning.
	   Boston improved to 8-1-2 at home against Tampa Bay.
	   Craig Janney and Vincent Lecavalier scored for the Lightning,
who have the league's worst record (8-21-3) and dropped their 15th
game in their last 18.
	   Rob Tallas, making his first start since Nov. 24 and only his
sixth this season for Boston, stopped 24 shots. Bill Ranford made
31 saves in the Tampa Bay net.
 &UR; Maple Leafs 7, Penguins 1
	   In Toronto, Mats Sundin scored two goals and Alyn McCauley had a
goal and two assists as the Toronto Maple Leafs beat the Pittsburgh
Penguins.
	   The Maple Leafs, who lead the NHL with 105 goals, have scored 14
in the last two games with McCauley collecting seven points during
that span.
	   Toronto goaltender Curtis Joseph made 30 saves as the Maple
Leafs were outshot 31-27.
	   Jason Smith, Derek King, Sergei Berezin and Mike Johnson also
scored for the Maple Leafs, who have won 10 of their last 11 home
games. Jan Hrdina scored for Pittsburgh.
</TEXT>
