w1047 &Cx1f; wstm-
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-India-PatentLaw     12-22 0273
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Patent Law,0273 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Congress proposes amendment to patents law
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ The main opposition Congress party
proposed an amendment Tuesday to a controversial patent bill,
striking a populist chord by suggesting an exemption for products
drawn from India's traditional system of medicine.
	   The proposal came at the orders of Congress leader Sonia Gandhi
during a meeting of the party's parliamentary members, United News
of India said. The amendment would ban exclusive sales or
distribution rights to any company marketing products ``based on
(the) Indian system of medicine already in the public domain.''
	   The Indian government led by the Bharatiya Janata Party
introduced the bill last week intended to provide exclusive
marketing rights to foreign agrochemical and pharmaceutical
companies selling their products here.
	   It was not immediately clear whether the BJP would accept
Congress' proposal. The governing party needs Congress support to
push through the bill.
	   Leftist parties vehemently opposed the bill, introduced by
Industry Minister Sikander Bakht, arguing working people will be
hurt because foreigners will destroy indigenous business.
Reformists say patent protections will make India a more attractive
place to do business for foreigners.
	   No date has been set for a debate or vote on the bill.
	   The bill proposes that India start giving patents in 2005, but
the World Trade Organization has asked New Delhi to provide a
mechanism to receive applications beginning next April.
	   The existing 1970 law catered for process patent, but did not
provide for product patent. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
