w1049 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SriLanka-Fighting     12-22 0231
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sri Lanka-Fighting,0230 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
At least 34 die in clashes in northeastern Sri Lanka
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) _ At least 34 people were killed in
clashes between government troops and guerrillas in northeastern
Sri Lanka in the heaviest fighting in three months, military
officials said Tuesday.
	   Troops killed at least 30 insurgents in an ambush near the
northern town of Oddusuddan on Monday, said military officials who
asked not to be named.
	   Oddusuddan, 270 kilometers (165 miles) north of the capital,
Colombo, was captured by government troops earlier this month.
	   Two other guerrillas were killed in a clash a few kilometers
(miles) to the west near the town of Kanakarayankulam on Monday,
the officials said.
	   One soldier was killed and eight wounded the same day when
rebels attacked a military convoy near Eravur town in eastern
Batticaloa district, the officials said.
	   A civilian died in another grenade attack Monday, this one on a
shop in the eastern Valaichchenai town.
	   It was the fiercest fighting since several big battles in
September killed more than 1,000 on both sides.
	   The guerrillas are fighting for a homeland in the northeast for
the country's minority ethnic Tamils, who say they are
discriminated by the majority Sinhalese who control the government
and military. More than 56,000 people have been killed in the war.
</TEXT>
