<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Riot </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Indonesian mobs attack soldier in provincial town
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Soldiers fired warning shots to
disperse a crowd that attacked an army officer in a northern
provincial town, a newspaper reported Tuesday. Six people,
including two soldiers, were injured.
	   The violence erupted Monday on the outskirts of Lhokseumawe in
Aceh province, where the military has been accused of human rights
abuses during a campaign against separatist rebels.
	   The armed forces recently ended the campaign and apologized for
any wrongdoing, but resentment among Acehnese toward Indonesia's
security forces still runs deep.
	   The daily Kompas newspaper said mobs tried to seize an army
sergeant suspected of harassing a woman who was heading to a mosque
on Monday for evening prayers.
	   Mobs also smashed an army vehicle and injured the driver, an
army major, as well as his wife and son.
	   Lhokseumawe is an oil and gas center that lies 2,100 kilometers
(1,300 miles) northwest of Jakarta, the Indonesian capital. The
city was hit by riots in August that were triggered by resentment
toward the military. 	   
</TEXT>
