w1079 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Japan-SpySatellites     12-22 0277
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Spy Satellites </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cabinet approves plans to launch spy satellites
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japan's Cabinet officially approved a plan Tuesday
to launch four surveillance satellites by 2002 in an apparent move
to monitor North Korea's weapons program.
	   Proposals for Japan to build a multipurpose spy satellite have
gained momentum since the firing in August of a North Korean
rocket.
	   Defense Agency chief Hosei Norota told a Cabinet meeting Tuesday
that the introduction of a surveillance satellite would be ``very
significant'' by giving Japan its own information-gathering
capability, according to news media.
	   Japan relied on information from the U.S. military to monitor
the Aug. 31 firing of the rocket, which flew over Japan before
landing in the Pacific Ocean.
	   Last week, a Russian news report cited Russian Defense Ministry
officials as saying that North Korea is planning another test.
	   The United States says North Korea has also begun construction
of a suspected underground nuclear-related facility at Keumjang-ri,
40 kilometers (25 miles) northeast of the North's main nuclear
complex of Yongbyon.
	   The reclusive communist states says the new facility is for
civilian use and refuses a U.S. demand that it allow unconditional
inspection there.
	   On Monday, the Finance Ministry approved a total of 8.2 billion
yen (dlrs 74.14 million) in research spending on the surveillance
satellite project for next fiscal year, which begins April 1.
	   The sum will include 6.8 billion yen (dlrs 58.6 million) for
technology studies by the Science and Technology Agency, said
agency official Masaaki Nishijo.
 &UR; (km)
</TEXT>
