w1080 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Indonesia-SuhartoRela     12-22 0295
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Suharto Relative </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indonesia investigates whether Suharto relative sought Jordanian
</HEADLINE>
citizenship

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) - The government said Tuesday it was
investigating a report that a son-in-law of former President
Suharto had sought citizenship in Jordan.
	   Several months ago, military investigators said they might
court-martial former Lt. Gen. Prabowo Subianto for his alleged role
in the abduction of nine political activists.
	   Prabowo was commander of Indonesia's special forces when the
pro-democracy activists were kidnapped and tortured earlier this
year. He lost his job after the ouster in May of his authoritarian
father-in-law, who was dislodged by riots and protests.
	   Justice Minister Muladi said the government was checking whether
Jordan had offered citizenship to Prabowo, who is viewed as a
villain by many Indonesians.
	   The daily newspaper Kompas reported Tuesday that Jordan had
granted citizenship to Prabowo, a onetime rising star in the
Indonesian military whose career plummeted when Suharto's fortunes
turned.
	   ``The government will have to prevent him from going abroad
because he still has a case to be resolved,'' Muladi said.
	   However, he could not confirm that Prabowo was in Indonesia.
	   An employee at the Jordanian embassy in Jakarta said no one was
available to comment.
	   Suharto's successor and former protege, President B.J. Habibie,
is implementing political reforms and the military has pledged to
clean up its human rights record. Student protesters say the
government is not moving fast enough on democratic change.
	   A military court was scheduled on Wednesday to begin the trial
of 11 members of the special forces who have been accused in the
kidnappings of the activists. 	   
</TEXT>
