r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Olympics-Homeb     12-22 0230
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Olympics-Homebush Lease </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Company paid millions to move from Olympic site
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ A private company was paid 37.9 million
Australian dollars (23 million US dlrs) of taxpayers' money to
relocate from the Olympics site at Homebush Bay, a report said
Tuesday
	   The New South Wales state Auditor-General's annual report said
that the payout came after Ian Armstrong, then state agriculture
minister and now the opposition Olympics spokesman in the
government, extended the company's lease against legal advice in
1989.
	   Auditor-General Tony Harris said Armstrong had approved the
extension by 21 years of a 10-year lease for food processing
company P and S Smallgoods. The lease had originally been due to
expire in September 1995.
	   He said Homebush Bay had been recommended to the government as
the site for the mooted bid for the 1996 Olympic Games in June
1989, the month before Armstrong approved the lease extension on
July 28. Sydney won the right to host the 2000 Games in 1993.
	   Four months before the compensation was agreed to, the Olympic
Coordination Authority (OCA) had four options for dealing with the
site, including building around the site at a cost of up to 10
million Australian dollars (6.2 million US dlrs) and with
substantial disruption to construction and the operation of the
Olympics. (djp) 	   
</TEXT>
