<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Jordan-Iraq </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Evacuated U.N. humanitarian workers head back to Baghdad
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo available
 &UR; By ALIA SHUKRI HAMZEH &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) _ About 120 U.N. humanitarian workers,
evacuated from Iraq last week during U.S.-British air attacks, left
Amman on Monday to return to the Iraqi capital Baghdad.
	   Before departing, many in the group were smiling and taking
photos of each other in front of the buses that will take them on
the more than 12-hour journey across the desert.
	   ``We are very happy to be going back to take up our work in
Iraq,'' Darleen Biseau said as she boarded one of the three buses
making the journey, along with eight four-wheel-drive cars.
	   The U.N. workers had left the Iraqi capital on the second day of
the airstrikes on Iraq.
	   Biseau, who works on the U.N.-approved oil for food program in
Baghdad, had described her trip to Amman on arrival Saturday as a
journey the U.N. workers made with tears for the people they left
behind. She said the bombardment would add to the suffering of
Iraqis.
	   She said she was ``hoping for the best'' in returning.
	   Abdullah Odeh, resident representative in Amman for the U.N.
Development Program, said all the agency personnel who left Baghdad
except those on holiday leaves were returning to ``pick up the
pieces'' of their work.
	   ``They will continue the mission they are there for, which is
the full humanitarian mission,'' he added.
	   The oil-for-food program is an exception to punishing trade
sanctions imposed by the U.N. Security Council after Iraq's 1990
invasion of Kuwait. It allows Iraq to sell limited quantities of
oil to buy needed food and medicine for its 22 million people.
	   Most of the U.N. workers departing Amman refused to talk to
reporters.
	   The workers were evacuated after spending the first night of the
airstrikes last Thursday huddled in their headquarters on the
outskirts of Baghdad.
	   Those who had remained in Baghdad were special U.N. envoy
Prakash Shah, U.N. humanitarian coordinator Hans von Sponeck, and
26 other U.N. workers.
 &UR; ash-jah-ggl
</TEXT>
