<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Protest </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
65 hospital workers in Russian Far East start hunger strike
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ More than 60 workers at a hospital in Russia's Far
East went on a hunger strike Tuesday to demand months of back pay,
a news report said.
	   The 64 hospital employees in the remote village of Plastun have
not been paid in nine months, but will continue to treat patients
under their care, according to the ITAR-Tass news agency.
	   The report gave no other details about the strike.
	   Plastun is located about 6,600 kilometers (4,100 miles) east of
Moscow on Russia's Pacific coastline.
	   Millions of workers receive their salaries months late in
Russia, part of a cycle of non-payments that plagues the Russian
economy.
	   But the situation is particularly bad in the country's far flung
regions, where impoverished local governments are much more
dependent on dwindling federal subsidies.
	   (nw/ren)
</TEXT>
