<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Anwar Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Defense alleges star prosecution witness a spurned lover
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with prosecution accusing witness of taking bribes
from politicians to smear Anwar; ADDS photo numbers.
 &UR; AP Photos KL101-105
 &UR; By R. MAGESWARY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Lawyers defending Anwar Ibrahim on
Tuesday accused the prosecution's star witness of taking bribes and
acting in a jealous rage because the former deputy prime minister
spurned her overtures.
	   ``I put it to you that you had confessed to a number of people
that you were crazy about Dato Seri Anwar Ibrahim,'' Christopher
Fernando, the lawyer, asked of Ummi Hafilda Ali.
	   The 31-year-old advertising executive, who claims Anwar had
sexual relations with her brother's wife, glowered as Fernando
persisted in this line of cross examination.
	   ``Did you write a few love letters to Dato Seri Anwar Ibrahim?''
he asked.
	   ``I think I can sue you for making such an allegation,'' Ummi
retorted, before denying the claim.
	   Ummi sent a letter to Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad last year
that set off an avalanche of events leading to Anwar's firing and
arrest in September.
	   Ummi alleged that Anwar, 51, was sleeping with her
sister-in-law. Anwar's lawyer alleged Ummi was just jealous.
	   She also helped a driver in the Anwar household, to come forward
with allegations that he had been repeatedly sodomized by the
politician.
	   Fernando accused her of taking money from politicians opposed to
Anwar in return for making false allegations.
	   ``I put it to you that you were the one who cheated the nation
for money,'' Fernando told Ummi. ``You have sold your soul.''
	   She denied the allegation, but admitted to giving copies of her
letter to Mahathir to two senior Cabinet ministers.
	   The defense also asked if Ummi's advertising company, Karisma,
was winning huge government contracts. She admitted to getting
large contracts and said she was negotiating for the advertising
account of the company that manages the Kuala Lumpur International
Airport.
	   Anwar has said he was a victim of a political conspiracy. He is
now being tried for four counts of corruption and a separate trial
for another corruption charge and five illegal sex acts charges
will follow.
	   When the cross-examination delved further into Ummi's alleged
passion for Anwar, there were snickers and giggles from the public
gallery, though trial judge Augustine Paul was not amused.
	   ``I think this line of questioning should be properly backed up,
otherwise it is highly scandalous,'' Paul said.
	   But when the chief prosecutor later objected, the judge allowed
Fernando's questions.
	   Fernando dove further by asking if she kept a picture of Anwar
on her pillow.
	   She denied having a photo of Anwar in her room but admitted to
carrying a picture of Anwar, herself and her sister-in-law in her
purse.
	   Ummi had retracted all the allegations she made against Anwar
last year.
	   But on Monday, she testified that her original allegations were
true and that police had threatened to send her to jail for two
years if she didn't retract them. Prosecutors say the police had
acted at the behest of Anwar.
	   Her cross-examination resumes Wednesday. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Malaysia-Anwar Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
