w1112 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BalloonQuest 2ndLd   12-22 0678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Balloon Quest, 2nd Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
China tells balloon team to head south
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS lead; UPDATES thruout with new information from
Chinese Foreign Ministry; EDITS overline to conform; No UPPICK &QL; 
 &UR; By EMMA ROSS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Three men hoping to be the first to circle the
world by balloon were still aloft Tuesday despite crossing into
Chinese air space without permission, which initially prompted
fears that their adventure would be forced to come to an early end.
	   The Chinese Foreign Ministry expressed regret that the
balloonists did not abide by an earlier agreement to fly over
southernmost China below 26 degrees north latitude. But while
Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao said Tuesday that China
could not agree to the balloon's current course, he did not call on
the three-man crew to withdraw immediately or land.
	   ''China is very regretful,'' Zhu said at a routine media
briefing. ''China will not take responsibility for the
consequences.''
	   The balloon's support team in London said they were making every
effort to comply with China's demands and fly south, but were being
hampered by slow winds.
	   Piloted by British tycoon Richard Branson, American Steve
Fossett and Sweden's Per Linstrand, the balloon crossed from Nepal
into Chinese-ruled Tibet late Monday.
	   Beijing had given permission for the ICO Global balloon to
travel only over southernmost China. It would have effectively kept
the balloonists away from the isolated Tibetan plateau, where
rescue would be difficult, and out of busy air traffic corridors
monitored by a spotty air traffic control system.
	   But because of diversions around Mediterranean storms and Iraq,
the balloon crossed the Himalayas further north than planned and
entered China 250 miles (400 kms) north of the agreed airspace
corridor.
	   Project director Mike Kendrick said Chinese air traffic
controllers were informed the moment the balloon passed over the
border, with an apology added to the communication. The balloon
team continued to contact them every 15 minutes to keep the Chinese
informed about their position.
	   ``A balloon goes wherever the wind takes it,'' project manager
David Partridge said Tuesday. ``Unfortunately, it took us where we
weren't supposed to go. But we are basically using our best
endeavors to get further south.''
	   An official at the British Embassy, speaking with customary
anonymity, said the Chinese recognize that the balloon can't be
turned around quickly.
	   In February, China withheld permission for a European balloon
team to fly through its airspace, forcing them to land and end
their around-the-world bid.
	   As it became apparent early Monday that the balloon would
inevitably cross into unauthorized Chinese territory, frantic
diplomatic negotiations were launched by the British government.
Prime Minister Tony Blair sent a message to Chinese Premier Zhu
Rongji asking for China's help, the British embassy official said.
	   The ICO Global balloon had already run into trouble on its trip.
Libya unexpectedly revoked permission to enter its airspace, but
the situation was resolved shortly before the three-man crew flew
over the country on Saturday.
	   Then, in conditions marred by thunderstorms, the crew had to
maneuver the 270-foot (82-meter) craft through narrow gaps between
no-fly territories, including war-torn Iraq.
	   On Monday night, the crew were flying through some of the
world's highest peaks, where landing _ if China demands it _ would
be dangerous and difficult. Landing also would mean an end to their
bid.
	   The crew members estimate the trip could last from eight days to
nearly three weeks. They hope to touch down somewhere in western
Europe at the end of a 24,000-mile (38,000 kms) flight, which will
take them over India, the South China sea, the Pacific and the
United States.
	   The team secured permission from 97 countries for overflights
and initially had only four refusals _ Iran, Iraq, Russia and North
Korea.
	   (rb-em-mb)
</TEXT>
