<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-East Timor </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. diplomat meets Indonesian president on East Timor
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ President B.J. Habibie on Tuesday
thanked a United Nations envoy for his efforts to end the bitter
conflict in Indonesian-controlled East Timor.
	   U.N. diplomat Jamsheed Marker spent more than an hour with
Habibie, who has adopted a more conciliatory approach on East Timor
than his authoritarian predecessor, Suharto.
	   Peace talks on the former Portuguese colony have gained momentum
since Suharto quit in May amid riots and protests against his
32-year rule. In 1975, Suharto ordered an invasion of East Timor
and annexed the territory a year later.
	   Habibie has offered autonomy in exchange for international
recognition of Indonesian sovereignty, but East Timorese
separatists say an autonomy deal should be transitional prior to a
vote on independence.
	   A new round of U.N.-sponsored talks between Indonesia and
Portugal is scheduled next month in New York. The United Nations
considers Portugal to be the administering power in East Timor.
	   ``President Habibie expressed his gratitude to the efforts made
by the United Nations to resolve the East Timorese problem,''
Marker said after the meeting.
	   ``I have been certainly encouraged by his understanding of the
problems and the difficulties,'' said Marker, who met pro- and
anti-independence leaders in East Timor this past weekend.
	   ``We are progressing although it is not an easy matter,'' said
Marker. He was scheduled to leave Indonesia on Wednesday.
	   Foreign Minister Ali Alatas met separately with Marker and then
accompanied him to the meeting with Habibie at the state palace. He
said Indonesia would push for a negotiated solution.
	   ``Indonesia will continue as it is committed to proceed with the
process of negotiations under the auspices of the U.N.
Secretary-General,'' Alatas said.
	   After several months of relative calm, sporadic fighting between
separatist guerrillas has resumed and recent separatist rallies
have raised fears of confrontations with Indonesian soldiers.
	   On Sunday, protesters tore down a fence at the commercial
airport in the East Timorese capital of Dili and pushed past
soldiers as they tried in vain to speak to Marker as he left. 	   
</TEXT>
