</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-The Euro-Primer,0436 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Europe's new central bank meant creation of new institutions
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With FEA-The Euro-Banker &QL; 
 &UR; By DIDI KIRSTEN TATLOW &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) _ The launch of the European Union's
single currency has required new institutions to manage the
historic project.
	   The European Central Bank will set monetary policy for the 11
nations taking part in the euro starting Jan. 1. It is housed in a
silver skyscraper in the heart of Frankfurt, Germany's traditional
banking capital.
	   The bank's key aim is to maintain price stability, a mandate
written into the 1992 Maastricht Treaty, which provided the
blueprint for the single currency.
	   The treaty also guaranteed the ECB independence, and it is
widely expected to guard it fiercely. The bank, with a staff of
520, will work to support the economic policies of EU nations but
not at the expense of price stability.
	   The European Central Bank is the core of a group of European
central banks behind the economic and monetary union, called the
European System of Central Banks.
	   Central banks of all 15 EU members are in the system, including
the four initially not participating in the euro launch: Britain,
Denmark, Greece and Sweden.
	   Chiefs of the national banks from each of the 11 euro countries
will travel to Frankfurt twice a month to debate and decide common
policies. National central banks will not be scrapped _ they simply
lose independent policy-making power.
	   The European Central Bank has a 17-member governing council,
composed of the 11 national banks' chiefs plus a six-member
executive board. Wim Duisenberg, a former Dutch central banker, is
president of both; his deputy is Christian Noyer of France.
	   Duisenberg, Noyer and four other banking or finance
professionals nominated by their governments sit on the executive
board, which carries out day-to-day management.
	   The ECB will set interest rates in the euro zone, define and
implement monetary policy, conduct foreign exchange operations and
manage the official foreign reserves of member nations.
	   The national central banks will transfer part of their reserves
to the ECB on Jan. 1. The ECB's total reserves will amount to 50
billion euros, or close to dlrs 60 billion. Although the euro rate
will not be set until Dec. 31, one euro is expected to be about
dlrs 1.17.
	   The ECB also has a general council, which will allow the four
central bankers from the EU countries not joining the euro to
discuss decisions that will affect their economies. It will be
dissolved once all EU nations join the euro. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-FEA-The Euro-Primer; CT:i; 
