<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japanese stocks plunge, driving up dollar against yen
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS; UPDATES with closing bond, late afternoon currency
prices; ADDS analyst comment in 8th graf
 &UR; By MARTIN FACKLER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japanese stocks plunged Tuesday amid concern about
damage to bank earnings from tumbling bond prices. The rout spilled
over into the currency market, driving the yen lower against the
U.S. dollar.
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average dropped 373.50
points, or 2.64 percent, to close at 13,779.45 _ its lowest close
since Oct. 30. On Monday, the average closed down 41.34 points, or
0.29 percent.
	   The dollar bought 117.08 yen in late afternoon trading in Tokyo,
up 2.18 yen from late Monday here and above its late New York level
of 116.21 yen.
	   Price movements in all markets were exaggerated by the
relatively small number of participants during the holiday season,
forcing sellers to slash prices to find buyers.
	   ``Amid a thin trade the market is very volatile,'' said Yasuo
Ueki, a general manager at Nikko Securities Co.
	   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, volume was a moderate 362 million
shares, up from 246 million Monday. Declining shares outnumbered
risers almost three to one.
	   Share prices fell as declines in the bond market were seen
hurting one of the few profitable operations at Japan's ailing
banks: their bond trading business.
	   ``The bond market's sharp fall was the major negative factor in
the stock market,'' said Keiko Kondo, an analyst at Merrill Lynch
Japan.
	   That drove the broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues
listed on the first section down 16.66 points, or 1.52 percent, to
1,082.46. The TOPIX closed up 2.58 points, or 0.23 percent, on
Monday.
	   The price of the most widely watched bond in Japan, the No. 203
10-year Japanese government bond, tumbled to 99.19 yen from
Monday's close of 102.44. That drove up the yield _ which moves in
the opposite direction of the price _ to 1.900 percent from 1.505
percent.
	   Yields are up from historical lows of 0.695 percent just two
months ago.
	   Investors are worried that new bond issues by the Japanese
government to pay for fiscal stimulus spending will cause a glut in
the market, traders said.
	   Prices also took a tumble after Japan's finance minister said
the ministry's trust bureau, one of the biggest market
participants, will cease its monthly purchases in January.
	   Meanwhile, the dollar recovered recent losses against the yen as
currency market participants followed the stock and bond markets'
lead in selling Japanese assets.
	   The dollar started trading as low as 115.67 yen but skyrocketed
to a high for the day of 117.45 yen as falling stock prices spooked
traders into dumping yen.
	   The triple decline by stocks, bonds and the yen ``shows the
worst tendency of Japanese investors,'' said Ryohei Muramatsu,
chief foreign exchange manager at Commerzbank in Tokyo.
	   ``When they buy, they all buy together, and when they sell, they
all sell together. That's all there is to it,'' he said. 	   
</TEXT>
