<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Buddha Statue,0190 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
New York museum to return Buddha statue missing from India
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ A 600-year-old Buddha statue that
disappeared 10 years ago from an Indian religious retreat will be
returned by a New York museum that bought the antique, a domestic
news agency reported Tuesday.
	   Authorities at the Metropolitan Museum of Art agreed to return
the statue, which they bought for dlrs 50,000 eight years ago,
Press Trust of India news agency reported quoting R.V.V. Ayyar, the
top official of the Indian government's Culture Ministry.
	   Ayyar met with the museum officials recently following a tip
that the statue from a retreat in Bodhgaya had ended up in New
York. Bodhgaya, where the faithful believe Buddha achieved
enlightenment, is a major Buddhist pilgrimage town 900 kilometers
(560 miles) southeast of New Delhi.
	   The museum agreed to hand over the statue for free to Indian
embassy officials, Ayyar said.
	   The statue will be kept at the National Museum in New Delhi
until police solve the case, he said. Ayyar said it was unclear how
the statue disappeared from the retreat. 	   
</TEXT>
