w1134 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Israel-Politics 1stLd-Writethru   12-22 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Politics, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Netanyahu ridicules rivals, demands Palestinian guarantees
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with fresh Netanyahu, Palestinian
comment, reorganizes and TRIMS. &QL; 
 &UR; By RON KAMPEAS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu opened his
re-election campaign Tuesday by deriding the ``fantasies and
ambitions'' of his political rivals and insisting that the public
will back his tough stance toward the Palestinians.
	   ``We will go to the people and the people will give us the
support to achieve peace with security,'' the prime minister told
Israel radio a day after Israel's parliament voted overwhelmingly
for early elections and rejected Netanyahu's policies toward the
Palestinians.
	   The collapse of the prime minister's governing coalition and the
outset of what is likely to be a nearly 4-month-long election
campaign appeared to put the already ailing Mideast peace process
on hold.
	   That is drawing bitter protest from the Palestinians, who call
the political turmoil an internal Israeli affair and insist Israel
is still bound to the Wye River accord, just as it is to other
pre-existing international agreements.
	   ``It's really unfortunate that the only thing that Mr. Netanyahu
has decided to stop is the peace process with us,'' said chief
Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat told the AP on Tuesday. ``I
think this is a very grave development.''
	   The elections are likely to take place by the end of April. In
addition to Netanyahu and Labor Party leader Ehud Barak, a
half-dozen other figures have indicated they will jump into what is
shaping as a wild political free-for-all.
	   Netanyahu brushed aside polls suggesting he would lose by a slim
margin to Barak and by a considerably wider margin to former army
chief of staff Amnon Lipkin-Shahak, who has indicated his intention
to form a centrist party.
	   ``The fantasies and ambitions of all those who want to be prime
minister _ please. We will allow the voters to decide who needs to
lead the state,'' Netanyahu said in the radio interview. He
predicted he would draw ``utmost, massive'' support from voters
affiliated with his conservative Likud party.
	   Others likely to declare their candidacy include hard-liners
such as Benjamin Begin, the son of the late Prime Minister Menachem
Begin, and Limor Livnat, Netanyahu's communications minister.
Livnat's rumored candidacy has troubled ultra-Orthodox legislators
who question a woman's fitness for leadership.
	   The early elections bill given preliminary approval by lawmakers
on Monday must pass two more parliamentary readings, but Netanyahu
has said he will not try to block its final passage.
	   The unraveling of Netanyahu's coalition began with the signing
of the U.S.-brokered Wye River peace accord two months ago. The
pact's land-for-security provisions infuriated hard-liners who made
up a small but powerful faction in Netanyahu's government.
	   The opposition Labor party promised Netanyahu support as long as
he stuck to the agreement, but that fell apart when he scrapped a
scheduled troop withdrawal from 5 percent of the West Bank after a
wave of anti-Israel violence last month.
	   Netanyahu's conditions to the Palestinians for resuming Israeli
compliance with the Wye accord, presented to lawmakers on Monday,
included: a renunciation of claims to statehood and Jerusalem; a
confiscation of arms; an end to violence and incitement to
violence; and a renunciation of claims that Netanyahu had agreed to
release Palestinians jailed for killings.
	   The prime minister, who remains in his job until the new voting,
repeated accusations Tuesday that the Palestinians are violating
the accord.
	   ``We won't give territory to the Palestinians when they say they
will simply take that territory and will continue the violations
and will decide unilaterally on our future,'' he told Israel radio.
	   Palestinian leaders called on the Israeli public and the Clinton
administration to reject Netanyahu's latest demands and pressure
him to move ahead with the promised handover of West Bank
territory.
 &UR; (lk)
</TEXT>
