w1140 &Cx1f; wstm-
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Philippines-Economy     12-22 0382
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Economy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Government upbeat about 1999 economic prospects
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ The Philippines' chief economic
planner on Tuesday expressed optimism the country will post higher
economic growth in 1999 after suffering a slowdown caused by the
Asian financial crisis and a severe drought this year.
	   Next year will be a ``period of further consolidation and
recovery,'' Socio-Economic Planning Secretary Felipe Medalla told
reporters at a year-end briefing.
	   The government projects the gross national product to grow
between 0.5 percent and 1.0 percent and gross domestic product to
grow 1.0 percent in 1998, Medalla said.
	   GNP measures a country's total output while GDP excludes the net
factor income from abroad.
	   For 1999, the government targets a GNP growth of 3.0 percent to
3.5 percent while GDP is projected to grow by 2.6 percent to 3.1
percent, Medalla said.
	   Medalla said a resilient service sector and continued consumer
market demand allowed the Philippines to escape a recession in 1998
and elude the various economic problems suffered by its neighbors
due to the regional financial crisis.
	   The probability of recovery in 1999 will be stronger as the
government generates additional foreign financing, including money
from Japan's ``Miyazawa Fund,'' for its deficit of 68.4 billion
pesos (dlrs 1.72 billion), Medalla said.
	   Medalla noted that escaping a recession and implementing crucial
structural reforms will allow the country to speed economic growth.
	   Inflation is expected to ease to between 8 percent and 9 percent
as agricultural production improves and the exchange rate becomes
more stable, he added.
	   Medalla said the government has allotted about 21.4 billion
pesos (dlrs 538.4 million) in new spending to stimulate economic
growth.
	   New revenue measures are expected to help finance the
government's budget next year. These include a road user's tax, a
land user's tax and a motor vehicle's tax.
	   Medalla said the labor front remained ``relatively calm''
throughout 1998 despite a rise in unemployment, while other
countries like Indonesia and South Korea grappled with unrest.
	   The unemployment rate rose to 9.6 percent in October 1998
compared with 7.9 percent for the same month last year. 	   
</TEXT>
