<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Lebanon-Israeli </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Israeli warplanes raid suspected guerrilla bases in south Lebanon
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MARJAYOUN, Lebanon (AP) - Israeli warplanes fired rockets on
suspected guerrillas bases facing Israel's occupation zone in south
Lebanon on Tuesday, Lebanese security officials said.
	   The attack targeted the wooded hills near Maidoun in the western
Bekaa Valley, three kilometers (two miles) northeast of the
occupied enclave, the officials said, speaking on customary
condition of anonymity.
	   Two Israeli jets fired four rockets at 9:30 a.m. (0730gmt) on
the area where guerrillas of the Iranian-backed Hezbollah
guerrillas are active, they said.
	   The air attack came after the guerrillas exchanged fire with
Israeli troops and their allies of the South Lebanon Army militia,
the officials added.
	   An Israeli army spokesman in Jerusalem said the Israeli pilots
scored direct hit and returned safely to their base.
	   No casualties or damage were reported from the air attack or the
ground fighting.
	   Hezbollah, or the Party of God, is trying to oust Israeli troops
and their militia allies from the so-called security zone that
Israel established in 1985 to protect its northern towns against
guerrilla attacks.
 &UR; jp-ggl
</TEXT>
