</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-South Africa-AIDS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAfrica: Teachers, pupils with HIV must be allowed in school
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) _ Students and teachers infected
with the AIDS virus must be allowed to attend school and keep their
jobs, an education department spokesman said on Tuesday.
	   Though South Africa's constitution already defends such rights,
the government has recently drawn up policy protecting the 3
million South Africans with the HIV virus or AIDS from being
discriminated against in education.
	   ``This is a national policy to protect the rights of individuals
with AIDS,'' Bheki Khumalo said.
	   South Africa's AIDS epidemic is one of the fastest growing in
Africa, and every day 1,500 South Africans are infected. Sufferers
often become outcasts in society and lose their jobs.
	   The policy document concludes there is an ``insignificant risk''
of spreading the disease in schools and universities. It also
prohibits mandatory testing for pupils and teachers and AIDS
sufferers cannot be forced to disclose they have the virus.
	   ``Learners and students with HIV/AIDS should lead as full a life
as possible and should not be denied the opportunity to receive an
education,'' it said.
	   Where students are too ill to travel to classes, they should be
allowed to study at home, the document recommends.
	   (ph/djw)	   
</TEXT>
