<SLUG> BC-Greece-Kids-Help,0360 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Volunteer school helps street kids
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With Greece-Traffic Light Kids, Bjt &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   ATHENS, Greece (AP) _ Nikos sits in a corner, learning to keep a
steady hand while forming letters of the Greek alphabet.
	   The 9-year-old boy has a short attention span, struggling with
skills that he should have learned in school. He soon moves off to
play.
	   Nikos is one of dozens of ``traffic light kids'' the teaching
center is trying to help. The volunteers running the center are
trying to reach out, gently, to children targeted in an official
roundup that might separate them forcibly from their families.
	   Police are gathering street children in an effort to curb child
exploitation and begging. Critics fear the operation could tear
apart families of illegal immigrants by placing some children in
orphanages or with foster parents.
	   Inside the learning center, children speak a jumble of
languages: Greek, Turkish and Albanian and Gypsy dialects. They
talk about everything except what they do for a living: begging or
selling trinkets at traffic lights.
	   It all goes on in one small room, two flights up from a
garbage-strewn street surrounded by brothels. Domestic quarrels can
frequently be heard from nearby apartments.
	   ``I like it here. That's why I come,'' says Dimluko, a
16-year-old boy with intense eyes and greasy hair parted down the
middle.
	   Children like Dimluko and Nikos visit the center between morning
and night ``shifts'' of work to help their families.
	   The center opens at 11 a.m. It's busiest on rainy days when the
trade at traffic lights is slow.
	   The center has enrolled 87 children in elementary schools this
year and helps families qualify for government benefits instead of
sending their children out to work on the streets.
	   ``We try to teach them the basics of reading and writing and
some arithmetic, so they can read a street sign or understand
something written,'' says Evanthia Constanopoulou, a volunteer at
the center.
	   ``But they are still kids,'' she said. ``We try and help them
find their identity as children _ to draw, to write to play _ to
feel like kids.''
</TEXT>
