<SLUG> BC-Asia Business Briefs </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Philippines. Some of these stories also moved earlier today as
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Contains items from Japan, Singapore, South Korea,
separates.

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japan's top economic official said Tuesday his
country would no longer rely on exports to pull itself out of
recession and was moving quickly with internal reforms, such as
cutting taxes and red tape.
	   Speaking along with Japan's prime minister before a group of
business leaders, Taiichi Sakaiya, said Japan must follow the
example of the robust U.S. economy, which he said is reaping the
benefits from a shrinking of government in the 1980s.
	   ``In that same America where they used to have such big
deficits, they're now debating what to do with their (budget)
surpluses,'' he said. Sakaiya heads the Economic Planning Agency.
	   A necessary step is curtailing government involvement in the
economy, which Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi said would lead to
opportunities for creating new industries.
	   ``Entrepreneurship is the basis of economic growth,'' Obuchi
said.
	   Sakaiya said that since taking power in August, Obuchi had also
taken a page from former President Ronald Reagan's economic
policies and sliced the top income bracket to 50 from 65 percent.
He also cut corporate taxes to levels similar to the United States.
	   Combined with massive spending on public works, Sakaiya
predicted the changes would be enough to restore Japan's gross
domestic product to a growth rate of about 0.5 percent next year,
up from this year's contraction of 2.2 percent.
	   ``I have a lot of confidence that growth will become positive,''
he said.
	   ___
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Top real estate companies have pleaded with the
government to boost the sagging property market through a curb on
land sales and new housing loan regulations, a newspaper reported
Tuesday.
	   The five largest real estate firms _ CB Richard Ellis, Colliers
Jardine, Edmund Tie and Co., Jones Lang Wootton and Knight Frank _
recently presented a joint report on Singapore's ailing property
sector to the National Development minister, The Business Times
reported.
	   The companies argued that property prices, which have tumbled by
as much as 40 percent since peaking in 1996, might fall further
unless the government acts to limit the supply of land for new
residential development, according to the report.
	   The companies' key proposal was for the ministry to extend the
current freeze on government land sales to 2002, until the
estimated 30,000 existing private residential units _ comprising
unsold homes and units in imminent projects _ is depleted.
	   The property companies predict sluggish sales of about 6,000
units per year in the medium term, meaning the current supply will
not be fully absorbed until 2003.
	   They recommended annual reviews of land sales after 2002 based
on consultations between industry participants and the government,
and urged the authorities to buy back some previously-sold sites at
current market prices, the daily reported.
	   The real estate firms also requested the government lower the
minimum 20 percent down payment required of home buyers, allow
banks greater flexibility in granting housing loans, and reduce
stamp duties.
	   The newspaper did not say whether or how the government
responded to the various proposals.
	   ___
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ Samsung Electronics Co., the world's
largest memory chip maker, said Tuesday it has sold one-third of
its non-memory chip operations to a U.S. firm for dlrs 455 million.
	   The deal calls for Fairchild Semiconductor Co. to take over one
of Samsung's two non-memory chip plants in South Korea and its
1,500 workers as of Jan. 1, 1999. Located in Puchon west of Seoul,
the plant produces power devices, transistors and linear integrated
circuits.
	   The Puchon plant recorded net profit of 19.6 billion won (dlrs
15.3 million) on 420 billion won (dlrs 350 million) in total sales
in 1997.
	   Before the sale, non-memory chips accounted for 30 percent of
Samsung's total semiconductor operations.
	   Samsung said the deal is part of its restructuring efforts to
concentrate on more advanced chips for use in communications or
digital televisions.
	   Samsung Electronics, the flagship unit of the Samsung group,
South Korea's second largest conglomerate, produces semiconductors,
telecommunications products, home appliances and computer products.
	   A number of local companies have been selling off their assets
and units to foreign investors in a bid to streamline their
businesses and improve their financial positions.
	   Based in South Portland, Maine, Fairchild specializes in
non-memory chip production.
	   ___
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Moody's Investors Services on Tuesday said it is
reviewing its rating of Japanese automaker Mazda Motor Corp.'s
creditworthiness for a possible downgrade.
	   The New York-based credit rating agency cited the ``the weakened
auto market and the banking system in Japan'' as its reason for
reviewing Mazda's Baa3 senior unsecured long-term debt rating. A
cut would put Mazda's debt in so-called junk bond category.
	   Moody's said it will investigate Mazda's ability to shore up its
finances amid slumping domestic auto demand and heightened
competition among rivals to launch new products.
	   The agency also said it will consider the effectiveness of
Mazda's current restructuring drive and its efforts to improve its
overseas operations and financial performance.
	   Moody's announcement sent Mazda shares 1.4 percent lower to 424
yen (dlrs 3.60) on the Tokyo Stock Exchange.
	   Hiroshima-based Mazda is 33.4 percent-owned by America's Ford
Motor Co.
	   ___
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ The Philippines' chief economic
planner on Tuesday expressed optimism the country will post higher
economic growth in 1999 after suffering a slowdown caused by the
Asian financial crisis and a severe drought this year.
	   Next year will be a ``period of further consolidation and
recovery,'' Socio-Economic Planning Secretary Felipe Medalla told
reporters at a year-end briefing.
	   The government projects the gross national product to grow
between 0.5 percent and 1.0 percent and gross domestic product to
grow 1.0 percent in 1998, Medalla said.
	   GNP measures a country's total output while GDP excludes the net
factor income from abroad.
	   For 1999, the government targets a GNP growth of 3.0 percent to
3.5 percent while GDP is projected to grow by 2.6 percent to 3.1
percent, Medalla said.
	   Medalla said a resilient service sector and continued consumer
market demand allowed the Philippines to escape a recession in 1998
and elude the various economic problems suffered by its neighbors
due to the regional financial crisis.
	   The probability of recovery in 1999 will be stronger as the
government generates additional foreign financing, including money
from Japan's ``Miyazawa Fund,'' for its deficit of 68.4 billion
pesos (dlrs 1.72 billion), Medalla said.
	   Medalla noted that escaping a recession and implementing crucial
structural reforms will allow the country to speed economic growth.
	   Inflation is expected to ease to between 8 percent and 9 percent
as agricultural production improves and the exchange rate becomes
more stable, he added.
	   Medalla said the government has allotted about 21.4 billion
pesos (dlrs 538.4 million) in new spending to stimulate economic
growth.
	   New revenue measures are expected to help finance the
government's budget next year. These include a road user's tax, a
land user's tax and a motor vehicle's tax.
	   Medalla said the labor front remained ``relatively calm''
throughout 1998 despite a rise in unemployment, while other
countries like Indonesia and South Korea grappled with unrest.
	   The unemployment rate rose to 9.6 percent in October 1998
compared with 7.9 percent for the same month last year. 	   
