<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Spain-Christmas Lottery </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Spain awaits winning numbers in world's richest lottery
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MADRID, Spain (AP) _ People throughout Spain waited anxiously to
see whether their Christmas festivities would get off to a jingling
start Tuesday with a win in a lottery billed as the richest in the
world.
	   As of 9 a.m. (0800 gmt), ticket holders were glued to the TV and
radio sets as children from a school in Madrid picked out numbered
balls from drums and sang out the winning numbers in a ceremony
that lasts some four hours.
	   This year the grand prize of the lottery, which is dubbed ``El
Gordo'' (The Fat One), was for 300 million pesetas (dlrs 2.1
million).
	   The lottery was to dish out a total of 194 billion pesetas (dlrs
1.4 billion) in winnings to tens of thousands of ticket holders
throughout Spain.
	   The lottery, which began in 1818, comprises 140 number series
with each series divided into 66,000 tickets valued at 30,000
pesetas (dlrs 2,100) each. The tickets are subsequently divided
into 10 `decimo' shares worth 3,000 pesetas (dlrs 21) each.
	   Most Spaniards share tickets or `decimos' with family, friends
and coworkers, so lottery windfalls ripple through whole
communities.
	   Income from ticket sales was 250 billion pesetas (dlrs 1.8
billion) this year, 8.9 percent up on last year, according to the
State Lottery Department.
	   The Spanish Treasury hives off 30 percent of the total raised
before the draw takes place to keep the winnings tax free.
	   (cg) 	   
</TEXT>
