<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Garbage Riot </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Residents flee toxic waste; soldiers standby to clean it up
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By CHRIS FONTAINE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SIHANOUKVILLE, Cambodia (AP) _ Trucks brought soldiers to this
seaport town Tuesday to clean up an illegal shipment of toxic waste
as hundreds of residents frightened of health hazards left for
safer areas.
	   Police confirmed that four people were killed in road accidents
Monday when more than 1,000 people fled Sihanoukville, bringing
total confirmed deaths in connection to the waste shipment to five.
	   A dock worker died mysteriously a day after cleaning the hold of
the ship that brought the 3,000 tons of waste, believed to be
compressed industrial ash, from Taiwan to Sihanoukville about two
weeks ago.
	   Analysis by a Hong Kong laboratory has shown the waste contains
traces of mercury, a poisonous metal. It was illegally dumped at a
site about 10 kilometers (six miles) north of Sihanoukville.
	   In Taiwan, the Environmental Protection Bureau said the waste
had been properly treated and should not cause hazards to human
beings. It said it was willing to send a team to Cambodia to
investigate.
	   If the investigation shows the hazards were caused by the
Taiwanese waste, the bureau said it would ask the company that
produced it, Formosa Plastic Corp., to take it back.
	   Bulldozers and other heavy equipment moved earth to form a dike
around the waste Tuesday. Soldiers covered it with plastic tarps to
prevent any of the fine dust from blowing away.
	   Imported protective clothing meanwhile arrived at Koh Kong, a
nearby province, and was to be flown in by helicopter for soldiers
about to get a crash course in removing hazardous materials.
	   Eight truckloads of oil barrels and three shipping containers
have been brought to the dump site. The soldiers will begin packing
the waste Tuesday or Wednesday, officials said.
	   Sihanoukville was rocked by two days of violent protests over
the weekend by residents outraged by alleged corruption among
customs and government officials who let the waste into the
country.
	   One protester who fell out of the window of a hotel that was
ransacked was badly injured, though there has been no confirmation
he was killed.
	   Prince Norodom Ranariddh, president of the National Assembly,
said that he had been informed by Prime Minister Hun Sen that dlrs
3 million had been paid in bribes to corrupt officials to get the
waste into the country. The government has vowed to find and
prosecute them.
	   About half a dozen soldiers stood guard Tuesday outside the
house of deputy governor Khim Bo, which was ransacked by mobs over
the weekend.
	   Chief Prosecutor Mam Muth said 12 demonstrators have been
arrested and are being detained at the local prison. Nine have been
charged with looting.
	   The other three are human-rights workers from Licadho, a local
organization. Mam Muth said that they had been identified as
ringleaders of the riot.
	   The 200 seats on all buses leaving for the capital, Phnom Penh,
185 kilometers (115 miles) to the north, were fully booked, agents
said. Passenger levels were four times higher than usual.
	   In Phnom Penh, a tourism official said that the presence of the
waste and the riots was hurting Sihanoukville's economy. The town
is a popular holiday spot.
	   ``Guest houses have no visitors and many bookings have been
canceled,'' said Thong Khon, secretary of state at the Tourism
Ministry. ``It is regrettable. This problem should not have been
allowed to happen.'' s regrettable. 	   
</TEXT>
