<HEADLINE>
Tourism to selected Pacific destinations healthy despite Asian
</HEADLINE>
crisis &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   SUVA, Fiji (AP) _ The three main South Pacific Island tourist
destinations _ Fiji, Tahiti and New Caledonia _ are expecting a
record number of tourists in 1999 despite the collapse of Asian
outbound tourism, the Fiji Visitors Bureau said Tuesday.
	   Twelve other Pacific destinations, including Australia, New
Zealand and Hawaii, were reporting tourist downturns caused by
slumping Asian visitor arrival figures, said Sitiveni Yaqona, chief
executive of the bureau.
	   But tourist numbers to Fiji are growing and the 1998 count is
expected to break the 1997 record of 359,441 visitors, he told an
industry meeting.
	   Tahiti, which had 163,774 visitors in 1997, and New Caledonia,
which had 91,121 visitors in 1997 were reporting similar trends.
	   Yaqona said the bureau was confident of 8.5 percent growth in
1999, taking visitors to Fiji to about 400,000 visitors.
	   The bureau expects the number of Australian visitors to grow by
11.6 percent to 111,800; U.S. tourists to increase by 13.2 percent
to 55,800; Canadian visitors to grow by 20.3 percent to 16,000;
British visitors to grow by 8.5 percent to 43,000; and European
business to grow by 3.7 percent to 30,000 visitors.
	   Japanese tourists were expected to decline by 5 percent to
33,700, Yaqona said. 	   
</TEXT>
