<SLUG> BC-France-Ariane Launch </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ariane rocket launches American satellite 
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ An Ariane rocket placed an U.S. telecommunications
satellite into orbit overnight, completing the European Space
Agency's 1998 commercial launch program, the agency said Tuesday.
	   The launch from Guiana Space Center in French Guiana, on the
northern edge of South America, took place at 10:08 p.m. Monday
(0108 GMT) Tuesday, officials said.
	   It was the 115th launch of an Ariane 4 and the 11th of the year.
	   An Ariane 4 rocket equipped with two liquid-fuel engines was
used to place the 3.6 ton PAS-6B satellite in orbit.
	   It was the 7th satellite for the American Panamsat company that
Arianspace, the commercial arm of the European Space Agency, has
launched since June 1998.
	   Built by Hugues Space and Communications, the satellite should
be able to transmit television programs to Latin America for the
next 15 years from its orbital position over Brazil.
	   Next year is an important one for Ariane because for the first
time the new, more powerful Ariane 5 will be used for commercial
launches following a successful takeoff in October.
	   Ariane 5 is twice as powerful as Ariane 4, which it will
gradually replace. Two test launches prior to October had failed.
	   (parf-dgs) 	   
</TEXT>
