<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Fuji Heavy Industries Ltd. chairman Isamu Kawai,
who was arrested this month for allegedly bribing a lawmaker, has
resigned to take responsibility for the scandal, the company said
Tuesday.
	   Kawai, 76, is suspected of giving 5 million yen (dlrs 43,000) in
kickbacks to ruling Liberal Democratic Party legislator Yojiro
Nakajima in exchange for help in securing a government defense
contract.
	   Yasuyuki Kogure, 64, a former Fuji Heavy executive director, has
also been arrested on suspicion of bribing Nakajima.
	   A Fuji Heavy spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
that the chairman post will remain vacant for now.
	   Nakajima, 39, a Liberal Democratic Party member of Parliament,
was arrested last month on charges of ordering false receipts made
to account for missing party money. The arrest was unrelated to the
Fuji Heavy Industries case.
	   Fuji Heavy Industries is the maker of Subaru automobiles.
