<HEADLINE>
BC-Spain-Christmas Lottery, 1st Ld-Writethru
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Christmas lottery distributes massive winnings in Spain &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with No. 21856 winning top prize; EDITS to conform &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MADRID, Spain (AP) _ Christmas festivities got off to a whopping
start Tuesday in several towns across Spain which shared a prize of
300 million pesetas (dlrs 2.1 million), the top award in a lottery
billed as the world's richest.
	   The annual lottery, known as ``El Gordo'' (The Fat One), was to
dish out a total of 194 billion pesetas (dlrs 1.4 billion) in
winnings this year to thousands of ticket holders throughout Spain.
	   Each year, millions of television viewers watch as children from
a school in Madrid pick out numbered balls from drums and sing out
the winning number in a ceremony that lasts some four to five
hours.
	   The winning ticket bearing the number 21856 was picked at 10.30
a.m. (0930 gmt).
	   The second prize of 144 million pesetas (dlrs 102 million) was
for number 07308.
	   The lottery, which began in 1818, comprises 140 number series
with each series divided into 66,000 tickets valued at 30,000
pesetas (dlrs 2,100) each. The tickets are subsequently divided
into 10 shares worth 3,000 pesetas (dlrs 21) each.
	   Most Spaniards share tickets with family, friends and
co-workers, so lottery windfalls ripple through whole communities.
	   Income from ticket sales was 250 billion pesetas (dlrs 1.8
billion) this year, 8.9 perecent up on last year, according to the
State Lottery Department.
	   The Spanish Treasury hives off 30 percent of the total raised
before the draw takes place to keep the winnings tax free.
	   (cg) 	   
</TEXT>
