<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-Retail Sales </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
October retail sales plunge 20 percent
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Hong Kong retail sales plunged 20 percent in
October from the same month last year, the government announced
Tuesday.
	   Consumer concerns about the uncertain economic outlook and
rising unemployment _ at a 17-year high _ have made them more
cautious about spending, Hong Kong's Census and Statistics
Department said.
	   Retail sales fell to an estimated 15.8 billion Hong Kong dollars
(U.S. dlrs 2.0 billion) in October. The volume of goods sold fell
by 19 percent compared with October 1997.
	   Sales of motor vehicles posted the biggest fall, dropping 49
percent in value and 43 percent in volume compared to a year
earlier. Sales of clothing and footwear sank 31 percent in value
and 28 percent in volume.
	   For the first ten months of 1998, retail sales declined by 16
percent in value and 17 percent in volume.
	   Retailers have been closing branches, laying off staff, and
slashing wages to survive as the territory struggles through an
economic recession brought on by Asia's economic crisis.
	   Hong Kong's economy contracted 7 percent in the third quarter
and is expected to shrink by 5 percent this year, compared with 5.3
percent growth in 1997. 	   
</TEXT>
