<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Macedonia-Greece </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Frosty relations between Greece, Macedonia appear ready to thaw
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ELENA BECATOROS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SKOPJE, Macedonia (AP) _ In an indication of improved ties
between two Balkan neighbors, Greece's foreign minister arrived in
Macedonia on Tuesday for a series of meetings with government
officials.
	   Theodoros Pangalos' one-day trip is the first official visit by
a European Union minister since the new Macedonian government was
sworn in after October's general elections.
	   Pangalos was met at the airport by his Macedonian counterpart,
Aleksandar Dimitrov.
	   For almost a decade, Greece and Macedonia have squabbled over
what name the former Yugoslav republic could use. Greece claims the
use of the name ``Macedonia'' masks expansionist aims by its
northern neighbor, and insists the northern Greek province of
Macedonia is the only region which is entitled to use the name.
	   Talks held under United Nations auspices in New York to resolve
the dispute have made little headway, with 19 rounds of
negotiations already completed.
	   The dispute led to a crippling embargo imposed by Greece on
Macedonia in 1994. Although the embargo was lifted in 1995
following an interim agreement, relations remained frosty.
	   Greece recognizes Macedonia under the name ``Former Yugoslav
Republic of Macedonia,'' and will deal with the country only when
it uses that. The name ``Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia'' is
the one officially used by the U.N. General Assembly.
	   But Pangalos is expected to avoid raising the issue of the name
during his talks here, preferring to concentrate on now burgeoning
economic ties between the two countries.
	   The new Macedonian prime minister, Ljubco Georgijevski, appears
ready to help, diplomatic sources said on condition of anonymity.
	   Despite entering Macedonia's first parliament with the
center-right VMRO-DPMNE which championed nationalist values,
Georgijevski has softened his stance, and Greece is eager to take
advantage of a possible compromise.
	   Neither country wants the name dispute to stand in the way of
lucrative commercial ties. Although Macedonia is one of the poorest
Balkan nations, it provides an opportunity for Greece to expand
further into Balkan markets, as it has begun to do in Bulgaria and
Albania.
	   But Pangalos' visit has already raised objections at home, where
any hint that Greece's neighbor may eventually be allowed to use
the name ``Macedonia'' has the potential for whipping up
nationalistic fervor.
	   On Monday, former conservative Foreign Minister Andonis Samaras
complained Pangalos would be offering ``Christmas presents'' during
his visit by backing down on the name issue.
	   It was during Samaras' tenure as a foreign minister for the
conservative party that the problem first appeared, just after
Macedonia seceeded from Yugoslavia in 1991 - the only former
Yugoslav republic to do so without bloodshed.
	   Macedonia, which borders ethnically tense Kosovo province, is
particularly interested in reducing friction with its neighbors.
The new government's hopes to eventually join international
organizations such as NATO and the European Union add impetus to
the drive for improving relations with EU member Greece.
	   One of the new government's first decisions was to allow the
deployment on Macedonian soil of a 1,800-strong NATO rapid reaction
force, designed to provide assistance to 2,000 international
verifiers monitoring the situation in neighboring Kosovo.
	   Macedonia joined NATO's Partnership for Peace Program in 1995.
 &UR; eb/rr
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Macedonia-Greece; CT:i; 
