r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Japan-US-Rice     12-22 0394
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-US-Rice </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Agriculture minister: Increasing rice imports wouldn't fix trade
</HEADLINE>
imbalance

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Increasing American rice imports to Japan would do
little to correct the country's trade imbalance with the United
States, Japan's agriculture minister said Tuesday.
	   Shoichi Nakagawa's remarks came amid recent U.S. criticism of
Japan for deciding to heavily tax imported rice despite a
ballooning trade surplus with the rest of the world.
	   ``Every time this discussion (of the trade imbalance) springs
up, agricultural products and rice are singled out,'' Nakagawa told
reporters.
	   Instead, the U.S. should find other ways to boost imports to
Japan, since ``rice alone cannot resolve this issue,'' the minister
said.
	   Japan's trade surplus with the United States stood at dlrs 5.95
billion in October, 31.9 percent higher than the year before.
	   Last week, Japan's Cabinet officially endorsed a plan to impose
a flat tariff of 351.17 yen (dlrs 3.05) per kilogram on foreign
rice from April 1, 1999 despite opposition from major trading
partners.
	   Before the decision was made official, U.S. Ambassador Thomas
Foley warned that such high tariffs would ``cripple'' U.S. rice
imports to Japan and lead to a serious trade disagreement.
	   Imposing the tariff is widely seen as a move to protect Japanese
farmers, who are accustomed to some of the highest rice prices in
the world, from cheap imports.
	   Nakagawa, however, insisted that the decision to limit rice
imports reflects the demands of consumers, who tend to buy Japanese
rice over imported rice.
	   ``The majority of rice imported into this country has not met
the needs of the Japanese public palate,'' the minister said.
	   Japanese government representatives were in the Washington on
Monday for talks with U.S. officials about the issue following
Tokyo's official announcement of the tariff plan to the World Trade
Organization.
	   In his speech, Nakagawa said the tariffs are fully in line with
WTO regulations.
	   Japan pledged to open its rice market to imports in a landmark
1993 trade agreement which committed it to set minimum access
levels. The so-called Uruguay Round of the General Agreement on
Tariffs and Trade obliged Japan to import four percent of its rice
in 1995 and to gradually increase that amount to about eight
percent by 2000.
 &UR; (gp)	   
</TEXT>
