</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Traffic Scams </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Gang members sentenced for extorting money in fake accidents
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ A Beijing court has sentenced a gang of 17 people
to prison terms of up to 20 years for extorting money from drivers
after staging fake traffic accidents, the newspaper China Economic
Times reported Tuesday.
	   One member of the gang would intentionally run into a car on his
bicycle and then pretend to have been injured, while others would
emerge to force the driver into handing over cash as compensation,
the report said.
	   The group extorted more than 22,000 yuan (dlrs 2,660) from one
driver, it added. The court issued the sentences last Friday.
	   Meanwhile, two brothers in the southern province of Jiangxi were
sentenced to one and three years imprisonment each for using the
corpse of a third brother, who had died in a traffic accident, to
try to get money for his burial, the newspaper China Daily
reported.
	   The brothers used the corpse to block the road and also lay down
on the road themselves, blocking traffic, in their effort to raise
cash. The report said the pair were convicted of ``disturbing
traffic order.'' 	   
</TEXT>
