<SLUG> BC-Hungary-Rail Strike </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Railwaymen walk off work for higher wages
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) _ Workers of the Hungarian State Railways
staged a two-hour warning strike Tuesday morning to back their
demands for higher pay, the state-run news agency MTI reported.
	   The strike that took place between 5 a.m. and 7 a.m. (0400 to
0600 GMT), affected over 500 passenger trains.
	   The workers are demanding a 21 percent pay raise, while
management is offering only a 13 percent hike.
	   On Monday, railway engineers held a similar warning strike for
similar demands.
	   Representatives of the employers and the employees are get down
to the negotiating table later in the day to try to avoid a general
rail strike planned for January.
	   If no agreement is reached before the end of the year, the
engineers will walk off work between Jan. 4 and 7, and the other
rail workers from Jan. 7 for an indefinite time.
	   The average gross wages of the engineers is 96,000 forints (dlrs
465), while that of the state railways is 54,000 forints (dlrs
280).
	   (ek/rr) 	   
</TEXT>
