<SLUG> BC-Laos-UN-Drug Eradication </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UN gives dlrs 900,000 for Laos opium crop substitution
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ The United Nations Drug Control Program
has granted the government of Laos dlrs 900,000 for a program aimed
at eradicating opium growing and consumption, Laos government radio
said on Tuesday.
	   Parts of Laos are in the Golden Triangle, the jungle region
where the borders of Laos, Myanmar and Thailand converge and which
is a prime source of the world's supply of opium, the raw material
for heroin.
	   The report said the program will focus on Oudomsay province, the
second largest opium producing province in the country, and will
include aspects of community development, crop substitution, income
generation, environmental management, health and education.
	   It will also include treatment programs for addicts.
	   The grant will be distributed over a three-year period. 	   
</TEXT>
