<SLUG> BC-Asian Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Asian stock markets close generally mixed
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Asian stock markets closed generally mixed
Tuesday, with the key index tumbling in Tokyo but surging in
Taipei.
	   Tokyo's benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average dropped 373.50
points, or 2.64 percent, to close at 13,779.45 _ its lowest close
since Oct. 30. On Monday, the average closed down 41.34 points, or
0.29 percent.
	   Share prices fell as declines in the bond market were seen
hurting one of the few profitable operations at Japan's ailing
banks: their bond trading business.
	   Investors are worried that new bond issues by the Japanese
government to pay for fiscal stimulus spending will cause a glut in
the market, traders said.
	   Stock prices also took a tumble after Japan's finance minister
said the ministry's trust bureau, one of the biggest market
participants, will cease its monthly purchases in January.
	   Meanwhile, the U.S. dollar was quoted at 117.08 yen in late
afternoon trading in Tokyo, up 2.18 yen from late Monday here and
above its late New York level of 116.21 yen.
	   Share prices in Taiwan closed sharply higher, boosted by a
market stablization fund set up by the government to prop up the
flagging bourse.
	   Traders said retail investors took their lead from the
stabilization fund and moved into market in search of blue-chip
stocks.
	   The Taiwan market's key Weighted Stock Price Index surged 224.40
points, or 3.4 percent, to 6,782.68.
	   Elsewhere:
	   HONG KONG: Share prices closed generally lower Tuesday as
investors took profits following three consecutive sessions of
gains. The blue-chip Hang Seng Index fell 73.45 points, or 0.7
percent, closing at 10,322.56.
	   WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed higher for the sixth
straight session. The benchmark NZSE-40 Capital Index rose 23.39
points, or 1.1 percent, to 2,085.39.
	   MANILA: Philippine share prices closed mixed, with Wall Street's
overnight gain reviving interest in blue chips, though not enough
to boost demand for second-liners. The 30-share Philippine Stock
Exchange Index rose 20.51 points, or 1.1 percent, to 1,893.66.
	   SYDNEY: Australian share prices closed higher, pushed up by
local corporate news. The All Ordinaries Index rose 21.8 points, or
0.8 percent, to 2,759.8 points.
	   SEOUL: Share prices closed sharply lower as investors took
profits following Monday's surge when the index gained 7.7 percent.
The Korea Composite Stock Price Index fell 17.52 points, or 3.1
percent, to 547.75.
	   KUALA LUMPUR: Share prices closed sharply lower as investors
continued to take profits from last week's gains. The benchmark
Composite Index fell 13.62, or 2.5 percent, to 537.22.
	   JAKARTA: Share prices closed mixed in quiet trading. The
Composite Index rose 1.962 points, or 0.4 percent, to 406.465.
	   SINGAPORE: Share prices closed mixed as a sharp rise in bank
shares pushed up the benchmark index, while electronics stocks
opted out of the rally. The Straits Times Index rose 14.67 points,
or 1.1 percent, to 1,412.40.
	   BANGKOK: Thai share prices closed higher, pushed up by retail
buying in financial stocks whose prices have fallen recently,
dealers said. The Stock Exchange of Thailand (SET) Index rose 6.17
points, or 1.8 percent, to 343.34.
