<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-UN-Iraq </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
China offers to work with US to solve Iraq crisis
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Although strongly opposed to the U.S.-led bombing
of Iraq, China offered Tuesday to work with the United States to
resolve the crisis over U.N. weapons inspections in Iraq.
	   Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao said China and the United
States should work together in the U.N. Security Council.
	   ``This is not only good for the restoration of world peace and
security but also for the healthy and stable development of
China-U.S. relations,'' Zhu said.
	   The U.S. and British airstrikes on Iraq last week left the
Security Council sharply divided, especially over the future of the
inspections. Under the Gulf War cease-fire, the inspectors need to
certify Iraq has dismantled its missiles and nuclear, chemical and
biological weapons before sanctions can be lifted.
	   Russia and China want the sanctions removed and have demanded
the ouster of the chief weapons inspector, Richard Butler, who
heads the U.N. Special Commission, known as UNSCOM.
	   Zhu did not offer any new suggestions for resolving the crisis,
except to say that China was considering whether UNSCOM's
``approach and composition'' should be changed.
	   The United States and Britain want UNSCOM to continue its job
and support Butler.
	   Butler's report last week concluding Iraq failed to cooperate
fully with U.N. weapons inspectors triggered four days of air
strikes. 	   
</TEXT>
