<SLUG> BC-Koreas-Defector </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: South Korean dissident defects to North Korea
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ A South Korean dissident has defected
to North Korea, the communist country's state-run news agency
reported Tuesday.
	   Yoon Sung-shik, 60, said he defected to the North because
``justice, progress, democracy and reunification of Koreas cannot
be realized'' under the South Korean government, the North's
official Korean Central News Agency said.
	   About 200 North Koreans have escaped to South Korea in the past
three years, reporting widespread hunger in the isolated country.
But it is rare for a South Korean to defect to the North.
	   The agency gave no details about Yoon's escape route.
	   Seoul's government spy agency _ the Agency for National Security
Planning _ said Yoon disappeared while visiting an unidentified
third country to seek treatment for a heart ailment. The agency
didn't elaborate.
	   North Korea described Yoon as an active dissident leader,
involved in four dissident groups.
	   But the groups were considered minor in the South's dissident
movement. Two of them confirmed that Yoon was a member but said
they have little personal data on the man.
	   The Korean Peninsula was divided into the communist North and
capitalist South in 1945. The Koreas are technically still at war
because their 1950-53 war ended with an armistice, not a peace
treaty. 	   
</TEXT>
