<SLUG> BC-Poland-Miners </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Signs of emerging deal to end Polish miners' protest
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ANDRZEJ STYLINSKI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   WARSAW, Poland (AP) _ Prime Minister Jerzy Buzek said Tuesday
the government didn't intend to deprive miners and others working
in dangerous conditions of early retirement privileges.
	   Responding to a strike threat from miners protesting proposed
changes in their pension rules, Buzek said he believed the labor
dispute could be solved within the next 24 hours.
	   Government officials and leaders of the Solidarity union were to
meet Tuesday to discuss early retirement schemes for miners, while
more than 400 workers in 52 mines continued an underground sit-in.
	   Alarmed by the government pension reform that sets the
retirement age at 65 for men and 60 for women, Solidarity miners
began the sit-in Dec. 10 to demand keeping the present system,
which allows them to retire after 25 years of work, no matter their
age. They also oppose a mining restructuring plan that would cut
jobs and production.
	   Workers at coal mines in Silesia, as well as copper, zinc and
lead ore mines, staged a warning strike Monday and voted
overwhelmingly to hold a general strike on an undetermined date.
	   Solidarity's Mining Section said Tuesday that 98 percent of
miners supported the strike.
	   Buzek, attempting to calm the atmosphere, said his
Solidarity-led government never proposed that ``people working in
such difficult conditions like miners had to work until they are
65.''
	   He said the government was negotiating final details of
so-called ``bridge pensions'' for miners retiring after 25 years of
work, covering them until they become eligible to regular pensions
at 65.
	   Buzek's Cabinet, which took over the office in October 1997 from
a leftist government, has been working on widespread social and
economic reforms expected to complete Poland's transition from
communism to a market economy.
	   The reforms include restructuring ailing industries such as
mining and steel. Coal mining restructuring calls for reducing
production from 137 million tons last year to 110 million tons in
2002, as well as cutting jobs by more than 40 percent _ from
245,000 now to 138,000 in three years.
	   Coal mining, once the country's leading hard-currency earner
during communist times, is still heavily subsidized under Poland's
market reforms that began in 1989.
	   (ajs-tsc)
</TEXT>
