<SLUG> BC-Jordan-Iraq, 1st Ld-Writethru,0517 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Evacuated U.N. humanitarian workers head back to Baghdad
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES starting 13th graf with U.N. report on supplies
entering Iraq, oil leaving. No pickup. &QL; 
 &UR; With Iraq &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo planned &QL; 
 &UR; By ALIA SHUKRI HAMZEH &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) _ About 120 U.N. humanitarian workers,
evacuated from Iraq last week during U.S.-British air attacks, left
Amman on Tuesday to return to Baghdad.
	   Before departing, many in the group were smiling and taking
photos of each other in front of the buses that will take them on
the more than 12-hour journey across the desert.
	   ``We are very happy to be going back to take up our work in
Iraq,'' Darleen Biseau said as she boarded one of the three buses
making the journey.
	   The U.N. workers left the Iraqi capital on the second day of the
airstrikes on Iraq.
	   Biseau, who works on the U.N.-approved oil-for-food program in
Baghdad, on Saturday described her trip to Amman as a journey the
U.N. workers made with tears for the people they left behind. She
said the bombardment would add to the suffering of Iraqis.
	   She said she was ``hoping for the best'' in returning.
	   Abdullah Odeh, resident representative in Amman for the U.N.
Development Program, said agency personnel who left Baghdad were
returning to ``pick up the pieces'' of their work.
	   ``They will continue the mission they are there for, which is
the full humanitarian mission,'' he added.
	   The oil-for-food program is an exception to punishing trade
sanctions imposed by the U.N. Security Council after Iraq's 1990
invasion of Kuwait. It allows Iraq to sell limited quantities of
oil to buy needed food and medicine for its 22 million people.
	   Most of the U.N. workers departing Amman refused to talk to
reporters.
	   The workers were evacuated after spending the first night of the
airstrikes last Thursday huddled in their headquarters on the
outskirts of Baghdad.
	   Those who had remained in Baghdad were special U.N. envoy
Prakash Shah, U.N. humanitarian coordinator Hans von Sponeck, and
26 other U.N. workers.
	   Meanwhile, a statement issued by the U.N. humanitarian spokesman
in New York, John Mills, said that the flow of food and medicine
into Iraq resumed Monday via Umm Qasr in southern Iraq and were to
restart Tuesday at the Jordanian and Syrian borders.
	   Through the airstrikes, the border crossings between Turkey and
Kurdish areas in northern Iraq remained open, the statement said.
	   It also confirmed earlier reports that oil exports had continued
normally via the southern Iraqi port of Al-Bakr and the Turkish
port of Ceyhan. It said the value of oil exported since the
beginning of fifth phase of the oil-for-food program on Nov. 26 was
about dlrs 172 million.
	   The program allows Iraq to sell dlrs 5.2 billion dollars worth
of oil in a six-month period to buy needed food and medicine for
its 22 million people.
	   But the government has said that low world oil prices and
problems stepping up production at its badly maintained oil
facilities won't let it meet the sales target.
</TEXT>
