<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Olympics-IOC-Bribes,0479 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Newspaper says George Mitchell will head USOC probe
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SALT LAKE CITY (AP) _ US West, a major sponsor of Salt Lake's
2002 Winter Olympics, has written the head of the Salt Lake
Organizing Committee a strong letter protesting the ``unsavory
allegations'' surrounding the bid for the games.
	   There are three official inquiries into the scholarships the
Salt Lake bid committee gave to six relatives of International
Olympic Committee members. There also have been allegations
regarding medical care and expensive gifts, including shotguns and
skis, given to some IOC members.
	   IOC President Juan Antonio Samaranch scheduled a special meeting
of his executive board Jan. 22-23 to deal with a report on the IOC
investigation into the Salt Lake City allegations.
	   SLOC's ethics committee also is investigating, and the U.S.
Olympic Committee is launching its own probe under the guidance of
former Sen. George Mitchell.
	   US West has asked SLOC President Frank Joklik to ``clarify what
has transpired and what actions the Olympic movement is taking to
address these issues.''
	   Mark Roellig, US West's general counsel, said in a Dec. 18
letter obtained by The Salt Lake Tribune and KTVX that ``the ideals
and spirit of the Olympic Games and the values and high standards
of the athletes draw companies like ours to sponsor the process and
to use these powerful symbols of commitment, determination and fair
play in our marketing, management and community affairs efforts.
	   ``The very core of these ideals and the spirit of the Games are
now under scrutiny and perhaps tainted. This is an extremely
serious issue for all of us,'' wrote Roellig.
	   He asked what is being done to ``restore the integrity of the
Olympic brand'' and ``Are there going to be any more `surprises'
that you are aware of?''
	   Relations with corporate sponsors concern the USOC, which is the
lead entity in a joint marketing agreement with SLOC.
	   Any scandal that undermines that effort is a concern to the
USOC, which called an 1500 GMT teleconference with the press to
announce its own investigation.
	   Mitchell, the former Senate Democratic leader from Maine, is
chairman of the USOC's Ethics Oversight Committee, and will head
the investigation. Now a Washington lawyer, Mitchell also was
President Bill Clinton's negotiator of this spring's peace accord
between Protestants and Catholics in Northern Ireland.
	   The New York Times reported Tuesday that Kenneth Duberstein, a
White House chief of staff under President Ronald Reagan, will be
the co-chairman of the panel that also will include Donald Fehr,
executive director of the baseball players union; Roberta Cooper
Ramo, a New Mexico attorney who was the first female president of
the American Bar Association; and Jeff Benz, a member of the USOC's
athletes advisory council. 	   
</TEXT>
