<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Balloon Quest, 6th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
China tells balloon to land, but organizers say that's unsafe
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: COMBINES urgent serves, updates with balloon's position &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ China ordered a round-the-world balloon expedition
to land Tuesday, expedition organizers said, but they protested
that they didn't dare because of the rugged terrain.
	   ``Impossible _ landing in that area is life-threatening,'' said
project director Mike Kendrick in London, after the balloon team
disclosed the Chinese decision.
	   The ballon was over Tibet, 50 miles (80 kms) north of Bhutan at
about 1100 GMT, according to Press Association, the British news
agency.
	   Earlier, the Chinese Foreign Ministry said it regretted that
British tycoon Richard Branson, American millionaire Steve Fossett
and Per Lindstrand of Sweden did not abide by an earlier agreement
to fly over southernmost China below 26 degrees north latitude.
	   Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao had said China could not
agree to the balloon's northerly course, but he did not call on the
crew to withdraw immediately or land.
	   Organizers of the expedition apologized, said they were trying
to head south as quickly as wind and weather permitted _ which is
about 50 mph (80 kmh). They said the balloon was forced off course
by storms, the U.S.-British military campaign in Iraq and the
refusal of two other countries to permit their flight.
	   ``China is very regretful,'' Zhu said at a routine media
briefing. ``China will not take responsibility for the
consequences.''
	   Beijing had given permission for the ICO Global balloon to
travel only over southernmost China. It would have effectively kept
the balloonists away from the isolated Tibetan plateau, where
rescue would be difficult, and out of busy air traffic corridors
monitored by a spotty air traffic control system.
	   But because of diversions around Mediterranean storms and Iraq,
and the refusal of Russia and Iran to open their airspace, the
balloon crossed the Himalayas further north than planned and
entered China 250 miles (400 kms) north of the agreed airspace
corridor early Tuesday morning, Chinese time.
	   Kendrick said Chinese air traffic controllers were informed the
moment the balloon passed over the border, with an apology added to
the communication. The balloon team continued to contact them every
15 minutes to keep the Chinese informed about their position.
	   In February, China withheld permission for a European balloon
team to fly through its airspace, forcing them to land and end
their around-the-world bid.
	   As it became apparent early Monday that the balloon would
inevitably cross into unauthorized Chinese territory, Prime
Minister Tony Blair sent a message to Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji
asking for China's help.
	   The ICO Global balloon had already run into trouble on its trip.
Libya unexpectedly revoked permission to enter its airspace, but
the situation was resolved shortly before the three-man crew flew
over the country on Saturday.
	   Then, after steering around thunderstorms near Cyprus, the crew
had to maneuver the 270-foot (82-meter) craft through narrow gaps
between no-fly territories, including Iraq.
	   The crew members estimate the trip could last from eight days to
nearly three weeks. They hope to touch down somewhere in western
Europe at the end of a 24,000-mile (38,000 kms) flight, which will
take them over India, the South China sea, the Pacific and the
United States.
	   The team secured permission from 97 countries for overflights
and initially had only four refusals _ Iran, Iraq, Russia and North
Korea.
	   (aw-rb)
</TEXT>
