<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Japan-Rice </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japan raising a ``bamboo curtain'' against trade: Fischer
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CANBERRA, Australia (AP) _ Japan's massive new rice tariff
represented a ``bamboo curtain'' which could prolong the Asian
financial crisis and result in retaliatory action by its trading
partners, Australia's Deputy Prime Minister said Tuesday.
	   Tim Fischer conceded the new Japanese tariff was not illegal,
and would not stop the existing Australian dollars 72
million-a-year (U.S. dlrs 44.6 million) worth of rice exported to
Japan.
	   Japan owed its postwar prosperity to the opening up of world
trade in the wake of World War II, but the country had apparently
failed to heed the message of the Great Depression, which was
prolonged by nations erecting trade barriers, he said.
	   ``Fortress Japan, or for that matter, Fortress Australia, would
be absolutely the wrong way to go,'' he said.
	   ``This represents a bamboo curtain, with some pretty spikey
bamboos, but we'll be doing all we can to wedge open that curtain,
and reduce its size, in the next round of negotiations.''
	   Fischer said Japan's new tariff was 15 times Australia's highest
tariff. While he ruled out raising Australian tariffs, he said he
would look into other action that could be taken against Japan. 	   
</TEXT>
