<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Eritrea-Ethiopia-Djibouti </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Official: Ethiopian troops in Djibouti to outflank Eritreans
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By JULIA STEWART &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ASMARA, Eritrea (AP) _ Ethiopia has moved troops into
neighboring Djibouti to outflank Ertirea in the seven-month border
dispute between the two Horn of Africa neighbors, a senior Eritrean
official has said.
	   Speaking to reporters late Monday, Foreign Minister Haile
Weldensae said both Djibouti and Sudan were supporting Ethiopia's
war effort against Eritrea.
	   ``It is dangerous for Djibouti,'' Waldensae said, adding that
Eritrea would defend itself whenever necessary.
	   The official also charged that landlocked Ethiopia _ which used
to use the Eritrean ports of Assab and Massawa _ is using Port
Sudan on Sudan's Red Sea coast for logistical support.
	   Djibouti now serves as Ethiopia's main entry for imports and
exports.
	   It was not immediately possible to obtain comment from
authorities in Djibouti because of the Muslim Ramandan holiday when
most government offices only work half days.
	   Ethiopia and Eritrea clashed in May and June over undemarcated
colonial boundaries, and several hundred people were killed.
	   Thousands of troops from both sides are hunkered down along both
sides of their common 1,000-kilometer (620-mile) border. Periodic
shelling at hot spots and large-scale build up of weapons has
sustained tensions.
	   Djibouti severed diplomatic ties with Eritrea Nov. 18, following
Eritrean allegations that the tiny port state in the crook of the
Horn of Africa was aiding the Ethiopian war effort.
	   Ertirea and Sudan broke relations in 1994 amid accusations that
each suppported the other's rebel movements.
	   The foreign ministers of Sudan and Eritrea met in Qatar on Nov.
10 and agreed to hold periodic talks.
	   Weldensae said Eritrea will continue to meet Sudanese officials,
but no normalization of relations cna take place as long as
Khartoum's National Islamic Front government continues its policy
of regional destabilization.
	   Although Sudanese rebels and opposition have their headquarters
in Asmara, Weldensae denied that the Sudan People's Liberation Army
carries out any military activity or training exercises on Eritrean
soil.
	   But witnesses have seen SPLA camps inside Eritrea.
	   (js/sl) 	   
</TEXT>
