<HEADER>
w1318 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Soccer-Bosman     12-22 0534
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Bosman </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Belgian soccer federation awards dlrs 463,900 in damages to Bosman
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ANNA SATHIAH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) - Belgium's Soccer Federation said
Tuesday it will award 16 million Belgian francs (dlrs 463,900) in
damages to Jean-Marc Bosman, ending an eight-year legal battle for
the former player whose fight for justice led to a ruling that
revolutionized soccer in Europe.
	   ``With this agreement, the various parties wished to end
elegantly this affair ... in order to focus in a positive manner on
the new football challenges at the eve of the year 2000,'' the
Federation's secretary-general, Jan Peeters said in a statement.
	   Bosman, who told the Associated Press earlier this month he
hoped for an out-of-court settlement by the end of the year, is
immensely relieved, his lawyer said.
	   ``Even if this is not a huge amount, it is very important
because it allows him to stop being the Bosman affair and to return
to being Jean-Marc Bosman,'' Bosman's lawyer Jean-Louis Dupont
quoted his client as saying.
	   Dupont said the agreement was made possible by a change of
leadership at the head of FIFA, soccer's world governing body.
``Two years ago such a transaction would not have been possible,''
he said.
	   ``Tuesday's agreement shows the soccer world is seeking a new
spirit of cooperation and of mutual respect in its relations with
the public authorities, and particularly with the European Union,''
Dupont said.
	   Bosman gained fame as the man who challenged Europe's soccer
authorities before the courts when his transfer from Belgium's FC
Liege to France's Dunkirk was blocked.
	   On Dec. 15, 1995, Bosman won his case when the European Court of
Justice ruled that the system of transfer fees after contracts had
expired was illegal. So were the limits on European Union
foreigners.
	   The Bosman ruling set a precedent, releasing players from the
control of clubs with the end of a contract and effectively
creating free agency, while allowing clubs to field as many EU
players as they liked.
	   But the case didn't end there for Bosman. The ruling went back
to the appeals court in Belgium, where Bosman's case became
logjammed. Bosman has been out of work for the past three years,
having quit competitive soccer because he could not live off his
salary.
	   Dupont said Bosman's last wish before turning the page now is
that players around the world will respond to a ``Thank You
Jean-Marc Bosman'' operation launched earlier this month by a local
sports and union rights organization.
	   The organization called on all first-division players in the 15
EU nations to donate the bonus of one game to Bosman in a show of
solidarity. So far not one cent has been given, Dupont said.
	   Bosman hopes there will be a response. He wants to use most of
the funds to set up a foundation for young players who don't make
it into the professional world and have no one to turn to.
	   ``Nine out of ten young players from Africa or South America who
get tried out when they're 14 or 15 years old don't make it into
the football world, and often they end up on the streets,'' Dupont
said.
	    &UR; (as-rjm)
</TEXT>
