<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP Top Financial News,0772 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   A summary of financial and business news from The Associated
Press at 1200 GMT. Stories carry ``f'' or ``i'' category codes and
move on this circuit in expanded form:
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Asian stock markets closed generally mixed
Tuesday, with the key index tumbling in Japan but surging in
Taiwan. Tokyo's benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average dropped
373.50 points, or 2.64 percent, to close at 13,779.45 _ its lowest
close since Oct. 30. Share prices fell on fears that declines in
the bond market would further hurt Japan's ailing banks. Share
prices in Taiwan closed sharply higher, boosted by a market
stablization fund set up by the government to prop up the flagging
bourse. Taipei's Weighted Stock Price Index surged 224.40 points,
or 3.4 percent, to 6,782.68. Meanwhile, the U.S. dollar was quoted
at 117.08 yen in late afternoon trading in Tokyo, up 2.18 yen from
late Monday here and above its late New York level of 116.21 yen.
(ASIAN MARKETS)
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ After helping to stabilize world financial
markets with three interest-rate reductions this fall, Federal
Reserve officers meeting Tuesday little reason to cut again right
now, economist believe. Stock prices, which plunged in the United
States and elsewhere after the August devaluation of the Russian
ruble, have recovered. After more recent jitters over the
impeachment of President Bill Clinton, the Dow Jones average of
industrial stocks gained 85 points Monday, closing at 8,989. And
business credit, which contracted sharply for all but low-risk
borrowers this fall, has loosened up. Not only that, the U.S.
economy just keeps barreling along, showing little sign outside of
manufacturing and farming that it has slowed in response to the
world's economic problems. (US-ECONOMY-INTEREST RATES)
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ Interest rate cuts in the United States and
other industrial countries have eased the threat that the Asian
financial crisis will trigger a global recession, the International
Monetary Fund said in an updated economic outlook. But the
182-nation lending agency still found plenty of things that could
go wrong in the new year, ranging from a sudden plunge in U.S.
stock prices or the value of the dollar to the failure of Japanese
authorities to aggressively battle their country's worst recession
in 50 years. Accordingly, the IMF trimmed its forecast for world
growth in 1999 to just 2.2 percent, down by 0.3 percentage point
from a report issued just two months ago. The crisis that began in
Thailand in 1997 has spread to a number of other Asian countries,
pushing them into deep recessions and in August leveled the Russian
economy. (WORLD OUTLOOK)
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ The European Union's Foreign Trade
Commissioner says the EU will push for a World Trade Organization
solution to its banana dispute with the United States after
Washington unveiled a list of EU goods subject to stiff trade
sanctions. Leon Brittan said in a statement Monday ``It is time to
take action against the pernicious and unlawful effect of this
wholly unilateral legislation.'' On Monday, the United States
published a list of EU products ranging from sheep's milk cheese to
cashmere sweaters that will be slapped with 100 percent import
tariffs. U.S. Trade Representative Charlene Barshefsky said in
Washington the United States is exercising its rights under the WTO
to impose penalties on the EU for, in the U.S. view, unfairly
blocking U.S. companies from selling bananas from Latin America to
Europe. But Brittan lashed out at the sanctions, saying, ``It is
difficult to think of a more obvious breach of the multilateral
trade system than to take the law into your own hands in defiance
of the rules.'' (US-EU-BANANA WAR)
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russian workers are owed 84.9 billion rubles (dlrs
4 billion) in back wages, and most of the debt belongs to private
firms, not the government, an official said Tuesday. Millions of
Russians receive their wages and pensions months late, but
employers have been unable to break the cycle of debts that
continues to hobble the country's economy. Deputy Prime Minister
Valentina Matvienko said the government owed 18 billion rubles
(dlrs 850 million) of the overdue wages, while private companies
owed about 67 billion rubles (dlrs 3.2 billion), the ITAR-Tass news
agency reported. Russia's latest economic crisis, which hit in
August, has only made the problem worse. Many workers have lost
their jobs and the government continues to struggle to collect
taxes and pay its bills. (RUSSIA-ECONOMY)
</TEXT>
