<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Chechnya </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chechen officials delay release of slain foreigners
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Chechen officials on Tuesday delayed the return of
the remains of four Westerners killed earlier this month in the
breakaway Russian republic, news reports said.
	   Chechen leaders had said the severed heads would be delivered to
the British and New Zealand embassies in Moscow on Tuesday.
	   But the Chechens put off the action, saying there was a
``well-justified hope that the victims' bodies could be recovered
within the next few days,'' the Interfax news agency reported,
citing Chechen Prosecutor General Mansur Tagirov.
	   Tagirov said that the people with the corpses had been
contacted, but were demanding the release of one of their jailed
comrades before they give up the remains.
	   The victims _ Peter Kennedy, Darren Hickey, and Rudolf Petschi
of Britain and New Zealand's Stanley Shaw _ were abducted Oct. 3 in
the Chechen capital of Grozny, where they were installing a
cellular phone system.
	   Their heads were found by a roadside Dec. 8. Police say they
were killed after a rescue attempt went wrong.
	   Chechen officials have blamed the killings on a regional warlord
who has been accused of numerous kidnappings. But the warlord, Arbi
Barayev, has denied any involvement.
	   Chechnya has been plagued by violence and kidnappings for ransom
since its 1994-96 independence war against Russia. Abductions have
become a major business _ more than 100 people are thought to be in
captivity there, and ransom demands often run into the millions of
dollars.
	   Meanwhile, a 19-year old Russian soldier, kidnapped earlier this
month in neighboring Ingushetia, was freed by a Chechen anti-crime
squad, the ITAR-Tass news agency said Tuesday.
	   (vi/nw/gm) 	   
</TEXT>
