<HEADLINE>
Police arrest drug traffickers
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russian police arrested two suspected drug
traffickers carrying 300 kilograms (660 pounds) of marijuana
through central Russia, a news agency reported on Tuesday.
	   The suspects, from the former Soviet republic of Kazakstan, were
detained at a railway station in the Chelyabinsk region, 1,500
kilometers (950 miles) east of Moscow, the ITAR-Tass news agency
reported.
	   The report didn't say when the arrests took place.
	   Criminal proceedings have been launched against the suspects,
ITAR-Tass said, citing local police.
	   Russian has evolved into a major drug market since the 1991
Soviet collapse, with smugglers taking advantage of its economic
turmoil, widespread corruption and porous borders.
