<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Lithuania-Death Penalty,0199 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Lithuania abolishes death penalty
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   VILNIUS, Lithuania (AP) _ The Lithuanian parliament has
abolished the death penalty, a move that legislators hope will help
speed the country's entry into the European Union.
	   The vote Monday night in the Seimas parliament was 76-3, the
Baltic News Service reported.
	   The last execution in Lithuania was in 1995, when organized
crime boss Boris Dekanidze was killed with a single shot to the
head for ordering the assassination of a journalist.
	   Capital punishment has wide support among the public, with a
recent poll showing more than 80 percent of the respondents
favoring capital punishment.
	   But the EU, which Lithuania ardently wants to join, had said
that retaining capital punishment would be an obstacle to
membership.
	   This month, Lithuania's highest court put pressure on parliament
to change the law when it declared the death penalty
unconstitutional, saying it violated provisions against cruelty and
torture.
	   President Valdas Adamkus has also lobbied for the death penalty
to be scrapped.
	   Life imprisonment will be the maximum sentence a Lithuania court
can hand down.
</TEXT>
