<SLUG> BC-Egypt-Palestinians </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
First Palestinian airline arrives in Egypt
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ The first commercial Palestinian flight to
Egypt landed in Cairo's International Airport Tuesday, inaugurating
an air route between the autonomous Gaza Strip and Egypt, the
Middle East News Agency reported.
	   The Palestinian Airlines flight, which transported 14
passengers, was met by Egyptian Transportation Minister Suleiman
Metwally.
	   The inauguration of the route between Gaza and Cairo is a
``confirmation of Palestinian sovereignty over Palestinian lands,''
ports and airports, Metwally was quoted as saying by the Egyptian
news agency.
	   The Gaza airport was inaugurated in late November under the
U.S.-brokered Wye River accord which envisages Israel ceding more
lands to the Palestinians in return for security guarantees.
	   The Palestinian airlines already has a route from Gaza to the
Jordanian capital, Amman.
	   Last Friday, Egypt's national carrier, EgyptAir, inaugurated its
route to Gaza, the news agency said.
