w1366 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Cambodia-GarbageRiot 1stLd-Writethru   12-22 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Garbage Riot, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Protective clothing arrives for massive waste cleanup
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS and UPDATES throughout with Thais testing waste,
provide clothing, cleanup to take 10 days.
 &UR; By CHRIS FONTAINE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SIHANOUKVILLE, Cambodia (AP) _ Toxic waste experts from the Thai
army arrived in this seaport town Tuesday to help some 400
Cambodian troops clean up an illegal waste shipment from Taiwan.
	   A steady, two-hour rain dampened the 3,000 tons of waste,
believed to be compressed industrial ash, raising fear among
Environment Ministry officials that dangerous chemicals could seep
into ground water.
	   Plastic tarps that were supposed to have been stretched over the
waste to prevent such problems were not in place in time.
	   The experts from neighboring Thailand, including chemists and
nuclear technicians, passed Geiger counters over the waste, dumped
about 10 kilometers (six miles) north of Sihanoukville two weeks
ago, and determined it was not radioactive.
	   ``We have simply been requested to take samples and determine if
there is a health hazard,'' said Col. Chalermsuk Yugala. ``So far,
we have determined it is not radioactive. It could be toxic; it
could be nontoxic.''
	   Analysis by a Hong Kong laboratory has already shown the waste
contains mercury, a highly poisonous metal.
	   Deputy Prime Minister Sar Kheng said that he believed the hazard
from the waste was limited. Several officials involved in the
shipment have been suspended, he said. A cleanup involving hundreds
of soldiers and expected to last 10 days was to start Wednesday.
	   ``We will try to ship it out as soon as possible,'' Sar Kheng
said. ``We cannot let one or two people destroy the people's
health.''
	   Hundreds of residents fled to safer areas Tuesday, frightened of
health hazards and the violent rioting over the weekend against
corrupt officials who allowed the waste to enter the country. The
village closest to the dump site was deserted.
	   Police confirmed that four people were killed in road accidents
Monday when more than 1,000 people fled Sihanoukville, bringing
total deaths in connection to the waste shipment to five.
	   A dock worker died a day after cleaning the hold of the ship
that brought the waste about two weeks ago.
	   In Taiwan, the Environmental Protection Bureau said the waste
had been properly treated. The bureau said it was willing to send a
team to Cambodia to investigate. If the investigation showed the
hazards were caused by the Taiwanese waste, the bureau said it
would ask the company that produced it, Formosa Plastic Corp., to
take the waste back.
	   Thailand sent 300 protective suits, 300 gas masks and 100 pairs
of rubber boots to Cambodia to equip local soldiers for the cleanup
process.
	   Prince Norodom Ranariddh, president of the National Assembly,
said that he had been informed by Prime Minister Hun Sen that dlrs
3 million had been paid in bribes to officials to get the waste
into the country. The government has vowed to prosecute them.
	   All seats on buses leaving for the capital, Phnom Penh, 185
kilometers (115 miles) to the north, were fully booked, agents
said.
	   In Phnom Penh, a tourism official said that the presence of the
waste and the riots was hurting Sihanoukville's economy. The town
is a popular holiday spot.
	   ``It is regrettable,'' said Thong Khon, secretary of state at
the Tourism Ministry. ``This problem should not have been allowed
to happen.'' 	   
</TEXT>
