<SLUG> BC-Kenya-Sendashonga </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Judge sets Sendashonga murder trial for Feb. 4
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) _ A judge has set Feb. 4 as the opening date
in the trial of three suspects in the murder of former Rwandan
government minister Seth Sendashonga, news reports said Tuesday.
	   Judge Daniel Aganyanya set the date Monday after the three
suspects pleaded innocent to gunning down the former Rwandan
Interior Minister and his driver in Nairobi May 16, the East
African Standard said.
	   Okiki Kiwanuka of Rwanda, Charles Muhanji Wamuthoni of Kenya and
Christopher Lubanga Mlondo of Uganda have been in police custody
since their arrest May 20.
	   They are not eligible for bail because murder is a capital
offense in Kenya.
	   Sendashonga, a Hutu, was a member of the predominantly Tutsi
Rwandan Patriotic Front that ousted a Hutu extremist government in
Rwanda in July 1994 after it carried out a three-month slaughter of
at least 500,000 people, mostly of them minority Tutsis.
	   Sendashonga and several other government officials were
dismissed from their posts in August 1995 after they protested the
reprisal killings of Hutu civilians by Tutsi soldiers.
	   Sendashonga had been living in exile in Kenya where his wife
works for the United Nations Environment Program.
	   (gm/sl)	   
</TEXT>
