<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Balloon Quest, 7th Ld </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
China tells balloon to land, but organizers say that's unsafe
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: UPDATES with comment from project director &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ China ordered a round-the-world balloon expedition
to land Tuesday, expedition organizers said, but they protested
that they didn't dare because of darkness, cloud cover and the
rugged terrain.
	   ``Impossible _ landing in that area is life-threatening,'' said
project director Mike Kendrick in London, after the balloon team
disclosed the Chinese decision.
	   The ICO Global balloon was over Tibet, 50 miles (80 kms) north
of Bhutan at about 1100 GMT, according to Press Association, the
British news agency.
	   Earlier, the Chinese Foreign Ministry said it regretted that
British tycoon Richard Branson, American millionaire Steve Fossett
and Per Lindstrand of Sweden did not abide by an earlier agreement
to fly over southernmost China below 26 degrees north latitude.
	   ``They are stuck in a balloon, they cannot land it at this
particular time,'' Kendrick said in an interview with Sky News.
``There is absolutely nothing we can do but appeal to the Chinese
people for their understanding and their help, and to apologize
profusely.''
	   Kendrick said the balloonists were trying to move south into the
authorized corridor, but the wind was against them. ``I don't think
there is any chance we can make our way south,'' he said.
	   Foreign Ministry, graf 5
	   (rb)
