<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-US </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian ambassador to return to U.S. on Wednesday
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russia's ambassador to the United States, who was
recalled last week after America began bombing Iraq, will return to
Washington on Wednesday, an official said.
	   The Russians strongly opposed the U.S. and British air strikes
against Iraq, and recalled ambassadors from both countries. But the
Russians said Tuesday that Ambassador Yuli Vorontsov would return
to his post in Washington a day later.
	   ``The complication of Russian-U.S. relations was not our
choice,'' Russian Foreign Ministry spokesman Vladimir Rakhmanin
told a news conference.
	   ``Now that the United States has stopped using force against
Iraq ... the process of settling the situation in Iraq by political
methods should be restored fully,'' he added.
	   Russia has long opposed the use of force against Iraq, and said
the air strikes only complicated any settlement in the long-running
confrontation between the Arab nation and United Nations over
weapons inspections.
	   In recalling its ambassador, Russia denounced the United States
in harsh rhetoric reminiscent of the Cold War.
	   But Russia said Tuesday that a planned visit next month by U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright ``will be important for
overcoming the negative consequences of the U.S. use of force
against Iraq,'' Rakhmanin said.
	   The Russians were still holding discussions with Great Britain
about the return of Moscow's ambassador to London, Rakhmanin said.
	   The Russians have long-standing relations with Iraq and want to
help rebuild the country's oil industry when U.N. sanctions are
lifted.
	   The sanctions were imposed following Iraq's 1990 invasion of
Kuwait and are to remain in place until U.N. inspectors verify that
all weapons of mass destruction have been dismantled.
	   The United States and Britain launched their air strike
following a U.N. report saying Iraq had refused to cooperate with
weapons inspectors.
	   (gm/nw) 	   
</TEXT>
