<HEADLINE>
Former consul charged over dlrs 100 million deception
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   GENEVA (AP) _ The former honorary consul of Paraguay in Geneva,
Gustavo Gramont Beres, appeared in court in the city Tuesday on
charges of a dlrs 100 million fraud.
	   Beres, who had been charged for other offenses in Paraguay, was
extradited to Switzerland on the request of Geneva authorities,
said investigating magistrate Leonardo Malfanti.
	   Beres, an Argentine national, was the Paraguayan honorary consul
in Geneva from 1979 to 1989.
	   City authorities began an inquiry into Beres last year, and made
an official request for his extradition in February.
	   After a brief court appearance, Beres was detained in prison
pending his trial. The charges relate to deception and forgery to
the tune of around dlrs 100 million in Swiss francs and German
marks, according to Geneva magistrate Malfanti. He gave no more
details.
