w1402 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sudan-Relief     12-22 0453
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sudan-Relief </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Aid agencies warn famine could resume crisis proportions
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) _ Famine, fighting and flooding still
threaten more than 4 million people in Sudan, creating a bleak
outlook for 1999 despite improvements reported since the crisis
earlier this year, Operation Lifeline Sudan warned Tuesday.
	   In its annual needs assessment report, the umbrella body for
United Nations and other relief agencies operating in war-torn
southern Sudan said international response to famine this year
succeeded in alleviating conditions in the western Bahr el-Ghazal
region.
	   However, warning that the situation could easily revert to acute
famine, the report called for an extension of a humanitarian
cease-fire implemented in August and extended to Jan. 15, 1999.
	   ``Many people are surviving on a fragile base which insecurity
could easily shatter,'' Philippe Borel, OLS director and
coordinator for U.N. operations in Sudan, said in a statement.
	   Borel is based in the Sudanese capital, Khartoum.
	   ``Even a few weeks of insecurity, especially in Bahr el-Ghazal,
could produce the kind of crisis we were confronting earlier this
year,'' Borel said.
	   The 15-year civil war for control of southern Sudan, in which an
estimated 1.9 million people have died, many of them from
war-related famine, has caused millions more to flee their homes.
Crops left untended have been looted or destroyed, leaving people
without food.
	   In February, the government in the Arab, Islamic north banned
relief flights to rebel-held areas in the south for two months. The
ban, together with the worst flooding in 50 years, pushed millions
to the brink of starvation.
	   Rebels from the mainly African, Christian and animist south are
fighting government forces for self-determination for the region.
	   Global pressure forced the Khartoum government to lift the
flight ban in April, allowing the world's largest current relief
operation to commence.
	   The U.N. World Food Program estimates that it will have to
supply at least 150,000 tons of food until October 1999 in order to
feed 2 million people still in need in Sudan.
	   ``Although there has been improvement, it's still going to be a
grim year ahead for those recovering from the 1998 crisis,'' said
WFP spokeswoman Lindsey Davies.
	   ``That's why we will continue to pour in food, not only so that
the very weak can continue to survive, but so others can start to
recover. It's still a long way off.''
	   To help in the recovery, relief agencies are planning to
distribute seeds and tools to more than 300,000 households and
fishing equipment to about 120,000 households in rebel-held areas,
OLS said.
	   (dmc/sl)	   
</TEXT>
