<SLUG> BC-Russia-Yeltsin, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Parliament expected to vote on Yeltsin impeachment next month
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDs: LEADS with impeachment motion to come up next month, ADDS
byline.
 &UR; By NICK WADHAMS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russian lawmakers are expected to vote next month
on whether to impeach President Boris Yeltsin, the speaker of
parliament said Tuesday. At present, the impeachment motion appears
likely to fail.
	   Parliament's impeachment committee has already said that Yeltsin
should be removed from office for launching Russia's botched war in
Chechnya, sending in tanks against his hard-line foes in 1993,
instigating the collapse of the Soviet Union, and neglecting
Russia's military.
	   The committee must still decide on a motion that accuses Yeltsin
of waging genocide against the Russian people.
	   Gennady Seleznyov, the speaker of the lower house, or State
Duma, said the committee has almost completed its work and will
send the impeachment motion to the full house in January for a
vote.
	   Yeltsin foes say enough evidence had been presented already to
impeach the president.
	   ``The lower house of the U.S. Congress brought an impeachment
motion against President Clinton only because he told a lie,''
Communist leader Gennady Zyuganov told the Interfax news agency.
``But if you collect everything that Yeltsin lied about, two train
loads would not be enough to carry it.''
	   To be approved, the impeachment motion must win a two-thirds
majority in the lower house, which is considered unlikely. If it
passes that hurdle, the motion must also pass through the
Constitutional and Supreme Courts and then win passage in the upper
house of parliament.
	   Only then would Yeltsin be removed from office.
	   Meanwhile, Yeltsin gave a tongue lashing to Russia's top
policeman Tuesday, saying he had failed to stop the falsification
of crime statistics, a new report said.
	   Some police figures indicate that Russia's high crime rate has
gone down a bit in the last few years, but Yeltsin said his data
showed the opposite.
	   ``And you tell me everything is fine,'' Yeltsin told Interior
Minister Sergei Stepashin at the Kremlin meeting, according to the
Interfax news agency.
	   ``I treat you with trust and respect,'' Yeltsin said. ``I judge
your work by its results. But God forbid that you should
overestimate yourself a little bit or relax.''
	   Stepashin, who is responsible for the police force, has
acknowledged that police falsified crime figures to earn perks and
make themselves look good. But he promised Yeltsin that statistics
would no longer get any ``window-dressing.''
	   Yeltsin has been sidelined by a string of illnesses, but said
stopping crime remained one of his top priorities.
	   The president also presented state awards to a number of
prominent Russians, including Mikhail Kalashnikov, the designer of
the famous AK-47 assault rifle, and Valentin Vlasov, the
presidential envoy to Chechnya who was freed Nov. 13 after six
months of captivity.
	   Yeltsin was recently hospitalized for two weeks to recover from
pneumonia. He was released about two weeks ago, and has been
holding regular meetings since then.
	   (pvs/vl/nw) 	   
</TEXT>
