r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Israel-Christmas     12-22 0300
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Christmas,0299 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
In Christmas message, Latin patriarch decries threats to peace
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ In a somber Christmas message, the Latin
patriarch of Jerusalem said Tuesday that the cause of peace has
been hurt by Israeli-Palestinian strife and conflict in Iraq.
	   In the Christmas season, ``the whole world ... turns its gaze
toward our land and our holy cities with the hope of finding in
them the grace of God which can renew persons and societies,'' said
Michel Sabbah, the top Roman Catholic clergyman in the region.
	   Dressed in a long black robe with a large silver cross around
his neck, Sabbah, a Palestinian, mourned what he said were setbacks
in efforts to bring about peace between Israel and the
Palestinians.
	   ``The peace process remains paralyzed, despite big efforts in
recent days to bring it back to life,'' the patriarch said in his
message. ``The Israeli vision remains too narrow to welcome
Palestinian freedom.''
	   Sabbah also said he hoped the international community would take
steps to try to ease the suffering of the Iraqi people. Four days
of U.S. and British airstrikes on suspected weapons sites last week
killed at least 62 Iraqis and injured 180.
	   ``We hope that the grace of Christmas may enlighten their minds
and hearts and help them find other ways to resolve the conflict
without imposing death on the people,'' he said.
	   The patriarch also called for reconciliation between Muslims and
Christians in the largely Arab city of Nazareth, in northern
Israel, where tensions have increased in recent weeks between the
two communities.
	   Sabbah, quoting the biblical book of James, urged meditation on
the mystery of God, ``the father of all light, from whom comes all
that is good, all that is perfect.''
</TEXT>
