<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Plane Crash </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Thai Airways denies impact of air crash on its share prices
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By THAKSINA KHAIKAEW &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ Despite the recent crash of a Thai
Airways jetliner that killed 101 people, airline officials asserted
Tuesday that confidence by customers and shareholders remains
undented.
	   Airline officials said at the first shareholders' meeting since
the crash Dec. 11 that safety was Thai Airways' top concern.
	   ``The crash has not affected the share price,'' Mahidol
Chantragkurn, the chairman of the board, told a news conference
after the meeting. ``Shareholders have confidence in the company
and people understand that accidents such as this do not occur
often.''
	   Though Thailand is obliged to privatize the airline under an
economic bailout package supervised by the International Monetary
Fund, Thai Airways remains 93 percent-owned by the government.
	   On Dec. 9, the last day of trading before the crash, the share
price was 45.25 baht (dlrs 1.29). After reaching a low of 41.25
(dlrs 1.17) Dec. 16, it has regained value and closed Tuesday at
45.50 (dlrs 1.30).
	   The plane crashed in heavy rains during a night-time landing
approach at the airport in the southern city of Surat Thani.
	   The pilot, who was killed, has been criticized for making a
third attempt to land even though during the first two he had
difficulty in seeing the runway.
	   The airport has come under criticism for lacking an instrumental
landing system, which helps guide a plane in for landing.
	   The crash has raised questions about whether the airline, which
has had to cut costs as Thailand suffers its worst recession in
decades, has cut too far back and affected safety.
	   Mahidol denied it.
	   ``Thai Airways continues to set safety as its first priority,
even though we are on belt-tightening measures,'' he said. ``The
shareholders are worried about delays in dividends, not the crash's
implications.''
	   Shareholders have agreed to a postponement in dividends because
of the negative impact on earnings of foreign exchange losses,
Mahidol said.
	   Thamnoon Wanglee, president of the airline, said the company has
already paid 79.2 million baht (dlrs 2.2 million) in compensation
for 22 of those killed and 6.8 million baht (dlrs 187,000) for 34
injured.
	   Voice and flight data recorders will be sent to Canada or other
third countries for analysis, said Air Marshal Anek Phusuwan,
deputy chief of the staff of the Royal Thai Air Force.
	   Analysis should be completed in two weeks, Anek said, and the
cause of the crash would be officially disclosed. 	   
</TEXT>
