r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Croatia-Sports-Tennis     12-22 0346
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Croatia-Sports-Tennis-Ivanisevic </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Goran Ivanisevic's father and his opponent convicted of slander
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ZAGREB, Croatia (AP) _ The father of Croatian tennis star Goran
Ivanisevic and the head of the national tennis association were
found guilty of slandering each other, Croatian media reported
Tuesday.
	   A Zagreb district court on Monday convicted both Srdjan
Ivanisevic and Suad Rizvanbegovic to 30-day prison terms or
one-year suspended sentences for insulting and slandering the
other, Jutarnji list daily reported.
	   For more than a year, the elder Ivanisevic and Rizvanbegovic
have been engaged in a row for a year over who should control
Croatian tennis.
	   The quarrel went so far that Goran Ivanisevic stopped playing
Davis Cup tennis tours for his country, demanding Rizvanbegovic
vacate the top post in Croatia's Tennis Association.
	   He even appealed to President Franjo Tudjman _ an avid tennis
player and fan _ to intervene. But Tudjman apparently chose instead
to back Rizvanbegovic, who is often seen in his company.
	   Following the spat, Srdjan Ivanisevic closed the Croatian
Indoors tour he previously owned. Boris Becker and other famous
players participated in the tournament when it existed.
	   Ivanisevic and Rizvanbegovic both spoke to the press regarding
the quarrel and subsequently sued each other for slander.
	   Rizvanbegovic said he was offended by an interview Ivanisevic
gave to independent Globus weekly in February, in which he accused
Rizvanbegovic of ``buying'' his position with someone else's money
and not being a true Croat, as he arrived only in 1996.
	   Rizvanbegovic, who also is a head of the country's biggest
insurance company, said that the sentence was ``inappropriate.''
	   Ivanisevic, for his part, sued Rizvanbegovic over his claim that
Ivanisevic formed a pro-Yugoslav party in interviews he gave to
Vjesnik and Vecernji list dailies.
	   Croatia proclaimed independence from the former Yugoslavia in
1991, triggering a six-month war with minority Serbs in the
country.
	   (dl/sv/me) 	   
</TEXT>
