w1437 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Japan-USMilitary     12-22 0315
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-US Military </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. returns military drill ground to Okinawa
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The U.S. armed forces handed back a drill ground in
Okinawa on Tuesday as part of an agreement to reduce the American
military presence on the southern Japanese island, an official
said.
	   The Aha drill site _ comprising 480 hectares (1,186 acres) of
land and 7,900 hectares (19,513 acres) of water _ is the first of
11 U.S. facilities that will revert to Japan under a 1996 deal,
said regional defense official Kenji Fujimoto.
	   The United States has promised to eventually give back 20
percent of the territory in Okinawa occupied by U.S. troops.
	   Marines have been using the Aha facility in northern Okinawa for
small-unit training, including exercises in amphibious landings and
setting up command posts. It lies within the larger Northern
Training area, which Japan has agreed to extend by 37 hectares (93
acres) of land and 119 hectares (300 acres) of water to allow
Marines to continue practicing amphibious landings.
	   Chief Cabinet Secretary Hiromu Nonaka was quoted by Kyodo News
as saying the handover was ``very significant'' because it
symbolizes progress in efforts to scale back the U.S. military
presence in Okinawa.
	   ``The government will continue working toward the reorganization
and reduction of the military facilities... to lessen the burden on
Okinawa,'' the top government spokesman told a press briefing.
	   Two-thirds of the 47,000 U.S. troops stationed in Japan are
concentrated on the island, about 1,600 kilometers (1,000 miles)
southwest of Tokyo, even though it accounts for less than 1 percent
of Japan's total land area.
	   The U.S. military presence has long rankled Okinawa residents,
who have been angered in recent years by a string of violent crimes
_ including the rape of a 12-year-old girl _ committed by Marines
stationed on the island.	   
</TEXT>
