w1439 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Romania-OilDeal     12-22 0235
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Romania-Oil Deal </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
French oil company Elf Aquitaine invests in Black Sea drilling
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BUCHAREST, Romania (AP) _ France's oil giant Elf Aquitaine
signed an agreement Tuesday with Romania's national oil company
Petrom for oil exploration and drilling in the Black Sea.
	   ``This is another important step in Romanian-French bilateral
relations,'' said Radu Berceanu, Romanian trade and industry
minister.
	   It was the second important French investment here in the last
month. Societe Generale paid dlrs 200 million for a 51 percent
stake in the Romanian Development Bank. French auto manufacturer
Renault is in negotiations to buy the Romanian Dacia car maker.
	   Under the oil contract, Elf and Petrom will explore a surface of
10,000 sq. kilometers (4,000 sq. miles) in Black Sea for the next
30 years.
	   Elf will initially pay dlrs 10 million, and if they find oil,
they will pay up to dlrs 500 million for development projects, said
Anca Turcea, a spokeswoman for the Romanian trade and industry
ministry.
	   Elf is one of the world's foremost oil companies which
specializes in deep sea drilling. Romania, once the richest oil
country in the Balkans, has not explored the Black Sea, lacking the
necessary equipment.
	   Petrom extracted in 1998 almost 6 million tons of crude oil all
over the country and exported dlrs 150 million worth of oil.
	   (ma/am/rr)
</TEXT>
