w1441 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Russia-Economy 2ndLd-Writethru   12-22 0500
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Economy, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian Communists plan to give quick approval to budget
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDs: NEW 7th graf with additional Zyuganov quote. CORRECTS grafs 10
to note that wages debts are to state workers, and does not include
private sector. &QL; 
 &UR; By GREG MYRE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Communist leader Gennady Zyuganov said Tuesday he
wasn't entirely pleased with the 1999 budget, but his party would
probably support quick passage because of the country's financial
turmoil.
	   ``We have a difficult choice between bad and very bad because
the present government has inherited from its predecessors only
debts and troubles, but no resources,'' Zyuganov told Russian news
agencies.
	   An austere, realistic budget is seen as essential for
stabilizing Russia's economy. The lower house of parliament, the
State Duma, is to begin discussing the draft budget Thursday, and
passage has required months of rancorous debate in recent years.
	   But the Communists, the largest faction in parliament, have been
generally supportive of Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov's
government, raising hopes that the budget will win swift approval.
	   ``The budget, it appears, should be passed on the first
reading,'' Zyuganov said.
	   The Duma must approve the budget in four readings, and then it
goes to the upper house, which usually passes it with little delay.
	   The Communists have regularly called for more state spending to
help impoverished individuals and ailing industries. Zyuganov also
said he wanted to see more money for the military, education and
culture.
	   But in the current economic crisis there's broad agreement that
the government simply doesn't have much money to spend.
	   Russia's overall economy is expected to shrink about 5 percent
this year and could be even worse next year. The International
Monetary Fund has forecast a decline of 8.3 percent next year for
Russia, which has seen its economy contract most of this decade.
	   Meanwhile, wage debts to state workers stand at 84.9 billion
rubles (dlrs 4 billion), said Deputy Prime Minister Valentina
Matvienko.
	   Millions of Russians receive their wages and pensions months
late, creating a cycle of debts that continues to hobble the
economy.
	   The government's debt to pensioners now stands at 30 billion
rubles (dlrs 1.4 billion) and overdue subsidies to families with
children is currently at 24 billion rubles (dlrs 1.1 billion).
	   ``We should do all we can not to allow children to go hungry,''
Matvienko said. ``In each such case, the local authorities should
take urgent measures.''
	   Russia is to receive food aid from the United States and Europe
this winter to guard against potential food shortages. So far, no
serious food problems have been reported.
	   The government will sell some of the food aid on the Russian
market, and the money will be used to pay pension arrears, Deputy
Prime Minister Gennady Kulik told a news conference Tuesday.
	   (gm/nw) 	   
</TEXT>
