w1447 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Russia-India-China     12-22 0343
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-India-China </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian Communists call for defense union with India, China
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russian Communist leaders called Tuesday for a
defense partnership with India and China to offset what they
perceive as the military dominance of the United States, a news
report said.
	   The recent U.S. and British bombings of Iraq showed ``what may
happen if (American) policies are disliked overseas,'' Communist
Party leader Gennady Zyuganov said, according to the Interfax news
agency.
	   The proposal for a ``strategic triangle'' between Russia, India
and China was first made by Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov
during his trip to India this week. India and China are leading
buyers of Russian arms.
	   Russia, China and India all opposed the use of force against
Iraq to make Saddam Hussein comply with the U.N. weapons
inspectors. Russian hard-liners claimed that the West may some day
attack Russia.
	   Gennady Seleznyov, a Communist who serves as speaker of the
lower house of Russia's parliament, supported Zyuganov's call.
	   ``Tomorrow any country whose president or position is opposed by
the masters of the world may become a target of violence,''
Seleznyov was quoted as saying Tuesday during a visit to
Yugoslavia.
	   Seleznyov met with Mira Markovic _ the hard-line communist wife
of Serbia's authoritarian president Slobodan Milosevic _ and the
two condemned the bombings of Iraq, Interfax reported.
	   Markovic was quoted as saying that ``the three historically
great nations _ Russia, India and China _ are capable of assuming
responsibility for the future of the world.''
	   Separately, Russian Deputy Trade Minister Igor Mitrofanov
claimed Tuesday that India and China may buy up to 200 Russian
military aircraft over the next two years. That would bring Russia
between dlrs 8 billion and 10 billion, Interfax reported.
	   Mitrofanov didn't provide any details. An agreement on that
scale would be far in excess of any previous aircraft deals between
the countries.
	   (ad/nw/gm) 	   
</TEXT>
