<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Spain-Christmas Lottery, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Christmas lottery distributes massive winnings in Spain
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS to CORRECT and CLARIFY top prizes total 42 billion
pesetas; UPDATES with quotes from lucky ticket holders &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos Available &QL; 
 &UR; By CIARAN GILES &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MADRID, Spain (AP) _ Christmas festivities got off to a jubilant
start for dozens of retirees in the southeastern town of La Union
who had shares in the total top prize of 42 billion (dlrs 300
million) in Spain's Christmas lottery, _ billed as the world's
richest.
	   News reports said champagne corks were poppping at The
Penioners' Home as residents and neighbors celebrated the club's
win of 3 billion pesetas (dlrs 21 million) after buying 10 of the
140 winning series 21856, each worth 300 million pesetas (dlrs 2.1
million)
	   The lottery, which began in 1818, comprises of number series
split into 140 tickets which are valued at 30,000 pesetas (dlrs
2,100) each. The tickets are subsequently divided into 10 shares
worth 3,000 pesetas (dlrs 21) each and are then often subdivided
into smaller parts.
	   Known as ``El Gordo'' (The Fat One), the lottery dished out a
total of 194 billion pesetas (dlrs 1.4 billion) in winnings this
year to thousands of ticket holders throughout the country.
	   It was not immediately clear exactly how many people in the
pensioners's home had won. Prizes were estimated to range from 1.6
million pesetas (drls 10,000) to 30 million pesetas (dlrs 210,000).
	   ``Let's say I won't be able to run wild with it, but I'll be
able to keep my head high'' Carmen Hernandez, a neighbor of the
club, told the private news agency Europa Press.
	   She said her winnings, which she declined to quantify, would
help get medical treatment for her husband, who suffers from an
unspecified illness.
	   Also lucky was Juan Gomez, a 54-year-old unemployed father of
four who was entitled to 10 million pesetas (dlrs 70,000) after
buying two shares of 500 pesetas (dlrs 3.5) each in what is the
most popular lottery of the year in Spain.
	   ''Now I'll be able to pay off the mortgage and help out my
sons,'' Gomez, who lives in the northeastern town of Sabadell, told
reporters. The national news agency Efe said three of Gomez's sons
were unemployed and a fourth was a student.
	   Shares of the winning number series, 21856, were sold in six
towns across Spain.
	   Each year, millions of television viewers watch as children from
a school in Madrid pick out numbered balls from drums and sing out
the winning number in a ceremony that lasts some four.
	   The second prize of 144 million pesetas (dlrs 1 million) went to
the each of the 140 series numbered 07308.
	   Most Spaniards share tickets with family members, friends and
coworkers, so lottery windfalls ripple through whole communities.
	   Financial pressures were also certain to be easier for
66-year-old street tobacco seller Miguel Trillo who news reports
said planned to use the 30 million pesetas (dlrs 210,000) he'd won
``to pay off debts and share with my daughters.''
	   ``Nobody pays any attention to you when you're broke,'' Efe
cited Trillo as telling journalists in a cafe in the southern port
city of Malaga where he lives.
	   Income from ticket sales was 250 billion pesetas (dlrs 1.8
billion) this year, 8.9 percent up on last year, according to the
State Lottery Department.
	   The Spanish Treasury hives off 30 percent of the total raised
before the draw takes place to keep the winnings tax free.
	   (cg) 	   
</TEXT>
