<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Railway Threats </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bomb threats add to scare at German railways
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By GEORGE BOEHMER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) _ Amid jitters about a blackmail attempt
against the German railway, police arrested a man Tuesday for
threatening to blow up a train station.
	   The 44-year-old unemployed man was nabbed shortly after calling
the city fire department saying he would blow up the station in
Fulda, 90 kilometers northeast (55 miles) northeast of Frankfurt.
No bomb was found.
	   Authorities said there was no apparent link to a series of
attacks on rail lines this month linked to extortionists. The
sabotage has prompted overflights by air force reconnaissance
planes equipped with high-performance cameras. Helicopters and 400
border police and are also patrolling rail lines.
	   With Deutsche Bahn railways and travelers alike unsettled,
officials revaled more measures to protect trains Tuesday.
	   Rudi Schaefer, head of the rail workers' union, said on ARD
television that federal border police with night vision equipment
are accompanying trains after dark to help detect any sabotage.
	   Manfred Schell, chairman of the railway engineers union, said
empty trains were being sent out to check main lines before dawn
before the day's passengers traffic starts.
	   The checks center on the northeast of the country, where recent
sabotage has taken place.
	   Federal criminal investigators on Tuesday linked three attacks
to extortionists who the national railways say have demanded 10
million marks (dlrs 6 million) in several ransom letters.
	   In the most serious incident, a cargo train carrying paper rolls
derailed Friday near Anklam, 160 kilometers (100 miles) north of
Berlin, after someone loosened bolts holding down the tracks. No
one was hurt.
	   Bild newspaper reported the special tools used were believed
stolen from the railway in Brandenburg, but officials declined to
confirm that.
	   Also linked to the blackmailers was a similar attack that forced
a high-speed ICE train enroute from Hannover to Berlin into an
emergency stop on Dec. 8.
	   Transport Minister Franz Muentefering has said the government
will spare no ``personnel, energy, money or technology'' to solve
the extortion case.
	   But railway unions have criticized company management, saying
they kept employees in the dark too long about the threat.
 &UR; (gb-tc)
</TEXT>
