w1469 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Eritrea-Ethiopia     12-22 0343
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Eritrea-Ethiopia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Eritrea: chances for peaceful settlement not exhausted
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; RETRANSMITTING TO FIX SLUG &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   ASMARA, Eritrea (AP) _ Chances for a peaceful settlement to the
seven-month Eritrea-Ethiopian border conflict have not been
exhausted despite a recent and inconclusive OAU summit, a senior
Eritrean official has said.
	   Speaking to reporters late Monday, Foreign Minister Haile
Weldensae the conflict resolution organ of the Organization of
African Unity had only five hours at its meeting last weekend in
Ouagadougou, Burkina Faso to discuss half a dozen conflicts in
Africa.
	   But he said a high-level OAU team made up of representatives
from Zimbabwe, Burkina Faso and Djibouti would continue to work
toward a negotiated settlement to the conflict after drafting a
peace plan in early November.
	   Horn of Africa neighbors Eritrea and Ethiopia clashed in May and
June over undemarcated colonial boundaries, and hundreds were
killed.
	   Thousands of troops are hunkered down on either side of their
common 1,000-kilometer (620-mile) border, and period shelling and
massive weapons buildups keep tensions high.
	   Ethiopia accepted the OAU peace plan, but Eritrea objected to
several points, particularly the one that called for a unilateral
withdrawal of Eritrean troops from the contested Badime area and
the return of Ethiopian administrators.
	   Eritrea's counterproposal, presented to the OAU team two days
before the Dec. 17 summit, called for:
	   _ precise legal language related to border delineation;
	   _ mutual demilitarization of the Mareb Setit border area;
	   _ deletion of the recommendation calling for the return of
Ethiopian administrators to the Badime area;
	   _ altering the paragraph on human rights issues to reflect that
Ethiopia is deporting ethnic Eritreans and not vice-versa.
	   Weldensae said U.S. special envoy Anthony Lake was expected back
in the region for another round of talks with Eritrean and
Ethiopian officials but he did not know the dates of his next
shuttle mission.
	   (js/sl)	   
</TEXT>
