w1471 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Russia-Treason     12-22 0271
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Treason </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian journalist accused of treason to run for city council
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ A Russian military reporter charged with passing
secrets about Russia's navy to Japanese media is running for city
council in the Far Eastern port of Vladivostok, an official said
Tuesday.
	   Capt. Grigory Pasko is in jail in Vladivostok on charges of high
treason for allegedly giving out classified information about the
combat readiness of the Russian Pacific Fleet.
	   Pasko, a reporter for the military newspaper Boevaya Vakhta, or
Combat Vigil, maintains that the documents only detailed
environmental problems at several Russian naval bases.
	   He registered to run in the Jan. 17 election for the Vladivostok
legislature, and the electoral commission has approved his
candidacy, commission chairman Ilya Grinchenko said Tuesday,
according to the ITAR-Tass news agency. About 140 candidates are
expected to compete for 22 city council seats.
	   Pasko's aide Sergei Ivanchenko said the campaign was aimed at
drawing attention to Pasko's case and helping obtain his released
from pre-trial detention, among other things, ITAR-Tass reported.
	   Pasko has been in jail since his arrest in November 1997. His
trial, postponed in October, is now expected to begin in
mid-January.
	   Pasko's case has drawn the attention of Russian and
international human rights organizations and journalist groups.
	   The Committee to Protect Journalists, based in New York, has
said it ``strongly protests the arrest and criminal prosecution of
Grigory Pasko for practicing his profession.''
	   (ad/adc)
</TEXT>
