w1474 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Africa-Briefs     12-22 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Africa-Briefs </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
on South Africa, Angola-Zimbabwe, Eritrea-Ethiopia, Rwanda
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Some items may have already moved separately; contains items
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   --
	   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) _ The world's biggest platinum
producer, Anglo American Platinum Corp., or Amplats, warned that
wage and conditions of employment talks with the National Union of
Mineworkers had reached deadlock and that a strike could begin
Wednesday.
	   ``Amplats is considering various courses of action and
discussions with the NUM are continuing,'' the company said in a
statement to the Johannesburg Stock Exchange.
	   Amplats said an NUM-led work stoppage occurred at its Lebowa
Platinum Mines division on Sunday. At issue was the use of
lightweight underground drilling equipment, but the dispute had
been ``settled through mutual agreement,'' Amplats said.
	   Steve Calladine, an Amplats spokesman, said he was confident an
agreement would be reached, heading off a strike and possible
disruption to platinum output.
	   --
	   CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) _ Students and teachers infected
with the AIDS virus must be allowed to attend school and keep their
jobs, an education department spokesman said on Tuesday.
	   Though South Africa's constitution already defends such rights,
the government has recently drawn up policy protecting the 3
million South Africans with the HIV virus or AIDS from being
discriminated against in education.
	   ``This is a national policy to protect the rights of individuals
with AIDS,'' Bheki Khumalo said.
	   South Africa's AIDS epidemic is one of the fastest growing in
Africa, and every day 1,500 South Africans are infected. Sufferers
often become outcasts in society and lose their jobs.
	   The policy document concludes there is an ``insignificant risk''
of spreading the disease in schools and universities. It also
prohibits mandatory testing for pupils and teachers and AIDS
sufferers cannot be forced to disclose they have the virus.
	   ``Learners and students with HIV/AIDS should lead as full a life
as possible and should not be denied the opportunity to receive an
education,'' it said.
	   Where students are too ill to travel to classes, they should be
allowed to study at home, the document recommends.
	   --
	   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) _ The Defense Ministry in Harare denied
claims Zimbabwe sent troops to back government forces fighting
rebels in Angola, the state-controlled Herald newspaper reported
Tuesday.
	   Officials dismissed allegations that some Zimbabwean soldiers
serving in the Congo were redeployed to fight UNITA rebels, who
have mounted a renewed onslaught against the government of Angolan
President Jose Eduardo dos Santos, the newspaper said.
	   The allegations were made by Jonas Savimbi, leader of UNITA, the
Portuguese acronym for the National Union for the Total
Independence of Angola. Savimbi said Zimbabwean forces entered
Angola on Friday and were threatening an escalation of fighting.
	   Angolan troops are in a southern African alliance with Zimbabwe
and Namibia supporting embattled President Laurent Kabila in the
Congo.
	   The Herald, seen as a government mouthpiece, said Zimbabwe
President Robert Mugabe last week described Savimbi as a war
criminal who must be sought out and defeated.
	   ``This may have been misconstrued to mean that Zimbabwe will
hunt down Dr. Savimbi,'' the newspaper said, quoting unidentified
defense officials.
	   Zimbabwe has 8,000 troops backed by warplanes and armor in the
Congo.
	   --
	   ASMARA, Eritrea (AP) _ Chances for a peaceful settlement to the
seven-month Eritrea-Ethiopian border conflict have not been
exhausted despite a recent and inconclusive OAU summit, a senior
Eritrean official has said.
	   Speaking to reporters late Monday, Foreign Minister Haile
Weldensae the conflict resolution organ of the Organization of
African Unity had only five hours at its meeting last weekend in
Ouagadougou, Burkina Faso to discuss half a dozen conflicts in
Africa.
	   But he said a high-level OAU team made up of representatives
from Zimbabwe, Burkina Faso and Djibouti would continue to work
toward a negotiated settlement to the conflict after drafting a
peace plan in early November.
	   Horn of Africa neighbors Eritrea and Ethiopia clashed in May and
June over undemarcated colonial boundaries, and hundreds were
killed.
	   Thousands of troops are hunkered down on either side of their
common 1,000-kilometer (620-mile) border, and period shelling and
massive weapons buildups keep tensions high.
	   --
	   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) _ A judge has set Feb. 4 as the opening date
in the trial of three suspects in the murder of former Rwandan
government minister Seth Sendashonga, news reports said Tuesday.
	   Judge Daniel Aganyanya set the date Monday after the three
suspects pleaded innocent to gunning down the former Rwandan
Interior Minister and his driver in Nairobi May 16, the East
African Standard said.
	   Okiki Kiwanuka of Rwanda, Charles Muhanji Wamuthoni of Kenya and
Christopher Lubanga Mlondo of Uganda have been in police custody
since their arrest May 20.
	   They are not eligible for bail because murder is a capital
offense in Kenya.
	   Sendashonga, a Hutu, was a member of the predominantly Tutsi
Rwandan Patriotic Front that ousted a Hutu extremist government in
Rwanda in July 1994 after it carried out a three-month slaughter of
at least 500,000 people, mostly of them minority Tutsis.
	   Sendashonga and several other government officials were
dismissed from their posts in August 1995 after they protested the
reprisal killings of Hutu civilians by Tutsi soldiers.
	   Sendashonga had been living in exile in Kenya where his wife
works for the United Nations Environment Program.
	   (var/djw)	   
</TEXT>
