w1477 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Israel-Settlers     12-22 0307
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Settlers </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Staking land claim, Jewish settlers start new neighborhood
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Jewish settlers have begun work on a new
neighborhood at near the West Bank town of Jericho in hopes of
preventing the land from being ceded to the Palestinians.
	   Since the signing of the Wye River land-for-security accord two
months ago, settlers have increased the rate of both illegal and
legal building to try to block land transfers with so-called
``facts on the ground.''
	   Construction of the new neighborhood at the Mitzpeh Jericho
settlement of 200 families was approved by the defense ministry
several months ago and work began this week, said Eli Greenwald,
secretary of the local council.
	   ``If we can stop part of the implementation of the agreements,
we will have done a great thing for the state of Israel,''
Greenwald told The Associated Press on Tuesday.
	   Government permission to expand the settlement was granted even
though 10 percent of the homes in it are empty, the settlement
watchdog group Peace Now reported.
	   With the building of the 147 housing units in the new
neighborhood, Mitzpeh Jericho's population will double in size,
Greenwald said. The settlement has permission to build as many as
1,200 homes, which will be done over coming years, he said.
	   Settlers have placed mobile homes on nine new sites near
existing settlements since the Wye agreement, said Hagit Yaari,
spokeswoman for Peace Now.
	   Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's government has frozen
Israeli compliance with the Wye River accord, including land
handovers. But Israeli media say settlers' building is being
spurred by fears a new government might move to implement the pact.
	   Lawmakers on Monday overwhelmingly approved early elections,
which will probably be before the end of April.
 &UR; (lc-lk)
</TEXT>
