r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Greece-SchoolRoadbloc     12-22 0381
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Greece-School Roadblocks </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Protesting school children block roads across Greece
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With AP photos available &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   ATHENS, Greece (AP) _ High school children staged roadblocks on
highways and busy city streets across Greece Tuesday, stepping up
their two-month protest against education reforms.
	   The blockades crippled traffic in many parts of Athens and the
northern port city of Salonica and seriously disrupted road
transport elsewhere in the country.
	   The students, who are also occupying some 2,000 high schools,
are protesting against the reforms which introduce stricter marking
systems but will create more university places.
	   Education Minister Gerasimos Arsenis Tuesday insisted the new
measures would be enforced. But, in a concession to the protesters,
he said children in this school year would be given additional
opportunities to improve their grades.
	   ``This system is being enforced for the first time and has led
to some uncertainty, so we are prepared to takes steps to help the
students,'' Arsenis told a news conference.
	   The schools protest has added pressure on Premier Costas
Simitis' Socialist government, struggling to push through a wide
range on cost-cutting reforms this winter.
	   Most of these are part of Greece's attempt to qualify for the
European Union's single currency group by the end of next year. The
reforms have led to frequent strikes and mass demonstrations which
have made life unpleasant for motorists.
	   School children have staged daily rush-hour blockades of Athens'
main streets this month, demanding that the education reform law be
abolished altogether.
	   Teenagers Tuesday, chanting slogans and singing Christmas carols
with protest lyrics, came face-to-face with angry drivers but only
let ambulances and military vehicles through the roadblocks.
	   High blockades were staged outside Athens and other towns.
	   Near the central town of Larissa, school children blocked the
Athens-Salonica highway for several hours, clambering on to parked
tractors provided by disgruntled local farmers.
	   School protest groups voted Sunday to continue their campaign
into the next year, but the government is hoping the roadblocks and
school occupations will fizzle out over the Christmas holidays.
 &UR; dg
</TEXT>
