<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Confederations Cup, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Germany takes France's place in Confederations Cup
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ADDS more background &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   ZURICH, Switzerland (AP) _ Germany will take part in next year's
Confederations' Cup in Mexico following the withdrawal of World Cup
champions France, FIFA said Tuesday.
	   The tournament will take place July 24 to Aug. 4 _ four days
earlier than planned _ to accommodate the new team, soccer's
governing body said.
	   After weeks of debate over the schedule and to the anger of FIFA
and local organizers, France pulled out because of clashes with its
domestic and European obligations.
	   The French move reflected a feeling by many European squads that
the Confederations Cup is an unnecessary feature on an overcrowded
soccer calendar.
	   In addition to the world champion and host nation, FIFA invited
Australia, Bolivia, Brazil, Egypt, Saudi Arabia and the United
States to participate in the competition.
	   ``FIFA consulted the German Football Association who have now
confirmed their participation following France's definite
withdrawal,'' FIFA said in a statement. Germany was eligible as the
1996 European Champion, it said.
	   FIFA initially moved the eight-nation event from Jan. 8-20 to
July 28-Aug. 8 to placate France. The French soccer federation said
it accepted this, but then changed its mind because the French
national league begins its 1999-2000 championship on July 28.
	   France then asked for the competition to be moved to the start
of the summer.
	   But FIFA refused to bow to this request, not least because South
America's Copa Libertadores isn't scheduled to end until June 16,
and the Copa America begins June 29 and runs through July 8.
 &UR; (cn)
</TEXT>
