<SLUG> BC-Georgia-UN, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Investigation completed into murder of U.N. worker in Georgia
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES in graf 5 with hearings to begin Jan. 25. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TBILISI, Georgia (AP) _ Police have completed an investigation
into the shooting death of Polish woman who worked for the United
Nations in Georgia, and the case has been sent to court, an
official said Tuesday.
	   Maria Magdalena Wewiorska, 31, was shot at point-blank range on
July 14 when she apparently startled a burglar in her apartment in
central Tbilisi.
	   The suspect, 20-year-old Zurab Bregvadze of Georgia, was
arrested in August.
	   The case was sent to Tbilisi municipal court last Friday, and
hearings are expected to begin on Jan. 25, court official Irina
Dzhaparidze said.
	   Bregvadze, who lived near Wewiorska, was identified by neighbors
who reported seeing him run out of her house shortly after the
shooting, police officials said.
	   U.N. officials said Wewiorska had moved to Tbilisi to work as a
secretary for the head of the U.N. mission in Georgia.
	   U.N. observers are in Georgia to monitor the truce between
government forces and separatists in the northwestern Black Sea
province of Abkhazia. The separatists took control of the province
in a 1992-93 war.
	   (pvs/ad/adc)
</TEXT>
