<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-South Africa-Zambia-Copper </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
S. African Anglo-American: Zambian copper deal not final
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) _ Anglo American Corp., the
South African mining and investment conglomerate, says it is still
negotiating to take over Zambia copper mines despite a statement to
the contrary by a Zambian official.
	   Anglo American said Monday it is concerned about current low
copper prices, and that it has not been able to attract partners,
it said.
	   The company said it has a memorandum of understanding with the
Zambian government, but the memorandum hasn't yet been ratified by
the government or the company.
	   Zambian Finance Minister Edith Nawakwi said Saturday that Anglo
American would take over Nchanga, Nkana and Konkola mines, the
remaining major assets of Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines.
	   Anglo American said the memorandum of understanding - between
the government and ZCI Ltd., the company through which Anglo
American holds its interest in the mines - isn't legally binding.
	   ``Negotiations on several important issues are continuing and it
remains uncertain that agreement will be achieved on a basis
acceptable to both sides,'' the company said. ``A joint statement
will be issued on the conclusion of the current negotiations.''
	   Nawakwi said the final touches of the deal would be completed by
March 31. She said the agreement also had the government keeping a
20 percent stake.
	   (djw/djw)	   
</TEXT>
