<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Iran </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Japan concerned about suspected Iranian missile part sales
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi told Iran's
visiting foreign minister on Tuesday he is worried about suspicions
that Iran is supplying missile parts to countries like North Korea,
a report said.
	   Obuchi said that Iranian efforts to allay such fears would help
contribute to the development of bilateral ties, Kyodo News
reported, quoting a Japanese government official.
	   Iranian Foreign Minister Kamal Kharrazi, who is on a three-day
visit to Tokyo, declined to comment on the issue during his meeting
with Obuchi, Kyodo said.
	   Tokyo has become deeply concerned about North Korean missile
development after the Stalinist state fired a rocket in August that
flew over Japan. U.S. and Japanese officials believe the launch was
a ballistic missile test.
	   Japanese Foreign Minister Masahiko Komura invited Kharrazi
during a trip to Tehran last April. Kharrazi's visit is the first
by an Iranian foreign minister to Japan in 11 years.
