<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Somalia-Fighting </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Two dead in South Mogadishu clashes over land
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOGADISHU, Somali (AP) _ At least two men were killed and more
than 15 others were wounded Tuesday in clashes between heavily
armed militiamen loyal to South Mogadishu warlord Hussein Mohamed
Aidid, witnesses said.
	   One group was connected with the Suleman sub-clan; the other
with an Islamic court in the southern half of the war-torn capital.
	   The fighting was said to be connected to disputes over land
ownership.
	   The witnesses said fighting began when a a group of militiamen
tried to kidnap another man, and militiamen from the Shirkole
Islamic court intervened.
	   Although three of the court's militiamen were wounded, the group
managed to restore calm to the area. One of the would-be kidnappers
as well as second unidentified man were killed.
	   Officials from the Islamic court said they would soon take up
the longstanding land dispute which civilian courts were never able
to resolve.
	   There has been no central government or administration in
Somalia since Aidid's late father, Gen. Mohamed Farah Aidid, and
north Mogadishu warlord Ali Mahdi Mohamed briefly joined forces to
oust longtime dictator Mohamed Siad Barre in 1991, plunging the
country into civil war.
	   Islamic courts have been established in Mogadishu and other
parts of the country in a attempt to curb violence and settle civil
disputes.
	   (aan/sl)	   
</TEXT>
