<SLUG> BC-Egypt-Palestinians, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
First Palestinian airline arrives in Egypt
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPGRADES attribution, INSERTS number of flights in 6th graf. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ The first commercial Palestinian flight to
Egypt landed at Cairo's International Airport on Tuesday,
inaugurating an air route between the autonomous Gaza Strip and
Egypt, airport officials said.
	   The Palestinian Airlines flight, which carried 14 passengers,
was met by Egyptian Transportation Minister Suleiman Metwally.
	   The inauguration of the route between Gaza and Cairo is a
``confirmation of Palestinian sovereignty over Palestinian lands''
as well as ports and airports, Metwally said.
	   The Gaza airport was inaugurated in late November under the
U.S.-brokered Wye River accord which envisages Israel ceding more
land to the Palestinians in return for security guarantees.
EgyptAir, the national carrier, sent the first plane for the
inauguration.
	   Palestinian Airlines already has a route from Gaza to the
Jordanian capital, Amman.
	   The airline will fly three flights a week to Egypt, an airport
official said. He spoke on condition of anonymity.
	   Last Friday, Egypt's national carrier, EgyptAir, inaugurated its
route to Gaza.
