<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Spain-Christmas Lottery, 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Christmas lottery distributes massive winnings in Spain
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS; CLARIFIES that 140 tickets sold for each five-digit
number; RESTORES dropped day in lede graf; CORRECTS dollar
conversion of ticket prices &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos Available &QL; 
 &UR; By CIARAN GILES &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MADRID, Spain (AP) _ Christmas festivities started jubilantly
Tuesday for dozens of retirees in a southeastern Spanish town who
will share part of the top prize of 42 billion pesetas (dlrs 300
million) in Spain's lottery _ billed as the world's richest.
	   News reports said champagne corks were poppping at The
Pensioners' Home in La Union as neighbors celebrated the club's win
of 3 billion pesetas (dlrs 21 million) after buying 10 of the 140
winning tickets, each worth 300 million pesetas (dlrs 2.1 million).
	   It was not immediately clear exactly how many pensioners held
shares in tickets for the winning number _ 21856. Prizes were
estimated to range from 1.6 million pesetas (dlrs 10,000) to 30
million pesetas (dlrs 210,000).
	   ``Let's say I won't be able to run wild with it, but I'll be
able to keep my head high'' Carmen Hernandez, a neighbor of the
club, told the private news agency Europa Press.
	   Known as ``El Gordo'' (The Fat One), the lottery dished out 194
billion pesetas (dlrs 1.4 billion) in winnings this year to
thousands of ticket holders throughout Spain.
	   The lottery sells 140 tickets, valued at 30,000 pesetas (dlrs
210) for each five-digit number. The tickets are subsequently
divided into 10 shares worth 3,000 pesetas (dlrs 21) each and are
then often subdivided into smaller parts.
	   Most Spaniards share tickets with family members, friends and
coworkers, so lottery windfalls ripple through whole communities.
Shares of the winning number were sold in six towns across Spain.
	   Each year, millions of television viewers watch as Madrid
schoolchildren pick out numbered balls from drums and sing out the
winning number in a four-hour ceremony.
	   Juan Gomez, a 54-year-old unemployed father of four learned
Tuesday morning that his two shares of 500 pesetas (dlrs 3.5) each
entitled him to 10 million pesetas (dlrs 70,000) in prize money.
	   ``Now I'll be able to pay off the mortgage and help out my
sons,'' said Gomez, who lives in the northeastern town of Sabadell.
The national news agency Efe said three of Gomez's sons were
unemployed and a fourth was a student.
	   Financial pressures were also certain to be easier for
66-year-old street tobacco seller Miguel Trillo who planned to use
the 30 million pesetas (dlrs 210,000) he'd won to pay off debts and
``share with my daughters.''
	   Income from ticket sales was 250 billion pesetas (dlrs 1.8
billion) this year, 8.9 percent up on last year, according to the
department that runs the lottery, founded in 1818.
	   The Spanish Treasury takes 30 percent of the revenues before the
draw to keep the winnings tax-free.
	   The second prize of 144 million pesetas (dlrs 1 million) will be
spilt among holders of tickets bearing the number 07308.
</TEXT>
