w1567 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Poland-Miners 1stLd-Writethru   12-22 0479
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Poland-Miners, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Signs of emerging deal to end Polish miners' protest
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with talks started in 3rd graf, protest by miners from
another union in 4th graf; RECASTS &QL; 
 &UR; By ANDRZEJ STYLINSKI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   WARSAW, Poland (AP) _ Prime Minister Jerzy Buzek said Tuesday he
expected talks between government and labor officials to produce an
agreement that would end a growing labor dispute in Poland.
	   Responding to a strike threat from miners protesting proposed
changes in their pension rules, Buzek said his government never
intended to eliminate pensions for miners and others working in
dangerous conditions who take early retirement.
	   Government officials and leaders of the Solidarity union began
talks Tuesday afternoon on early retirement schemes for miners,
while more than 400 workers in 52 mines continued an underground
sit-in.
	   Also Tuesday, scores of miners from another union gathered in
Warsaw to urge President Aleksander Kwasniewski to veto the pension
law changes, which have been passed by parliament.
	   The new law would set the retirement age to qualify for a full
government pension at 65 for men and 60 for women. Under current
regulations, miners and others in dangerous conditions get a full
pension after working 25 years, no matter their age.
	   Solidarity miners began the sit-in Dec. 10 to demand keeping the
present system. They also oppose a mining restructuring plan that
would cut jobs and production.
	   Workers at coal mines in Silesia, as well as copper, zinc and
lead ore mines, staged a warning strike Monday and voted
overwhelmingly to hold a general strike on an undetermined date.
Solidarity's Mining Section said 98 percent of miners supported the
strike.
	   Buzek, attempting to calm the atmosphere, said Tuesday his
Solidarity-led government never proposed that ``people working in
such difficult conditions like miners had to work until they are
65.''
	   He said the government was negotiating final details of
so-called ``bridge pensions'' for miners retiring after 25 years of
work, covering them until they become eligible for regular pensions
at 65.
	   Buzek's Cabinet, which took power in October 1997 from a leftist
government, has been working on widespread social and economic
reforms expected to complete Poland's transition from communism to
a market economy.
	   The reforms include restructuring ailing industries such as
mining and steel. Coal mining restructuring calls for reducing
production from 137 million tons last year to 110 million tons in
2002, as well as cutting jobs by more than 40 percent _ from
245,000 now to 138,000 in three years.
	   Coal mining, once the country's leading hard-currency earner
during communist times, is still heavily subsidized under Poland's
market reforms that began in 1989.
	   (ajs-tsc)
</TEXT>
