r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Germany-Iraq     12-22 0271
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Iraq </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Germany backs gradual lifting of Iraq sanctions
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BONN, Germany (AP) _ Iraq should be offered a gradual lifting of
United Nations sanctions as an incentive to cooperate with U.N.
weapons inspectors, Germany's foreign minister has said.
	   The comments by Joschka Fischer in a German television interview
late Monday were the first initiative on Iraq policy by the new
center-left government in office since October.
	   By putting equal emphasis on disarming Saddam Hussein but also
helping him lift sanctions, the new German stand could irritate the
United States, which has consistently taken a tough line on
sanctions.
	   Reflecting German unease about U.S. and British airstrikes,
Fischer suggested international efforts to tame Iraq were in a
``no-win situation'' that war would not solve.
	   He called for ``a combination of continuing disarmament controls
in Iraq with humanitarian measures and a step-by-step lifting of
sanctions.''
	   He acknowledged this would require the agreement of all U.N.
Security Council members, including the United States.
	   Fischer's remarks also set the stage for Germany's six-month
presidency of the European Union starting Jan. 1, where he said he
would seek a common European policy on Iraq.
	   With Britain siding with Washington and France critical of
airstrikes, Fischer admitted the task would be difficult.
	   ``Still, the majority of the European Union is taking roughly
the same line as Germany,'' he said. ``And it will be the task of
the German presidency to bring the two positions together.''
 &UR; (tc-gb)
</TEXT>
