<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Israel </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russia criticizes Israel for suspending accord with Palestinians
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russia's Foreign Ministry on Tuesday blamed Israel
for breaking a peace accord with the Palestinians by setting new
conditions for its implementation.
	   Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu's Cabinet on Sunday approved a
tough series of conditions for resuming Israel's already-suspended
compliance with the 2-month-old Wye River accord, brokered by the
United States.
	   Some of those conditions ``go beyond the framework of the signed
agreements,'' said Russian Foreign Ministry spokesman Vladimir
Rakhmanin. ``That causes us serious concern.''
	   Israel's parliament rejected Netanyahu's position and voted
overwhelmingly for early elections.
	   Russia ``urges the sides to act in strict compliance with their
commitments, demonstrate responsibility, restraint and good will''
in implementing the peace accord, Rakhmanin said.
	   Russia is officially a co-sponsor of the Mideast peace process
launched by a conference in Madrid, Spain, in 1991. But the United
States has played a far greater role.
	   Israeli Foreign Minister Ariel Sharon, who was scheduled to
visit Russia on Friday, has canceled his trip because of the
political situation in Israel. Rakhmanin voiced hope that the visit
would still take place in the future.
	   Netanyahu's latest conditions to the Palestinians, which they
have rejected, include a renunciation of claims to statehood rights
and Jerusalem; a confiscation of arms; an end to violence and
incitement to violence; and a renunciation of claims that Netanyahu
had agreed to release Palestinians jailed for killings.
	   (vi/adc) 	   
</TEXT>
