<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Euro </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ECB holds last policy-making meeting prior to currency launch
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: To be updated after news conference beginning 17:30 GMT &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) _ The European Central Bank's
policy-making committee held its final scheduled meeting Tuesday
before the Jan. 1 launch of Europe's common currency, the euro,
with most tough decisions already out of the way.
	   Suspense over the most important issue _ the level of the
euro-zone's key interest rate _ was eliminated on Dec. 3, when all
11 participating countries slashed rates. Ten cut rates to 3
percent, while Italy cut to 3.5 percent.
	   Italy is expected to cut rates to 3 percent by Jan. 1.
	   The ECB said the new rate will hold for the foreseeable future,
though analysts say a rate cut could happen again next year.
	   ECB President Wim Duisenberg has not ruled that out, but has
said pointedly that boosting Europe's flagging economies needs
structural reform to markets, including the labor market. Tinkering
with interest rates is not a panacea, Duisenberg said.
	   The ECB was expected to announce overnight deposit and overnight
lending rates for the euro area.
	   Analysts expect these to be set at 2.5 and 3.5 percent
respectively. Since the two rates represent the floor and ceiling
for money market rates, a relatively narrow band would act to stem
currency fluctuation which could arise amid the uncertainties of
the euro launch.
 &UR; dkt-gb
</TEXT>
