<SLUG> BC-Germany-Neanderthal Site </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Museum buys junk yard site where first Neanderthal bones found
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   DUESSELDORF, Germany (AP) _ The Neanderthal Museum has bought a
site currently used by an auto salvage yard where the first
Neanderthal Man remains were discovered, its director said Tuesday.
	   Gerd-Christian Weniger said the site must first be cleared of
old buildings and the junk yard before it can be set up for
visitors.
	   Plans call for a design competition for the site, with work to
run from mid-1999 until some time in 2000, he said.
	   Weniger declined to say how much was paid for the site, located
near the museum in the Neanderthal valley at Mettmann, about 15
kilometers (10 miles) east of Duesseldorf.
	   The first Neanderthal fossil was found in a cave that was
discovered during rock quarry work in 1856. The cave was later
chipped away as quarry work continued.
	   Neanderthals are believed to have lived until 30,000 years ago.
	   (gb-tc)
</TEXT>
