<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0786 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ogata, Walker face Serbian defiance in Kosovo
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Precede MALISEVO &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS and UPDATES with Serb police action, guerilla threats,
Ogata's quotes, independent radio quotes Walker as saying
cooperation with Yugoslav authorities bad. No pickup. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo BEL101 &QL; 
 &UR; By MISHA SAVIC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Serb police killed a Kosovo Albanian
and arrested six other alleged ``terrorists'' on Tuesday amid signs
of escalating tension, including threats by ethnic Albanian
guerrillas of all-out attack unless police leave central Kosovo.
	   Tensions of another kind were generated in Belgrade, where the
top U.N. refugee official denied accusations that she was biased
toward Kosovo's ethnic Albanian majority.
	   Sadako Ogata, the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees, toured
the province Monday to get a firsthand look at the condition of
tens of thousands of refugees displaced in past fighting.
	   After Ogata met Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic Tuesday in
Belgrade, she rejected claims of pro-Albanian bias. She spoke at a
news conference also attended by her chief accuser, Bratislava
Morina, the Serbian commissioner for refugees.
	   Both the Kosovo Serbs and Morina complained against alleged bias
Ogata showed by visiting mostly ethnic Albanian refugees, the main
victims of a Serb military crackdown in Kosovo that left about
300,000 people displaced and killed more than 1,000 since February.
	   Visibly annoyed by the claims, Ogata blamed both the Serbs and
ethnic Albanians for continued refugee problems in Kosovo, saying
that some 175,000 people have still not returned to their homes
despite being sheltered.
	   ``I strongly condemn (continued) violence and intimidation'' by
both sides in Kosovo, she said.
	   She said she urged Milosevic to implement a promise he made
after he in October signed a U.S.-sponsored Kosovo peace agreement
to grant amnesty for hundreds of ethnic Albanians still held in
Serb prisons on charges of ``terrorist activities.''
	   She did not say what Milosevic answered, but international human
rights groups said they had no information that anyone arrested
during the Kosovo clashes has been released as a result of his
amnesty.
	   More than 1,000 Kosovo Albanians are believed to be in Serbian
prisons and police stations, and at least five have died since
February from beatings and torture, the U.S.-based Human Rights
Watch said earlier this month.
	   Reporting on the shooting, the government-run Media Center said
that the police early Tuesday encountered fire when they tried to
arrest an ethnic Albanian ``terrorist group'' near Pec, west of
Pristina. The police fired back, killing one ethnic Albanian and
arresting six other ``terrorists.''
	   Guerrilla spokesman Adem Demaci warned police to leave central
Kosovo, telling reporters in Pristina: ``We promise, unless they
withdraw from those areas, that they will be attacked everywhere by
our forces.''
	   In Belgrade on Monday, heads of Yugoslavia's Serb-led army met
with NATO's top commander in Europe, Gen. Wesley Clark, who
repeated warnings that the alliance might intervene if fighting
between Serb security forces and ethnic Albanian rebels continues,
sources close to the talks said on condition of anonymity.
	   Milosevic averted threatened NATO airstrikes when he signed the
U.S.-sponsored deal, promising an end to the military campaign
against separatists in the overwhelmingly ethnic Albanian province
of Serbia, the dominant republic in Yugoslavia.
	   William Walker, the U.S. head of the 2,000-strong verification
mission in Kosovo, told independent B 92 radio Tuesday that the
Belgrade ``authorities are generally uncooperative with the
mission.''
	   He said that most of the mission's requests to the authorities
``have drawn a negative response,'' according to B 92.
	   Walker also blamed ethnic Albanian rebels for breaking the
cease-fire agreement and acting ``irresponsibly by carrying out
provocative missions.''
	   On Monday, Serb police carried out a sweep of a Kosovo Albanian
stronghold in retaliation for the killing of one of their officers
in escalating violence that has increased fear of a return to
all-out war in the troubled province.
	   According to a spokesman for the Organization for Security and
Cooperation in Europe, Monday's sweep began after the slaying of
Serb policeman Milic Jovic.
	   The spokesman, Jorgen Grunnet, said a column of Yugoslav army
vehicles, including seven T-55 tanks, left a military barracks just
south of Podujevo.
	   Afterward, OSCE staff heard tank and heavy machine gun fire from
the direction of the village of Dobrotin.
</TEXT>
