<SLUG> BC-Lebanon-Israel,0308 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Israeli warplanes raid suspected guerrilla bases in Lebanon
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BAALBEK, Lebanon (AP) _ Israeli warplanes fired rockets Tuesday
at a guerrilla-run radio station in eastern Lebanon, destroying a
transmitter, Lebanese security officials said.
	   The jets fired at least six air-to-surface missiles on the hills
around the villages of Nabi Sheet and Janta, about 23 kilometers
(14 miles) southwest of the ancient city of Baalbek.
	   The officials said a transmitter for Hezbollah's Voice of the
Oppressed radio on the edge of Nabi Sheet was destroyed. They spoke
on customary condition of anonymity.
	   A spokesman for the Iranian-backed Hezbollah, or Party of God,
confirmed that the afternoon attack hit a transmitter but gave no
other details. He also spoke on condition his name not be used.
	   The radio remained on the air, apparently using a backup
transmitter.
	   The security officials said a shepherd and his wife were wounded
in the attack, but did not say how seriously.
	   Earlier Tuesday, Israeli fighter bombers fired four rockets on
suspected guerrilla bases facing Israel's self-styled ``security
zone'' in south Lebanon.
	   The morning attack targeted the wooded hills near Maidoun in the
western Bekaa Valley, three kilometers (two miles) northeast of the
zone, the officials said.
	   The bombing raids came after Hezbollah guerrillas exchanged fire
with Israeli troops and their allied South Lebanon Army militia,
they said.
	   An Israeli army spokesman in Jerusalem said the Israeli pilots
scored direct hits and that the jets returned safely to base.
	   Hezbollah, or the Party of God, has led the fight to try to oust
Israeli troops and their militia allies from the security, which
Israel set up in southern Lebanon in 1985 to protect its northern
towns from cross-border raids.
</TEXT>
