<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Central African Republic-Elections </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Political parties jockey for allies in Bangui
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGUI, Central African Republic (AP) _ Recent legislative
elections have weakened the ruling Movement for the Liberation of
the People of Centrafrique, which captured the most seats in
parliament but failed to win an outright majority.
	   Election figures from the second round of staggered voting held
earlier this month were released by the Constitutional Court on
Tuesday, indicating the the MLPC won 47 seats in a parliament of
109. A coalition of several opposition parties control 29 seats
after the two rounds of voting, the court said.
	   The remaining seats belong to a variety of independent
candidates or smaller opposition groups, which may now play a key
role in helping either MLPC or the opposition coalition control the
legislative branch of government.
	   In all, about 840 candidates contested for the 109 parliament
seats _ the vast majority of which ahead of the polls were
controlled by President Ange-Felix Patasse's ruling MLPC.
	   The election is seen as an important effort to stabilize the
Central African Republic, which has been wracked by ethnic and
factional violence since independence more than three decades ago.
	   Amid claims of voting irregularities and possible election
fraud, voter turnout was low for the second stage of the polling
process earlier in the month.
	   Patasse's position is not affected by the vote and presidential
elections are not immediately planned.
	   (jb/ids/gam)
</TEXT>
