u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Lebanon-Israel 3rdLd-Writethru   12-22 0416
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Lebanon-Israel, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Israeli air raid kills seven Lebanese civilians
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with seven killed, two wounded,
CHANGES overline &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BAALBEK, Lebanon (AP) _ Israeli warplanes fired missiles at
suspected guerrilla bases in eastern Lebanon Tuesday, killing a
woman and her six children, Lebanese security officials said. A
guerrilla-run radio transmitter also was destroyed in the attack.
	   The officials said the casualties occurred when an Israeli
rocket crashed on a farm where a couple and their seven children
were working in the village of Nabi Sheet, about 23 kilometers (14
miles) southeast of the ancient city of Baalbek.
	   The dead children were between two and 11 years of age.
	   Their father and one other child were wounded, the officials
said, speaking on customary condition of anonymity. It was the
worst civilian casualty this year in the war between Israel and
Lebanese guerrillas.
	   There was no word from Israel on the report.
	   Lebanese officials said at least five other air-to-surface
missiles also hit the hills around the villages of Nabi Sheet and
Janta, about five kilometers (three miles) west of the Syrian
border.
	   The officials said a transmitter for Hezbollah's Voice of the
Oppressed radio on the edge of Nabi Sheet was destroyed.
	   A spokesman for the Iranian-backed Hezbollah confirmed that the
2:45 p.m. (1245 GMT) attack hit a transmitter but gave no other
details. He also spoke on condition his name not be used.
	   The radio remained on the air, apparently using a backup
transmitter.
	   Earlier Tuesday, Israeli fighter bombers fired four rockets on
suspected guerrilla bases facing Israel's self-styled ``security
zone'' in an occupied portion of South Lebanon.
	   Hezbollah, or the Party of God, has led the fight to try to oust
Israeli troops and their allied South Lebanon Army militia from the
security zone, which Israel set up in southern Lebanon in 1985 to
protect its northern towns from cross-border raids.
	   The morning attack targeted the wooded hills near Maidoun in the
western part of the Bekaa Valley, just outside the security zone,
the officials said. There was no word on casualties from the raid.
	   The bombing raids came after Hezbollah guerrillas exchanged fire
with Israeli troops and the SLA, they said.
	   An Israeli army spokesman in Jerusalem said the Israeli pilots
scored direct hits and that the jets returned safely to base.
 &UR; pvs-zk/vj
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Lebanon-Israel, 3rd Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
