<HEADLINE>
Former Paraguayan consul in Geneva charged in dlrs 100 million
</HEADLINE>
fraud &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: CORRECTS in first and final grafs that Beres appeared before
the magistrate but not in court. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   GENEVA (AP) _ The former honorary consul of Paraguay in Geneva
appeared before a magistrate Tuesday on charges of a dlrs 100
million fraud.
	   Gustavo Gramont Beres, who had been charged for other offenses
in Paraguay, was extradited to Switzerland on the request of Geneva
authorities, said investigating magistrate Leonardo Malfanti.
	   Beres, an Argentine national, was the Paraguayan honorary consul
in Geneva from 1979 to 1989.
	   City authorities began an inquiry into Beres last year, and made
an official request for his extradition in February.
	   After being questioned, Beres was detained in prison pending his
trial. The charges relate to deception and forgery of dlrs 100
million worth of Swiss francs and German marks, according to Geneva
magistrate Malfanti. He gave no more details.
</TEXT>
