<SLUG> BC-EU-US-Bananas </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EU: US sanctions banana trade sanctions dlrs 600 million a year
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ The EU said Tuesday U.S. sanctions
against European imports resulting from a transatlantic banana
trade dispute totaled dlrs 600 million a year with British and
Italian firms bearing the brunt of the punishment.
	   European Commission spokesman Nigel Gardner called the punitive
tariffs on European Union imports ``arbitrary and illegal.''
	   An initial calculation showed the imports _ ranging from cartons
to batteries to coffee makers to Pecorino cheese _ have an annual
value of 501,167 million euros, roughly dlrs 600 million, he said.
	   British and Italian imports account for respectively 24 and 21
percent of this total, Gardner said.
	   He said the EU will push ahead with ``major changes'' in its
banana import regime that will likely bring imports of Latin
American bananas into the EU from their current 68 percent market
share to around 85 percent.
	   ``We are completely happy our new banana rules comply'' with
World Trade Organization rules, Gardner told reporters.
	   On Monday, the EU executive commission said it will accelerate
steps in the WTO for consultations leading to a panel against
unilateral U.S. measures under Section 301 of the U.S. Trade Act.
	   That law lets Washington determine if its trade partners
unfairly protect their markets and whether to impose retaliatory
measures.
	   The banana dispute has dragged on for years. It began when the
EU decided to provide better access to bananas from ex-European
colonies at the expense of U.S.-owned Latin American producers who
serve 85 percent of the world market.
	   Washington has already won one WTO ruling against the EU and
maintains changes in EU banana imports resulting from the WTO
ruling were insufficient. On Monday, it published a list of EU
products that will be hit with 100 percent tariffs that will double
their prices in the United States.
	   Gardner said Britain will be hardest hit. He put the value of
British imports at 120 million euros (dlrs 144 million) a year or
24 percent of all imports targeted by the U.S. sanctions.
	   Italy was second at 103,5 million euros (dlrs 124.2 million),
followed by France, 95.5 million euros (dlrs 114.6 million);
Germany, 70.6 million euros (dlrs 85 million); Belgium, 35.4
million euros (dlrs 42.5 million); Spain, 21.9 million euros (dlrs
26.3 million); Portugal, 12.4 million euros (dlrs 15 million);
Denmark, (11.5 million euros (dlrs 13.8 million); Netherlands, 9.7
million euros (dlrs 11.64 million); Greece, 7.5 million euros (dlrs
9 million); Austria, 5.3 million euros (dlrs 6.4 million); Sweden,
4 million euros (dlrs 4.8 million); Finland, 2.2 million euros
(dlrs 2.6 million); Ireland, 1.9 million euros (dlrs 2.3 million).
	   The EU list was at odds with comments made by U.S. officials
Monday who said products of Denmark and the Netherlands will be
exempted from penalties because they were the only nations who
voted against the EU banana rules.
 &UR; (rw)	   
</TEXT>
