<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Middle East Business Briefs </SLUG>

 &UR; Eds: Contains items on Egypt and Jordan &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Egypt is seeking to boost its non-petroleum
exports by 20 percent in 1999, the daily Al-Ahram reported Tuesday.
	   To realize this goal, the government will increase cotton
exports by about 34 percent, the newspaper quoted Trade Minister
Ahmed Guweily as saying.
	   Rice exports will increase from 400,000 tons to 500,000 tons and
the textile sector will boost its exports from 3 billion Egyptian
pounds (dlrs 880 million) to 4 billion pounds (dlrs. 1.17 billion),
he said.
	   Guweily called on public and private sector firms to make full
use of accords signed recently with the Common Market for East and
Central Africa, or COMESA, and bilateral agreements and the free
trade areas set up between Egypt and a number of Arab countries.
	   Other plans for boosting exports include upgrading quality to
make Egyptian products more competitive on the world market,
concluding free trade agreements with other countries and boosting
investment in export-oriented industries.
 &UR; ___
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) _ The government plans to conduct a full
review early next year on ways to encourage and promote economic
investments in the kingdom, a government official said Tuesday.
	   The private sector and the presidents and members of the
financial committees of both houses of Parliament will be consulted
as part of the review, the official said. He spoke on condition of
anonymity.
	   He hinted at the possibility that the new review would include
amendments to an investment promotion law to simplify and
facilitate investment procedures.
	   The government is determined to make tax and customs incentives
more effective and reduce bureaucracy, he said.
	   Earlier this year, Jordan doubled the permitted level of foreign
investments in the commercial, industrial and economic sectors,
producing a 22 percent hike in investment during the
January-November 1998 period compared to the whole of 1997.
 &UR; __
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) _ Israel has agreed to ease restrictions on
transportation of goods between Jordan and the Palestinian
territories, an Israeli Embassy statement said Tuesday.
	   The statement said a meeting of Jordanian-Israeli Joint
Committee decided that Jordanian vehicles will be allowed to
transport goods directly to customers in the Palestinian held
lands.
	   The committee, chaired by Issa Ayoub, director-general of the
transport ministry, and his Israeli counterpart, Nahoum Langental,
agreed that loading and unloading docks should be constructed in
certain areas in Israel, close to the Palestinian territories under
Israeli supervision, the statement said.
 &UR; vars/vj
</TEXT>
