w1649 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Belgium-IFJ-Journalis     12-22 0321
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Belgium-IFJ-Journalists Slain </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IFJ: 49 journalists, 1 photographer killed in the world in 1998
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) - Norbert Zongo was a leading journalist
in Burkina Faso, Igor Lykov denounced corruption in the Russian
press, Afrim Maliqi criticized Serbian policy towards the Albanian
population of Kosovo.
	   All three were killed by gunmen in 1998. They are among 49
journalists and one photographer slain this year, the International
Federation of Journalists said in a report published Tuesday.
	   Of the 50 victims, 30 journalists and a photographer were killed
for reasons tied to their work, the IFJ's general secretary Aidan
White told a news conference. The IFJ is still investigating the
other 19 cases.
	   The highest death rate was in Colombia, where 10 journalists
were killed in 1998, followed by Mexico, where six journalists were
killed, and Russia, where five journalists died.
	   ``In certain countries, it seems to be accepted that if you kill
a journalist you won't get caught,'' White said, denouncing the
``lack of commitment at political level to trace the killers of
journalists.''
	   IFJ spokeswoman Cailin MacKenzie said the killings were only
``the tip of the iceberg.'' ``In Kosovo, for example, journalists
are being fined enormous amounts of money, newspapers are being
shut down,'' she said.
	   Central and South America remained the most dangerous zone for
journalists in 1998, with a total 22 journalists killed in Brazil,
Colombia, Mexico, Peru and Guatemala.
	   ``In some countries, the situation is improving,'' White said,
noting that for the first time in several years there were no
casualties among the press in Algeria.
	   Last year, as in 1996, 47 journalists were killed in the world.
	   White said the IFJ bases its evidence on locally-based sources,
as well as testimonies from the colleagues and relatives of the
victims.
	    &UR; (as)	   
</TEXT>
