<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-South Africa-Christmas Massacre </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAfrican judge frees five convicted in Christmas 1995 massacre
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By DANIEL J. WAKIN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) _ Party leaders appealed for
calm Tuesday after a judge released five people who were jailed for
the politically motivated massacre of 18 people on Christmas three
years ago.
	   The attack in 1995 was carried out by supporters of the Zulu
nationalist Inkatha Freedom Party in Shobashobane, a village 525
kilometers (330 miles) southeast of Johannesburg.
	   It was a particularly shocking episode in the decade-long war
between IFP militants and followers of the African National
Congress.
	   The fighting in the years before all-race elections in 1994 left
more than 10,000 people dead. With the next elections approaching
in mid-1999, many fear a resurgence of tensions.
	   ``We are asking people to restrain themselves,'' said Dumisani
Makhaye, an ANC spokesman in KwaZulu-Natal Province, site of
Shobashobane and scene of much of the violence.
	   Ruling in an appeal, Judge Jan Hugo overturned the convictions
of five of 13 men found guilty in the massacre and ordered them
released from prison. The judge found they had been wrongly
convicted, the South African Press Association reported. One of
those freed was Sipho Ngcobo, a leading IFP official in the area.
	   No opinion accompanied the ruling. No one was available in his
office Tuesday to comment.
	   The ANC reacted to the ruling with ``shock and disbelief,'' the
party said in a statement. It said it was ``ironic'' that the
decision came just a few days before the third anniversary of the
killing.
	   The IFP expressed relief at Hugo's ruling.
	   ``We are happy to have our people found not guilty in a court of
law of these terrible crimes,'' said Lauretta Ncgobo, an IFP
spokeswoman. She is not related to Sipho Ngcobo.
	   ``There has been a lot of rumbling going on that area. I would
hope ... there shouldn't be any trouble. We don't want any
trouble,'' she said.
	   In the bloodshed at Shobashobane, a village near the Indian
Ocean town of Port Shepstone, the victims were shot and hacked to
death when some 2,000 IFP supporters attacked.
	   On Monday, ANC officials blamed the IFP for the weekend burning
of 16 houses belonging to ANC supporters in the same rural area.
The Christmas period is particularly volatile because many
city-based workers travel home to see families.
	   (djw-aos)
</TEXT>
