<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Russia, 1st Ld-Writethru,0540 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Primakov urges increase in trade with India
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout to with details of joint declaration,
details, CHANGES byline. No Pick Up. &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: ADDS details about Yeltsin's visit, edits. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo DEL101-102
 &UR; By KRISHNAN GURUSWAMY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ India and Russia will sign a ``strategic
friendship'' agreement next year to reflect their close ties since
the 1971 treaty signed during the Cold War, according to a joint
declaration issued Tuesday.
	   It will be signed during President Boris Yeltsin's planned visit
to India next year, Russian Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov said
Monday. Yeltsin was scheduled to visit New Delhi in December, but
his trip was postponed as his health deteriorated. No fresh dates
have been set for Yeltsin's visit.
	   ``This political document of paramount importance will set new
parameters and guide further development of the close partnership
between India and Russia,'' said a joint declaration at the end of
a two-day visit by Primakov.
	   On Monday, the two nations signed seven agreements to boost
trade, air services, diplomatic interaction and extradition of
criminals.
	   Officials of both nations are working on a proposal to let New
Delhi to plow back about 10 percent of the money it owes Moscow
into joint venture companies in India, said the Indian official who
cannot be identified under briefing rules.
	   India has been paying about dlrs 1 billion each year to Moscow
for the last five years. The money is used to buy goods such as
tea, tobacco and medicines for Russian companies. New Delhi
suggested that some of that money could be used to set up joint
ventures in India in such areas as power generation, steel
production and information technology, which would benefit the
Russians, the official said.
	   On Tuesday, Primakov reassured Indian business leaders that his
country remains a safe place for investment.
	   Primakov, speaking to Indian industrialists at the end of his
state visit to New Delhi, tried to set at rest concerns about
Russia's economic problems, including the collapse of its banking
system. He said Russia was committed to its international financial
obligations, an open economy and noninterference with dollar
exchange rates.
	   Russia was also proposing lowering taxes for foreign investors
and would consider repaying Indian businessmen who lost money
deposited in banks backed by the government in the recent banking
crisis.
	   He called for a doubling of India-Russia trade by the year 2000
and for increased Indian investment in his country.
	   Russia has been one of India's largest trade partners, but
Russia's economic crisis has hit bilateral trade that has been
dwindling since the breakup of the Soviet Union. Trade between the
two countries has fallen from a high of dlrs 5.5 billion in 1990 to
dlrs 1.5 billion in 1998.
	   ``This we cannot accept,'' said Primakov calling for twofold
increase in trade by 2000 and a fourfold increase by 2005.
	   After his meeting Monday with his Indian counterpart Atal Bihari
Vajpayee, Primakov said the two prime ministers would personally
oversee removal of obstacles in the way of better trade.
</TEXT>
