<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Romania-Refinery Deal </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Turkey's Akmaya Sanayi Ve Ticaret to buy Romanian refinery
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BUCHAREST, Romania (AP) _ A leading Turkish holding company,
Akmaya Sanayi Ve Ticaret, signed Tuesday an agreement with the
Romanian government to buy a majority stake in Petromidia oil
refinery.
	   Under the agreement, Akmaya will purchase 65 percent of
Petromidia for dlrs 725 million in January 1999, the Romanian
government said in an official statement.
	   The deal includes rescheduling nearly dlrs 260 million of
Petromidia's debt through the Romanian government, the statement
said.
	   Strategically located in the Black Sea port of Constanta, oil
from Petromidia could be transported through western Europe by
waterways via the Danube and Rhine rivers, allowing oil to be
distributed at points along the way from Hungary to Germany.
	   Romania has 10 major oil refineries, built up under the tenure
of former dictator Nicolae's Ceausescu, which produce some 34
million tons of oil per year. Petromidia has an annual capacity of
4.8 million tons.
	   The state currently owns 69 percent of the refinery, while the
remaining 31 percent is held by a private-public investment fund
and the public. Akmaya's 65 percent stake will be wholly the
government share.
	   Akmaya holds assets in a range of companies, including
commodities, steel makers, communications, banking, finance and
insurance, in addition to 100 percent ownership of Turkey's Sumer
Bank.
	   (ma/me)
</TEXT>
