<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iran-Mayor </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Iranian court rejects appeal of former mayor
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) _ An Iranian court has rejected an appeal by
the former mayor of Tehran who was sentenced to five years in jail
in July for corruption, the Islamic Republic News Agency reported
Tuesday.
	   The appeal by Gholamhossein Karbaschi was considered by three
judges and the ``charges and the cases of conviction remain the
same,'' IRNA quoted judiciary spokesman Fotovat Nasiri-Savadkouhi
as saying.
	   IRNA said the court considered some commutation, but did not
make it clear if the sentence was actually reduced. It did not say
when the ruling was made.
	   Karbaschi, a key ally of moderate President Mohammad Khatami,
had been a target of the hard-line political rivals, and many
Iranians saw the trial as a political settling of scores.
	   He was found guilty in July of embezzlement during his eight
years as Tehran's mayor. He was fined 1 billion rials (dlrs
330,000), ordered to pay 600 million rials (dlrs 200,000) to the
city and banned from holding any government job for 20 years.
	   Karbaschi filed an appeal in August.
	   During his trial, which lasted more than a month, Karbaschi
admitted to making mistakes, but denied stealing public money.
	   Karbaschi won wide respect for his work as mayor. He built parks
and social centers and reduced pollution and traffic congestion.
But he also made enemies among the merchant class which resented
his taxes and his support for Khatami, a moderate cleric who
believes in relaxing the Islamic social code. His pro-Khatami
stance also incurred the enmity of hard-liners.
	   Riots erupted in Iran soon after Karbaschi's arrest in April.
	   Following the trial he was allowed to remain free on bail until
there was a ruling on his appeal of the sentence: three years for
embezzling public funds and two years for misappropriation of
government money.
	   For many Iranians, the televised trial gave the first insight
into Iran's judicial process and moderates saw it more as an
indictment of the judiciary than the mayor.
 &UR; av-ti-sf/vj
</TEXT>
