</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Kyrgyzstan-WTO </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kyrgyzstan becomes first ex-Soviet republic to join WTO
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The Central Asian nation of Kyrgyzstan has become
the first former Soviet republic to join the World Trade
Organization.
	   Kyrgyzstan ratified the WTO's terms for entry last month, and
then had to wait 30 days for the membership to become official, the
ITAR-Tass news agency reported Tuesday. The 30-day waiting period
expired on Monday.
	   Kyrgyzstan, a rural nation of about 4 million people, has a weak
economy based on agriculture, especially sheep farming. It is one
of the poorest of the 15 former Soviet republics.
	   Kyrgyzstan agreed to reduce import tariffs on goods including
some energy products, chemicals and paper to join the WTO, the
world's main trade body which sets global rules. Kyrgyzstan is the
group's 133rd member, trade officials said.
	   The country also promised to open international and
long-distance telephone services to foreign suppliers by Jan. 1,
2003.
	   Latvia is likely to become the next former Soviet republic to
join the WTO.
	   Russia applied for membership in 1993, but hasn't been admitted.
Kyrgyzstan applied in 1996.
	   (ad/adc)
</TEXT>
