<SLUG> BC-Sierra Leone-Fighting </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Refugees flood Freetown, while rebels draw nearer
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) _ Thousands of refugees poured into
Sierra Leone's capital on Tuesday as fighting intensified between
rebel forces and Nigerian-led West African intervention troops
based in nearby towns.
	   Villagers carried their few possessions on their heads and
walked throughout the night to reach Freetown. In the city, they
slept in the sweltering sun along sidewalks while others pitched
tents and some sought shelter in shop doorways.
	   A number of refugees recounted images of rebel fighters burning
down houses and randomly killing civilians with assault rifles in
the town of Wellington, about 20 miles (35 kilometers) to the east.
There were unconfirmed reports of heavy fighting in other towns
closer to the capital.
	   One of the refugees from Wellington, Arthur Nicol, said he
witnessed rebels gouging out the eyes of the national
general-secretary of the Young Men's Christian Association in
Sierra Leone, Paul Whenzle.
	   ``The rebels killed him only after he gave them all of his
money,'' Nicol added.
	   Faced with apparent the apparent setbacks, officials from the
government and the West African intervention force fighting on its
behalf instituted a press blackout, declining to speak to
journalists about the fighting and banning unauthorized dispatches.
	   Earlier this month a Sierra Leonean journalist working for the
British Broadcasting Corp. was arrested and charged in connection
with a report about fighting in Sierra Leone's interior.
	   Some West African soldiers speaking on condition of anonymity at
checkpoints along the Wellington-Freetown highway said the
coalition army, known as ECOMOG, had driven the rebels away from
Wellington early Tuesday, but the situation remained unstable.
	   Civilians leaving Freetown for Sierra Leone's interior were
turned back by ECOMOG troops, while others trying to take refuge in
the capital underwent vigorous searches before being allowed to
enter.
	   President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah's government has been waging war
against members of Sierra Leone's ousted military junta and its
rebel allies.
	   Kabbah was returned to power in March after the ruling military
junta that deposed him was itself ousted.
	   Together with the civilian militia, ECOMOG forces have been
given defense duties by the government, which earlier this year
disbanded the rebellious military and imprisoned thousands of
soldiers suspected of aiding the former junta.
	   Thousands of people have been brutally killed, raped and maimed
by the rebels in a sweeping revenge campaign against the
government.
	   The latest fighting prompted aid workers with the missionary
group Adventist Development and Relief Agency to abandon a hospital
and rehabilitation camp Monday for thousands of war amputees in
Waterloo.
	   On the outskirts of Freetown, the thumping of mortars and rattle
of machine-gun fire could be heard intermittently Sunday night,
when ECOMOG tightened a night curfew and patrolled beaches and
suburbs of the capital. Rebels captured the diamond-mining town of
Kono late last week.
	   Sierra Leone, a diamond-rich country of about 4.5 million
people, has been plagued by intermittent hostilities since 1990
despite the overwhelming unpopularity of the rebel alliance.
	   (var-gam/ids) 	   
</TEXT>
