<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sweden-Department Store Fire, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Fire hits department store amid Christmas rush
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Leads throughout to ADD details from police briefing, CORRECT
that liquid was inflammable but not necessarily gasoline.
 &UR; AP Photos planned &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) _ Fire broke out in a department store
crowded with Christmas shoppers Tuesday after a man poured an
inflammable liquid on the floor, police said. At least two people
were injured.
	   The fire started at 2:12 p.m. (1312 GMT) on the ground floor of
the six-story PUB store, one of Stockholm's largest. An explosion
connected with the fire blew out a display window, injuring a
female passerby.
	   Kristian Dalsgaard, a Stockholm police official suprevising the
investigation, told reporters that the fire was quickly
extinguished by the store's sprinkler system, but that it had been
potentially a ''very dangerous'' situation.
	   ''It's terrible that something like this can happen in a big
department store in the middle of the Christmas rush,'' he said.
	   The center of the store is an open, atrium-like space extending
from the top floor to one floor below street-level and the building
quickly filled with smoke, police said.
	   A man whom security guards saw puring liquid on the floor was
grabbed by security guards and turned over to police. Dalsgaard
said little was immediately known about the suspect.
	   The scene outside the store after the fire was calm, with people
lined up at a bank machine set in one of the building's walls. But
the Swedish news agency TT quoted an unnamed employee as saying
''We panicked and ran in every direction.''
	   The fire started in an aisleway next to a cosmetics boutique and
officials speculated the explosion may have been caused by burning
aerosol cans.
	   The store faces the Hoetorget square, directly across from the
city's main concert hall. Firemen closed off the square, which
includes about 20 covered stalls for vendors of produce and leather
and woolen goods, but allowed it to reopen about two hours later.
	   One of those injured was treated for smoke inhalation. The
condition of the woman cut by the flying glass was not immediately
known.
	   Police allowed journalists into the building breifly, showing
there was little fire damage but apparently substantial water
damage.
	   (jh)
</TEXT>
