<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-South Africa-Endangered Doctors </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Troubled times for foreign doctors in South Africa
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo available
 &UR; By ANDREW SELSKY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) _ After finishing his rounds,
Dr. Krysztof Zapolski went into an operating theater, put a cloth
soaked in anaesthetic over his face and a plastic bag over his
head. Workers found his body the next day.
	   Some of Zapolski's colleagues believe he committed suicide
because of his difficulties with the government over his work
permit. His wife Tracey insists he accidentally overdosed while
taking anaesthetic to relax from work pressures.
	   Whatever the circumstances, the death of the Polish doctor on
Dec. 8 has highlighted the plight of foreign-qualified physicians,
who share the burden of South Africa's massive health care needs.
	   They now find themselves facing the prospect of being ousted
from the country because of inflexible and murky immigration
procedures and because a first generation of South African
doctor-trainees are entering the workforce.
	   Like hundreds of other foreign doctors, Zapolski had to renew
his work permit every few months.
	   In the days preceding his death, he complained to colleagues
that the Home Affairs office said he had given insufficient reason
why his permit should be renewed, according to Dr. Safdar Malick, a
Pakistani who chairs the Foreign Qualified Doctors Association.
	   ``Chris' death was an expression of helplessness and
frustration, a feeling shared by many doctors,'' said Malick, whose
organization investigated Zapolski's death.
	   Doctors who earned their degrees abroad before emigrating to
South Africa find themselves on shaky ground, just as the nation's
health-care system is being strained beyond its limits.
	   Patients are overwhelming understaffed hospitals. Most South
Africans, 3 million of whom have HIV or AIDS, still lack adequate
access to health care, four years after the end of apartheid, which
deprived non-whites of most services.
	   In order to redress the imbalances and extend health care to
everyone, the government this year began requiring medical school
graduates to perform a year of public service.
	   But instead of the program putting more doctors into the field,
cash-strapped hospitals are firing doctors, many of them
foreign-trained, and filling the positions with the lower-paid
interns.
	   Chris Hani Baragwanath Hospital is this month terminating the
contracts of 42 foreign-qualified doctors and putting interns in
their places, said hospital spokeswoman Esther Hlongwane. The same
is occurring in other hospitals.
	   Of the 7,000 foreign-trained doctors in South Africa, 2,300 --
including some naturalized South Africans -- have ``limited
registration,'' meaning they can only work in public hospitals,
with the government dictating what medicine they can practice,
Malick said. Of those, 1,100 lack permanent residency and have
temporary work permits.
	   Last week, the Sowetan newspaper reported that Health Minister
Nkosazana Zuma had told foreign doctors with temporary work permits
that they must leave the country by the end of the year.
	   Zuma's spokesman, Vincent Hlongwane, dismissed the report as
``nonsense.'' Hlongwane, no relation to the hospital spokeswoman,
said he was unaware of plans to expel foreign-trained doctors.
	   Nevertheless, the Foreign Qualified Doctors Association is ready
to go to court to stop any expulsions.
	   Such expulsions might be applauded by some native South
Africans, who believe doctors from countries where the pay is lower
are taking jobs from locals.
	   Dr. Shahid Amin, a Pakistani, argued that there aren't enough
doctors in South Africa, period, regardless of nationality.
	   ``In this country, the ratio of patients to doctors is 2,400 to
one,'' he said. ``In many developed countries it is 1,000 to one.''
	   (aos/djw)	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
