<SLUG> BC-Ukraine-Taxes </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ukraine cancels late fines to encourage tax payments
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) _ Ukraine's President Leonid Kuchma has
signed a decree canceling late tax fines for companies that pay all
their 1998 taxes by next February, a news report said Tuesday.
	   The decree, signed Monday, was the latest in a series of
measures Ukraine's cash-strapped government has taken to improve
its chronically poor tax collection.
	   The decree will become effective in a month unless parliament
revokes it, the independent Ukrainian News agency said. Lawmakers
are unlikely to oppose the decree.
	   The nationwide tax debt in Ukraine skyrocketed this year from
January's 2.3 billion hryvna (dlrs 1.09 billion at the time) to
10.2 billion hryvna (dlrs 3 billion) as of Dec. 1, with most
companies trying to escape the suffocating tax burden by declaring
lower incomes, putting off tax payments _ or by not paying taxes at
all.
	   Economic reforms in Ukraine have proceeded slowly since it
gained independence with the 1991 Soviet collapse. The government
has failed to stop the continuing economic decline, which has left
most enterprises loss-making and unable to pay their bills _ or
taxes.
	   (vl/adc)
</TEXT>
