<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Ukraine-Economy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ukraine's government to print money to pay off wage debts
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) _ Ukraine's government will print money next
year to cover its mounting wage arrears, Prime Minister Valery
Pustovoitenko said Tuesday.
	   Pustovoitenko said the Cabinet plans a monetary emission of 1
billion hryvna (dlrs 292 million), all of which would be used to
pay off overdue wages and pensions, the Interfax news agency
reported.
	   Printing money generally stokes inflation. Pustovoitenko did not
say how he expected next year's money emissions to affect the 1999
inflation rate, which was earlier forecast at 19 percent.
	   Ukraine's government owes more than 2 billion hryvna (dlrs 584
million) to pensioners and about 1 billion hryvna (dlrs 292
million) in unpaid wages to state employees.
	   The debt has been rising for years as the government,
chronically short of revenues, kept delaying social security
payments to pay off its other debts, including those to foreign
creditors.
	   Ukraine has to pay off about dlrs 2 billion on its foreign debt
obligations next year, while its reserves amount to only half that
amount. The cash shortage has forced government officials to
propose printing money.
	   The Cabinet also has said recently that it would use proceeds
from upcoming privatization of the former Soviet republic's
telecommunications monopoly to pay off wage and pension debts.
	   (vl/adc)
</TEXT>
