<HEADLINE>
US general visits troops in Bosnia
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With AP Photo &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TUZLA, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) _ America's top soldier paid a
pre-Christmas visit to U.S. troops based in the northern Bosnian
town of Tuzla on Tuesday and praised them for doing a ``superb
job.''
	   U.S. Gen. Henry Shelton, chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff,
visited the some 6,900 American soldiers taking part in the
32,000-strong, NATO-led peacekeeping mission ``that is making a
real difference in the lives of the people of Bosnia,'' Shelton
told reporters.
	   Shelton said it was a pleasure to get away from Washington for a
while and to be back among soldiers, airmen, sailors and Marines,
particularly at this time of year.
	   ``With the holiday season upon us, I wanted to briefly visit our
troops here in Bosnia and thank them for the great job they are
doing,'' he said.
	   Although the joint U.S. and British action in the Persian Gulf
was in focus lately, Shelton reminded the troops that ``keeping
Saddam Hussein in his box'' was just one of America's current
military missions.
	   He also praised the U.S. military involvement in Bosnia and said
the troops will continue performing their ``magnificent job'' here,
including continuing to arrest war-crimes suspects as the
opportunities occur.
	   ``America appreciates your sacrifice and your dedication,''
Shelton told the troops.
	   (aptn/acr/asd) 	   
