w1780 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Canada-SwissairCrash     12-22 0467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Canada-Swissair Crash,0466 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Remains of all Swissair 111 victims identified, 16 weeks after
</HEADLINE>
crash &QL; 
 &UR; By DAVID CRARY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TORONTO (AP) _ Sixteen weeks after the crash of Swissair Flight
111 shattered the bodies of those on board, police said Tuesday
that remains of all 229 victims have been identified thanks to
state-of-the-art DNA techniques.
	   Police also said more than dlrs 1 million in U.S. currency has
been recovered from the wreckage on the ocean floor off Nova
Scotia. Still missing is a shipment of diamonds.
	   The impact of the Sept. 2 crash was so great that traditional
identification methods, including the use of dental and X-ray
records, were of minimal use in identifying the fragmented remains
retrieved from the Atlantic.
	   Blood samples were collected from relatives of those on board,
and the Royal Canadian Mounted Police coordinated an intensive
operation at several forensic laboratories around Canada to match
the samples with recovered remains.
	   RCMP officers, at a news briefing Tuesday in Halifax, Nova
Scotia, said DNA techniques had never before been used to such an
extent in the aftermath of an air disaster. They said recent
technological advances enabled them to complete tasks in days that
might previously have taken weeks.
	   The RCMP recommended that airlines henceforth keep fingerprint
and DNA records of their crew members to make identifications
easier.
	   About 85 percent of the wreckage of the MD-11 jumbo jet has been
recovered from the seabed, and a scallop dragger is being used in
an effort to scoop up the rest.
	   Investigators, who will take a 10-day holiday break starting
Wednesday, still don't know what caused the crash, but their
efforts are focused on determining the source of a fire in the
front of the jet. There is evidence of heat damage inside and just
outside the cockpit, where the two pilots reported smoke about 16
minutes before the plane crashed en route from New York to Geneva.
	   Vic Gerden, chief investigator for the Transportation Safety
Board of Canada, said small pieces of aluminum from the front of
the plane got so hot they melted moments before the crash.
	   Temperatures in some areas hit at least 1200F (650C), the point
at which that type of aluminum melts, Gerden said. But
investigators still don't know where the fire started.
	   Investigators have been examining hundreds of segments of
electrical wire from the front of the jet for signs of heat damage.
In all, more than 1 million pieces of wreckage have been recovered.
	   Investigators are trying to reconstruct the forward section of
the fuselage, but the process is complicated because many of the
pieces are small and were damaged by the crash.
	   ``It is a pretty challenging puzzle,'' Gerden said.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Canada-Swissair Crash; CT:i; 
