w1785 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Vatican-Iraq     12-22 0391
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Vatican-Iraq </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Vatican keeps up criticism of U.S.-British airstrikes
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By VICTOR L. SIMPSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   VATICAN CITY (AP) _ The Vatican is keeping up its criticism of
the U.S.-British airstrikes, with its newspaper suggesting Tuesday
that the attacks caused large numbers of civilian casualties.
	   ``The macabre dance around the figures of the real number of
victims,'' said L'Osservatore Romano, is ``yet another offense to
the Iraqi population and the entire family of nations.''
	   ``Hundreds of missiles launched on a city like Baghdad cannot
but have devastated home and stores, causing death, blood and
misery,'' the daily Italian-language newspaper said in a front-page
commentary.
	   Pope John Paul II opposed the 1991 Gulf War, and in the years
since has called for an easing of the sanctions against Iraq.
	   John Paul is generally opposed to the use of sanctions and
embargoes on grounds the measures most harm the weakest in society.
Taking that line, he spoke out against the U.S. economic embargo of
Cuba during a pilgrimage to Havana in January.
	   The Vatican has been especially blunt in its criticism following
the recent airstrikes. It called the attacks ``aggression'' and
said the pope was ``saddened'' that diplomatic efforts broke down.
	   The issue could end up dominating John Paul's scheduled meeting
with President Clinton in St. Louis, Missouri, Jan. 26. The pope is
making a two-day stop in the American city following a visit to
Mexico City and the president and pope are to hold talks in an Air
National Guard hangar at Lambert airport.
	   The criticism has come from the highest officials at the
Vatican.
	   The secretary of state, Cardinal Angelo Sodano, questioned the
``selective'' application of U.N. resolutions. Italian media took
that as a reference to the international community's failure to
demand that Israel meet all resolutions while insisting Iraq do so.
	   Asked by reporters if the airstrikes constituted aggression, the
cardinal replied:
	   ``Either it's a war of defense or a war of aggression. There's
no middle ground.''
	   Sodano, the Vatican's No. 2 official, also reiterated the pope's
desire to visit Iraq to stop at Abraham's Biblical birthplace
during a possible tour of holy sites in the Middle East in 2000.
	   (vls-fd)
</TEXT>
