<SLUG> BC-Lebanon-Israel, 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Israeli air raid in Lebanon kills mother and 6 children
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Israeli and Hezbollah statements, guerrilla
reported killed, quote from father; ADDS byline &QL; 
 &UR; By MORSHED DANDASH &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BAALBEK, Lebanon (AP) _ Israeli warplanes fired missiles at
suspected guerrilla bases in eastern Lebanon Tuesday, killing a
woman and her six children, Lebanese security officials said.
	   A guerrilla also was reported killed and a guerrilla-run radio
transmitter destroyed in the attack.
	   The officials said one Israeli rocket crashed on a farm where a
couple and their seven children were working in the village of Nabi
Sheet, about 23 kilometers (14 miles) southwest of the ancient city
of Baalbek.
	   The mother and six children aged between two and 13 were killed.
	   The father, Mohammed Othman, and one child were wounded, the
officials said, speaking on customary condition of anonymity. It
was the worst civilian casualty this year in the war between Israel
and Lebanese guerrillas.
	   ``I felt I was lifted from the ground and then everything went
black,'' Othman, who suffered shrapnel wounds, said from his
hospital bed in Baalbek.
	   In Jerusalem, an Israeli army spokesman said Israeli planes
targeted a guerrilla training facility and a broadcast station _ a
transmitter of the Hezbollah guerrilla group's Voice of the
Oppressed radio.
	   Although the targets were not near civilian areas, one missile
hit a building that was not the target, the spokesman said,
describing it as a ``malfunction.''
	   The spokesman, who cannot be identified under briefing rules,
``expressed regret'' at the loss of civilian life, and said an
investigation is underway.
	   Lebanese officials said five other air-to-surface missiles also
hit the hills around the villages of Nabi Sheet and Janta, about
five kilometers (three miles) west of the Syrian border.
	   The officials said a guerrilla from the Iranian-backed Hezbollah
was killed and another wounded in the attack. But a Hezbollah
official in Beirut said he was not aware of any guerrilla death.
	   The Hezbollah confirmed that its radio transmitter on the edge
of Nabi Sheet was destroyed. The radio, however, remained on the
air, apparently using a backup transmitter. No other details were
available.
	   In a statement, the Hezbollah called the Israeli raid an
``atrocious crime'' and threatened retaliation.
	   Israeli fighter bombers also fired four rockets earlier Tuesday
at suspected guerrilla bases facing Israel's self-styled ``security
zone'' in an occupied portion of South Lebanon. There were no
casualties from the raid.
	   Hezbollah, or the Party of God, has led the fight to try to oust
Israeli troops and their allied South Lebanon Army militia from the
security zone, which Israel set up in 1985 to protect its northern
towns from cross-border raids.
	   The bombing raids came after Hezbollah fighters exchanged fire
with Israeli troops and the SLA, the officials said.
 &UR; pvs-zk/vj
</TEXT>
