r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Airlines-Millennium     12-22 0262
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Airlines-Millennium,0266 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Companies will spend dlrs 2.3 billion to crack millennium bug
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   GENEVA (AP) _ Airlines will spend an estimated dlrs 2.3 billion
preparing their systems for the millennium and passengers need have
no fears about computer failure, the International Air Transport
Association said Tuesday.
	   ``Airplanes are not going to crash, of course,'' spokesman Tim
Goodyear said. Airlines are not going to put them in a situation
where they might crash.''
	   The association, which represents most of the world's air
carriers, has launched a project to make sure its members are ready
for the Year 2000 _ or Y2K _ bug, when computer systems which have
not been updated could fail because they only recognize the last
two digits of a year and assume it is 1900 instead of 2000.
	   IATA is spending dlrs 20 million carrying out personal visits to
702 airports and 74 air traffic control areas worldwide, while
other work will be carried out directly by the airlines.
	   IATA is monitoring airports around the world to ensure they are
making the necessary changes.
	   No total figure has been established for the cost to the air
transport industry of Y2K compliance. The dlrs 2.3 billion figure
represents the costs to airlines alone.
	   There have been widespread public fears that it might not be
safe to be in the air as the clock ticks to midnight at the turn of
the millennium. But Goodyear said these fears were unfounded.
	   ``The air transport industry sells itself on safety _ it has to
because it is under public scrutiny.''
</TEXT>
