<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Patent Law,0327 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Upper House of Parliament approves bill to change patent laws
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ The Upper House of Parliament on Tuesday
approved a bill to amend the 1970 patent laws to avoid penalties by
the World Trade Organization.
	   The leftist and socialist lawmakers walked out of the house
after they lost the vote 83-43.
	   The bill will now be introduced in the powerful lower house. It
seeks to provide exclusive marketing rights to foreign agrochemical
and pharmaceutical companies selling their products in the country.
	   The lower house is expected to pass the bill this week with
support from the governing Bharatiya Janata Party and the main
opposition Congress Party. It will then become a law.
	   On Tuesday, the government rejected amendments by leftist and
socialist parties which argued that working people will be hurt
because foreigners will destroy indigenous business.
	   Biplab Dasgupta (Communist Party of India- Marxist) and Rama
Shankar (Socialist Party) didn't accept reformists' view that
patent protections will make India a more attractive place to do
business for foreigners. They accused the government of
compromising national interests.
	   India is expected to start giving patents from the year 2005,
but the WTO has asked New Delhi to provide a mechanism to receive
applications beginning next April. The existing 1970 law catered
for process patent, but did not provide for product patent.
	   The amendment bill is part of economic reforms being pursued by
India since 1991, gradually dismantling its socialist-patterned
economy.
	   Its introduction was hastened by a WTO ruling in a dispute with
the United States that India was yet to fulfill its obligations in
providing marketing rights to foreign companies.
	   A panel set up by the Dispute Settlement Body of the WTO asked
India to immediately set up a mechanism for receiving patent
applications.
</TEXT>
