<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Tajikistan-Iran </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Iran to loan Tajikistan money for building roads
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Iran has agreed to give Tajikistan a dlrs 25
million loan to build roads and other infrastructure in the Central
Asian nation, which suffered heavy damage in a 5-year civil war, a
news report said Tuesday.
	   About 10 percent of the money will be used to build a highway
from Tajikistan to neighboring Pakistan and to buy road
construction equipment, Tajik Transport Minister Farrukha
Mukhitdinov told the Interfax news agency.
	   The rest of the money will go toward building electric power
stations, creating joint ventures and funding educational
institutions, he said.
	   The report did not say when the loan deal was signed.
	   Earlier this month, Iran agreed to help build a pharmaceutical
factory in Tajikistan.
	   Tajikistan's economy is in shambles following a civil war
between the secular government, which is backed by Russia, and the
mostly Islamic opposition. A truce signed last year ended
large-scale hostilities, but there are still periodic clashes.
	   (adc/ad)
</TEXT>
