<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Jamaica-Blood Shortage,0216 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
National blood bank running dry, tragic consequences predicted
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KINGSTON, Jamaica (AP) _ Jamaican hospitals are canceling
surgery and at least two patients may have died because the
national blood bank is running dry.
	   Technologists at the bank in Kingston, the capital, predict more
people could die over the Christmas season, when the Caribbean
island suffers more road accidents and other violence.
	   ``What is happening now is that we can only supply a third of
the demand of our hospitals. I predict some people will die,''
Mirth Treston, a medical technologist at the bank said Tuesday.
	   ``I know at least two men have died as a result of gunshot
injuries'' because no blood was available for transfusions, she
said.
	   Some hospital requests for blood from the bank have been turned
down and they have had to cancel some operations as a result, she
said.
	   Mobile clinics toured the island in a bid to collect blood last
week, but did not have much success. The bank blamed the shortage
on a lack of donors.
	   The national blood bank serves all but two of the island
hospitals. Cornwall Regional Hospital in northern Montego Bay
resort and University Hospital in Kingston, the island's only
training hospital, collect their own blood.
</TEXT>
