<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Ice Hockey-Bure-Belarus,0331 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Brother Valeri says Russian club wants Rocket
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CALGARY, Alberta (AP) _ Idled Russian right wing Pavel Bure, who
hasn't played for the Vancouver Canucks since requesting a trade in
the fall, has an offer to play in Belarus next season, according to
a published report.
	   Bure's brother and Calgary Flames right wing Valeri Bure told
the Calgary Herald the money in Belarus would be similar to the
money he would make in the North American National Hockey League.
	   Valeri Bure said Pavel was on television recently in Europe
explaining the offer from Belarus.
	   ``The president (of a club team) said that if nothing happens he
would pay him money to play in Belarus,'' Valeri Bure said.
	   ``I don't know what Vancouver is going to do, but he might not
even come back here. He might play in Belarus and make the same
type of money that he would here. That's what he said on
television. If nothing happens this year, he would probably go and
play for Belarus. It is a big statement for him to make in front of
a lot of people.''
	   Canucks general manager Brian Burke has taken a hard line on
Bure, maintaining from the outset he will not rush into a trade.
	   Pavel Bure is prohibited from playing for European teams because
he is under contract to the Canucks, who suspended him when he did
not report to the team's training camp. So far, Bure has lost more
than dlrs 1.8 million of his dlrs 5 million-per-season contract
because of the holdout.
	   Pavel has been skating with the Russian national team in Moscow
during the dispute.
	   The pair, who are close, haven't seen each other since August
when Pavel visited North America to celebrate the birth of Valeri's
child. But they speak frequently on the phone.
	   ``I talk to him and he sounds like he wants to get back, but he
can't let that get into his head,'' Valeri Bure said. ``It is
tough, though, for him to sit at home and watch the other guys
play.''
</TEXT>
