<SLUG> BC-Sierra Leone-Fighting, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sierra Leone's refugees flood capital, while rebels draw nearer
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES to ADD 5 grafs after 4th graf pvs on ECOMOG chief's
public appeal. ADDS byline. Pickup 5th graf pvs.
 &UR; By CLARENCE ROY-MACAULAY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   FREETOWN, Sierra Leone (AP) _ Thousands of refugees poured into
Sierra Leone's capital on Tuesday as fighting intensified between
rebel forces and Nigerian-led West African intervention troops
based in nearby towns.
	   Villagers carried their few possessions on their heads and
walked throughout the night to reach Freetown. In the city, they
slept in the sweltering sun along sidewalks while others pitched
tents and some sought shelter in shop doorways.
	   A number of refugees recounted images of rebel fighters burning
down houses and randomly killing civilians with assault rifles in
the town of Wellington, about 20 miles (35 kilometers) to the east.
There were unconfirmed reports of heavy fighting in other towns
closer to the capital.
	   Faced with the apparent setbacks, officials from the government
and the West African intervention force fighting on its behalf
instituted a press blackout, declining to speak to journalists
about the fighting and banning unauthorized dispatches.
	   ECOMOG commander Timothy Shelpidi issued a written appeal to
state radio late Tuesday for citizens to remain calm. Despite
attacks in Waterloo and other parts of the country causing a mass
refugee exodus, ECOMOG was in control of the security situation and
was ``seeking and destroying'' rebel hideouts, he said.
	   ``Do not panic and abandon your homes at the sound of gunfire,''
Shelpidi said. ``You need to be aware that the rebels are using
your fear to achieve their aims.''
	   Shelpidi warned refugees to beware of ``rebels who may have
mingled among you, pretending to be displaced people. Keep a
lookout for any suspicious movements.''
	   Yet he lashed out at civilians for spreading panic with false
rumors about the spread of hostilities.
	   ``We need your support to enable us to deal decisively with the
rebels,'' he said. ``We cannot do that if you panic and flood onto
the streets.''
	   Pickup 5th graf pvs. `Earlier this month ...' 	   
