w1859 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Turkey-SantaClausAd     12-22 0270
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Turkey-Santa Claus Ad </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Turkish St. Nicholas group incensed over Levis ad
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) _ A group that promotes St. Nicholas is
incensed over an ad by the Turkish branch of U.S. clothing
manufacture Levi Strauss and Co. because it contends the publicity
distorts the image of Santa.
	   The half-page ad in daily Hurriyet last week showed a
sad-looking Santa Claus sitting with his head bowed, with his
sleigh parked and his reindeers, with their heads cut off, hanging
on the wall.
	   The ad, announcing cut-price Levi's goods for the holiday
season, says Father Christmas will be made redundant this year
because ``there is no need to wait for gifts from anyone.''
	   In predominantly Muslim Turkey, people give each other gifts for
New Year.
	   ``Nobody has the right to show Father Christmas in such a
depressing mood especially on the eve of Christmas,'' Muammer
Karabulut, the president of the Father Christmas Foundation, said
Tuesday. ``Levi has damaged the holy image of Santa Claus, who
represents hope for children.''
	   The association promotes peace and the legend of St. Nicholas,
who is believed to have lived in the Turkish Mediterranean town of
Demre in the 4th century and given sacks of gold coins to dowryless
young girls.
	   ``We had no intention of humiliating Santa Claus,'' said Nil
Celik, a Levi Strauss official in Turkey. ``We canceled the
advertisement the day the foundation warned us.''
	   Karabulut said lawyers would ask the prosecutor's office on
Wednesday in Demre to launch a lawsuit against the San
Francisco-based clothing company.
	   (sh-sf-fd)
</TEXT>
