<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Spain-Budget,0129 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Spanish parliament approves 1999 budget
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MADRID (AP) _ Spain's parliament on Tuesday approved a
government budget for the coming year that aims to reduce the
country's budget deficit to 1.6 percent of gross national product,
down from the 2.4 percent expected for this year.
	   The spending plan also anticipates a decline in unemployment to
17.4 percent from rates above 19 percent, far higher than the
European average.
	   Finance Minister Rodrigo Rato said the budget is part of the
government's plan to erase the deficit by 2002 to promote a stable
climate for the euro, the common European currency to be introduced
Jan. 1.
	   Deputies from the ruling Popular Party approved the budget
Tuesday backed by deputies from regional parties.
</TEXT>
