<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 12/22/1998 13:19:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w1879 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo 3rdLd-Writethru   12-22 0735
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0735 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Violence persists as peace envoys and relief workers visit Kosovo
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS and UPDATES with US officials meeting Kosovo Albanian
guerrillas, quotes from the KLA, context, TRIMS &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos planned &QL; 
 &UR; By MISHA SAVIC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Ethnic Albanian guerrillas warned of
all-out war Tuesday unless Serb police pull out of central Kosovo,
amid new violence that left one ethnic Albanian dead and six others
in custody.
	   Also Tuesday, U.S. officials met with top guerrilla commanders
in Kosovo's rugged countryside in apparent effort to resuscitate a
de-facto truce increasingly frayed by bloodshed and possibly pave
the way for negotiations on the Serbian province's future.
	   The Serb-run Media Center reported that police pursuing
perpetrators of recent shootings killed one ``terrorist'' suspect
and arrested six others in the area. The source said the police
encountered fire and killed the ethnic Albanian when firing back.
	   The head of U.S. peace monitors in Kosovo, Shaun Byrns, and a U.
S. State Department official met top commanders of the Kosovo
Liberation Army in a remote village in central Kosovo.
	   The U.S. officials declined comment after the three-hour talks.
But KLA commander Jakub Krasniqi said: ``We hope that American and
European diplomacy will show more understanding for the KLA and
that they will support the Albanian people.''
	   The KLA has been stridently opposed to any plan for Kosovo that
stops short of independence for the Albanian-majority province, now
part of Serbia, the main Yugoslav republic
	   In the province's capital, Pristina, guerrilla spokesman Adem
Demaci warned police to leave central Kosovo, telling reporters:
``We promise, unless they withdraw from those areas, that they will
be attacked everywhere by our forces.''
	   Demaci said the police is not welcome in the parts of Kosovo
where there is no Serbian population.
	   Ethnic Albanians outnumber Serbs in Kosovo 9 to 1 and nearly all
demand independence. Hundreds have died and nearly 300,000 were
forced from their homes when ethnic tensions erupted into a war
this year.
	   The worst violence ended when Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic, pulled out under US pressure some government forces and
agreed to let 2,000 international peace verifiers into the
province.
	   But the head of the verifiers, William Walker, suggested his
people were being impeded, telling independent B 92 radio Tuesday
that the Belgrade ``authorities are generally uncooperative with
the mission.''
	   He said that most of the mission's requests to the authorities
``have drawn a negative response,'' according to B 92.
	   Walker also blamed ethnic Albanian rebels for breaking the
cease-fire agreement and acting ``irresponsibly by carrying out
provocative missions.''
	   Diplomatic efforts, and apparently the latest US meeting with
the guerrillas, are currently focused on bringing the KLA closer to
moderate ethnic Albanian leader Ibrahim Rugova.
	   The ethnic Albanian camp needs to be united before meaningful
negotiations can begin on Kosovo's future. However, the Serbian
government refuses to deal with the KLA, calling it a ``terrorist
group.'' And the Serbian stand _ no more than limited autonomy for
Kosovo _ is far removed from the independence demands voiced both
by the KLA and more indirectly by the Rugova camp.
	   In Belgrade, the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees, fresh from
a fact-finding trip in Kosovo, said that some 175,000 people have
still not returned to their homes, although they have found
shelter.
	   Commissioner Sadako Ogata shrugged off accusations, leveled at
her by a Serbian refugee official, that she was biased toward
Kosovo's ethnic Albanians.
	   ``I strongly condemn (continued) violence and intimidation'' by
both sides in Kosovo, Ogata told reporters, visibly annoyed by the
claims.
	   In Belgrade, heads of Yugoslavia's Serb-led army met Monday with
NATO's top commander in Europe, Gen. Wesley Clark, who repeated
warnings that the alliance might intervene if fighting between Serb
security forces and ethnic Albanian rebels continues, sources close
to the talks said on condition of anonymity.
	   Milosevic averted threatened NATO airstrikes when he signed the
October agreement, promising an end to the military campaign
against separatists.
</TEXT>
