<SLUG> BC-Israel-Politics, 5th Ld-Writethru,0613 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Israel's race for prime minister shapes up as a free-for-all
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS throughout. CHANGES byline. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos TLV101-102,JRL101-102 &QL; 
 &UR; By LAURA KING &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Even with his boss standing by, Israeli Foreign
Minister Ariel Sharon couldn't resist a little political joke.
Waving his hand at a group of low-level officials, he expressed
innocent surprise they weren't all running for prime minister.
	   Just about everyone else, it seems, is getting ready to jump
into the race.
	   On Tuesday, the first day of what's likely to be a long and
bruising electoral campaign, Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu was
bracing for an onslaught from all sides _ but expressing confidence
he would win ``utmost, massive'' voter support.
	   It was a notable show of bravado from a leader who only a day
earlier had been handed a stinging rejection of his peace policies
by lawmakers, who then voted overwhelmingly to hold early
elections.
	   It will be several more days before the lineup against Netanyahu
becomes clear, but at least half a dozen Israeli politicians have
announced candidacies or are weighing bids to become prime
minister. Balloting is expected by the end of April in what's
likely to be the last direct election for the post.
	   One of Netanhayu's toughest potential rivals, popular former
army chief of staff Lt. Gen. Amnon Lipkin Shahak, isn't campaigning
yet. He's still in the army and keeping quiet in line with military
regulations, but he's expected to be demobilized within days.
	   Another leading rival is Ehud Barak, head of the opposition
Labor party. He declared Tuesday that Netanyahu had ``lost the
trust'' necessary to negotiate any real peace with the
Palestinians.
	   Netanyahu brushed aside polls suggesting Barak could beat him by
a slim margin and Shahak by a wide one.
	   ``We will go to the people and the people will give us the
support to achieve peace with security,'' he told Israel radio.
	   Netanyahu's onetime finance minister, Dan Meridor, declared his
candidacy Tuesday, and quickly weighed in with a harsh assessment
of his former boss.
	   Meridor told Israel TV Netanyahu was ``a man who will say no in
the morning and yes in the evening ... a manipulator, a cynic, a
man who does not tell the truth.''
	   It also became clear Tuesday that Netanyahu would face a
leadership challenge from within the ranks of his own Likud party.
	   ``There must be a contest and it must be clean,'' lawmaker Uzi
Landau told Israel TV, indicating that if he himself didn't try for
the party leadership, he would back someone who did.
	   Netanyahu also sought Tuesday to deflect Palestinian complaints
that the peace process had already become a casualty of Israel's
political turmoil.
	   Saeb Erekat, the chief Palestinian negotiator, said Israel was
bound to honor the Wye accords despite the election upheaval, just
as it was committed to any other existing international agreement.
	   ``It's really unfortunate that the only thing that Mr. Netanyahu
has decided to stop is the peace process with us,'' Erekat told The
Associated Press.
	   Netanyahu, however, said Palestinian refusal to accept new
Israeli conditions for implementing the Wye River accord _ not the
election campaign _ was behind Israel's continuing freeze on
complying with the peace pact.
	   The prime minister's office said Israel will ``carry out its
part in the agreement without any relation to the election
schedule'' as soon as the Palestinians meet the latest conditions,
including a demand that they stop saying they will declare a
Palestinian state in May.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Israel-Politics, 5th Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
