<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-Russia-Moscow Journal,0792 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Moscow looking festive, but tinsel can't hide gloom
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With Russia-Economy &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo MOSB101 &QL; 
 &UR; By MITCHELL LANDSBERG &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ On orders of the mayor, Moscow is looking
downright festive these days.
	   Every store in the city is festooned with mandatory holiday
decorations. Streets are aglow with colored bulbs. The beaming face
of Grandfather Frost _ Russia's Santa Claus _ can be seen
everywhere, wishing the populace a Happy New Year.
	   With Mayor Yuri Luzhkov leading the way, Muscovites are throwing
themselves into the spirit of the season as best they can. But the
tinsel can't hide the gloom in the air. The economic crisis has
sharply cut most Russians' buying power, and holiday gift-buying
has become a depressing exercise in making do with less.
	   Merchants are especially downcast. Asked how business was going,
fur seller Valentina Goncharinko laughed bitterly. ``I can give you
a really short answer: It's really bad,'' she said.
	   Even in bad times, this is a magical time of year in the Russian
capital. The city is fully cloaked in snow, the air has an
invigorating bite to it (a nice way of saying it's frigid), the
theater, ballet and opera seasons are at their peak and people are
busy preparing for the big day.
	   That would be New Year's, not Christmas. After 70 years of
state-enforced atheism, Christmas is still largely an afterthought
here _ literally, since it falls on Jan. 7 on the Russian calendar.
But Russians celebrate New Year's much as many Westerners celebrate
Christmas, with alcohol-fueled family gatherings around the
``yolki,'' or New Year's tree, and gift exchanges with family and
friends.
	   One glance at the throngs now mobbing the city's shops and
outdoor markets would be enough to convince a newcomer to Moscow
that this city is still the post-communist boomtown some people
were describing a year or two ago.
	   At the upscale Manezh shopping mall, hard by the Kremlin,
teen-age mall rats cruise in packs and chic New Russians carry bags
bearing logos such as United Colors of Benetton, Nike and Lego.
	   At the new, Finnish-owned Stockmann's, a full-fledged,
three-level Western department store on the traffic-choked Garden
Ring Road, saleswomen startle shoppers with one of the rustiest
phrases in the Russian language: ``May I help you?''
	   And at the open-air Luzhniki market, the largest and busiest in
the former Soviet Union, throngs of shoppers push, shove, throw
elbows and lash tongues in some of the most spirited
urban-guerrilla shopping in the world.
	   But merchants say the crowds are thinner than last year, and
that people are buying less and driving harder bargains. Shoppers
agree that this will be a leaner, meaner New Year as a result of
the ruble devaluation and economic crash that hit Russia hard in
August.
	   The sky was sheet-metal gray and the weather unusually warm _
within a degree or two of freezing _ as Valentina Ivanova tried on
a muskrat fur coat at the Luzhniki market one day recently.
	   Underfoot, slush had become mixed with decomposing cardboard,
candy wrappers, plastic strapping cord and cigarette butts to form
a lumpy, brownish-black mass. Loud Turkish pop music blared from
loudspeakers; the smoke of cheap cigarettes mingled with the smell
of grilling meat from nearby food stands.
	   More than 4,000 vendors compete at Luzhniki from stalls offering
a head-spinning array of mostly inferior consumer products, from
Brand X children's toys to X-rated sex toys, from 50-cent socks to
dlrs 2.50 shirts and dlrs 9 rabbit-fur hats.
	   The coat Ivanova was trying, a brown model with spiky bristles,
was selling for dlrs 80. Her husband, who had promised her a fur
coat for New Year's, looked on admiringly as she flounced a bit in
a mirror held above the slush by a saleswoman, who cooed about how
good it looked. Finally, she took it off and decided to keep
looking.
	   She liked it, she said, but maybe she'd find something better
elsewhere.
	   Both she and her husband, Igor, are in the Russian air force,
and haven't received their salaries for months. The money they have
received is worth far less because of the ruble devaluation.
	   ``Last year, I could have bought two coats for this money,''
Ivanova said. ``Now, I can buy only one.''
	   Still, she and her husband were resolved to make the best of a
bad deal. They were looking forward to New Year's, and had already
bought a gift for their daughter _ a ``big'' toy that they refused
to describe further.
	   ``If people can,'' Ivanova said, ``they'll try to celebrate the
holiday in the nicest possible way.''
	   Then she turned and, arm in arm with her husband, slogged off
into the slush.
</TEXT>
