<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Homegrown Tunes, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
New Israeli law requires radio stations to play more local music
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES in grafs 3 and 4 with quote from law's sponsor;
CLARIFIES which stations will be affected, grafs 6, 7; minor
editing; ADDS byline.
 &UR; By MARK LAVIE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Half of all music played on Israeli stations
must be homemade, according to a law passed Tuesday by Israel's
parliament.
	   The law, which passed with bipartisan support, applies to Israel
state-run radio, army radio and privately-run regional stations _
although many radio stations already broadcast predominantly
domestic content.
	   Yona Yahav, the Labor party legislator who sponsored the new
measur, said the law was necessary to protect local artists.
	   ``A young culture must build protective barriers, just as
protective barriers are built around products,'' he said.
	   He noted that the law is declarative and does not include
penalties. ``Program producers will not be hauled off to jail,'' he
said, laughing.
	   Reshet Gimel, the state-run pop music station, has been on an
all-Israeli format in the early 1990s _ when MTV became available
in Israel.
	   The law does not apply to specific shows; instead, stations will
be expected to broadcast 50 percent Israeli content each month. How
they distribute it will be up to them.
	   The state-run classical music station will be exempted, as will
Israel's Arabic language service and a station that broadcasts
predominantly foreign language programs, for recent immigrants.
Other stations will be assessed on a monthly basis.
	   Some in the music business had questioned the need for the law,
saying that Israel's thriving recording industry benefited from
exposure to outside influences.
	   Backers of the law say there's plenty of foreign music already
available _ on MTV, on radio stations from neighboring Arab lands
and on pirate stations.
	   Benny Dudkevitch, a producer with Israel radio, said the new law
``will encourage more Israeli performers to record their music.''
 &UR; ml-rk	   
</TEXT>
