<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Balloon Quest, 10th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Round-the-world balloonists drift over China
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs; UPDATES, edits throughout &QL; 
 &UR; By AUDREY WOODS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Three round-the-world balloonists drifted high
over the Himalayas on Tuesday, hoping to catch a jetstream out of
prohibited Chinese airspace as quickly as possible.
	   ``We are going to look ... for the fastest, most direct route
out of China, which is what the balloon wants to do anyway,''
project director Mike Kendrick said after the Chinese balked at
approving the balloon's course.
	   British tycoon Richard Branson, American millionaire Steve
Fossett and Per Lindstrand of Sweden, aloft in the ICO Global
balloon heading eastward around the globe, had received permission
to cross China below 26 degrees north latitude.
	   But they drifted further north Monday after navigating around
Mediterranean storms and closed airspace over Iraq, Iran and
Russia.
	   The project ground crew, headed by Kendrick, said the Chinese
had asked the balloonists to land at the Lhasa airfield Tuesday
morning, but that the balloon overshot the field and it was
impossible to come down anywhere else.
	   Earlier in the day, Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao had
said China could not agree to the balloon's northerly course, but
he did not call on the crew to withdraw immediately or land.
	   As it became apparent early Monday that the balloon would
inevitably cross into unauthorized Chinese territory, Prime
Minister Tony Blair sent a message to Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji
asking for China's help.
	   The ICO Global project later said the Chinese government,
through the British Embassy in Beijing, had granted permission to
cross the country, on condition the balloon leave Chinese airspace
as soon as possible.
	   ``Thank you to the Chinese government,'' Branson said upon
hearing the news. ``We are embarrassed to have entered the airspace
without permission and relieved that they understand our
position.''
	   The craft was over Tibet, about 10 miles (15 kms) north of
Bhutan, at about 1300 GMT, but Kendrick said it was ``very
difficult to tell'' how long it would take to get out of Chinese
airspace.
	   Balloon pilots navigate by changing the lift of the balloon to
ascend or descend into different wind systems.
	   Kendrick said the crew could have created a problem by using up
a large amount of fuel to fly above the cloud base at 26,000 feet
(8,000 meters) to keep the balloon free of ice.
	   ``We have taken a long time to get where we are, clawing across
the Himalayas,'' he said. ``We have used more fuel than we would
have expected. We are going to have to assess the situation.''
	   The balloon had been moving through China at about 43 knots (48
mph), but Kendrick said the craft would need to reach 100 knots
(115 mph) to get around the world.
	   The crew members estimate the trip could last from eight days to
nearly three weeks. They hope to touch down somewhere in western
Europe at the end of a 24,000-mile (38,000 kms) flight, which will
take them over India, the South China Sea, the Pacific and the
United States.
	   The team secured permission from 97 countries for overflights
and initially had only four refusals _ Iran, Iraq, Russia and North
Korea.
	   Asked where the balloonists hoped to be Christmas Day, Kendrick
said, ``Somewhere in America, fingers crossed.''
	   (acw-kg)
</TEXT>
