<SLUG> BC-Germany-Tax Conviction </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Concert organizer guilty of tax evasion, gets five years eight
</HEADLINE>
months &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MANNHEIM, Germany (AP) _ The Mannheim state court on Tuesday
convicted a concert organizer of evading 15 million marks (dlrs 9
million) in taxes and sentenced him to five years and eight months
in prison.
	   Matthias Hoffmann, who has organized concerts for Luciano
Pavarotti, Jose Carreras, Placido Domingo and star soprano
Montserrat Caballe, among others, was visibly shaken when the
sentence was read.
	   Chief Judge Michael Meyer said Hoffmann had ``grossly worked to
his own advantage,'' in funneling money from concerts through
mailbox companies set up outside Germany ``to enrich himself.''
	   Meyer said Hoffmann was not a victim of poor tax advisors as his
defense had claimed, because they had been warned him repeatedly
that he was using illegal methods.
	   The judge said that the only thing positive about Hoffmann's
actions was that he had paid 6.5 million marks (dlrs 3.9 million)
in back taxes and his admission to guilt in the case.
	   The 47-year-old Hoffmann was released after posting a bond of
1.9 million marks (dlrs 1.1 million) until justice officials verify
trial procedures were correct before the sentence is activated.
	   Defense lawyers Egon Mueller and Alexander Keller said they
would decide within a week whether to appeal the sentence.
	   Pavarotti, Carreras, Domingo and Caballe, were named as suspects
last month for helping Hoffmann evade taxes.
	   Mannheim prosecutor Hubert Jobski said there were signs that the
four may have been involved, but that the investigation had only
started and could take months.
	   Hoffmann's trial began in October.
	   He was initially accused of using unreported payments and shell
companies in Ireland, London and elsewhere to evade almost 24
million marks (dlrs 15 million) in German taxes.
	   He had been in investigative custody since July 30.
	   (gb)
</TEXT>
