<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Switzerland-Weapons </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Swiss launch publicity campaign on new weapons laws
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By MATTHIAS BRUELLMANN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BERN, Switzerland (AP) _ Swiss authorities launched a big
publicity campaign Tuesday about a new nationwide gun law which
enters into force at the start of next year.
	   The new regulation _ which replaces a wide array of state ones _
introduces tighter licensing arrangements and restrictions on
foreigners buying or owning guns.
	   Switzerland has one of the world's highest rates of gun
ownership in the world, and the right to bear arms is steeped in
centuries-old tradition.
	   In a nation of less than seven million, there are said to be
about 4.5 million guns for recreation, hunting and self-defense. In
addition, every male who serves in the militia army has to keep his
assault rifle at home.
	   Despite this, the Alpine nation has one of the world's lowest
crime rates _ a fact frequently seized on by U.S. gun lobbies.
	   Faced with evidence in the early 1990's that guns brought in
Switzerland were being used in foreign wars and by terrorists, the
government drafted legislation to introduce more controls. This was
approved in a national referendum in 1993.
	   The new law is the outcome of that 1993 vote.
	   All nationals of former Yugoslavia are banned from buying
weapons. The government hopes this will reduce the number of guns
bought in Switzerland and smuggled for use in the war in Kosovo,
just as they were in Bosnia.
	   There will also be a ban on sales to people from Turkey _ which
is faced with a Kurdish insurgency _ Sri Lanka, Algeria and
Albania.
	   There will be stricter registration and ownership rules, and it
will be under central government control to end huge differences
between local cantons (states).
	   People who wish to carry a weapon for self-defense must obtain a
personal gun permit, having satisfied authorities that it is
essential and having passed a theoretical and practical
examination.
	   ``Fear alone is not enough,'' said Claude Mebes, from the
Federal Police's gun information service.
	   The big exceptions to this rule are hunters and sportsmen who
practice on rifle ranges dotted throughout the country. And, of
course, the army weapons.
	   To increase awareness of the new laws, authorities said they
were distributing 32,000 posters in key public places and at police
stations.
	   Current gun owners will have one year in which to obtain a
permit.
 &UR; (cn)
</TEXT>
