<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Canada-Swissair Crash, 2nd Ld,0309 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Remains of all Swissair 111 victims identified, 16 weeks after
</HEADLINE>
crash &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: SUBS last graf to CORRECT number of TWA 800 victims identified
by DNA alone &QL; 
 &UR; By DAVID CRARY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TORONTO (AP) _ Sixteen weeks after the crash of Swissair Flight
111 shattered the bodies of those on board, police said Tuesday
that remains of all 229 victims have been identified thanks to
state-of-the-art DNA techniques.
	   Police also said more than dlrs 1 million in U.S. currency has
been recovered from the wreckage on the ocean floor off Nova
Scotia. Still missing is a shipment of diamonds.
	   The impact of the Sept. 2 crash was so great that traditional
identification methods, including the use of dental and X-ray
records, were of minimal use in identifying the fragmented remains
retrieved from the Atlantic.
	   Blood samples were collected from relatives of those on board,
and the Royal Canadian Mounted Police coordinated an intensive
operation at several forensic laboratories around Canada to match
the samples with recovered remains.
	   RCMP officers, at a news briefing Tuesday in Halifax, Nova
Scotia, said DNA techniques had never before been used to such an
extent in the aftermath of an air disaster. They said recent
technological advances enabled them to complete tasks in days that
might previously have taken weeks.
	   The RCMP recommended that airlines henceforth keep fingerprint
and DNA records of their crew members to make identifications
easier.
	   By comparison, the vast majority of the 230 passengers who died
aboard TWA Flight 800, which crashed off the New York coast in
1996, were identified by dental records, either alone or in
combination with other methods. Only a few dozen of the 230 remains
were identified through DNA.
