w1923 &Cx1f; wstm-
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Olympics-Polan     12-22 0419
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Olympics-Poland </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Zakopane official calls banning trips by IOC members `strange'
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By BEATA PASEK &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   WARSAW, Poland (AP) _ Banning International Olympic Committee
members from visiting potential host cities would be ``a strange
solution'' to the ongoing Olympic bribery scandal, an official in
Zakopane's bid campaign said Tuesday.
	   The southern Poland mountain resort is one of six bidders for
the 2006 Olympics. Now it may have to alter its strategy if IOC
President Juan Antonio Samaranch enforces his call to halt visits
by voting IOC members to bid cities because of the bribery
allegations.
	   ``Changing the rules in the middle of competition is a strange
solution,'' said Piotr Bak, deputy mayor of Zakopane.
	   He said Zakopane sent invitations to all of the more than 100
IOC members and had expected a ``significant number'' to visit.
	   Zakopane planned to jointly host the IOC members with nearby
Poprad, Slovakia _ which is part of a separate bid to host the 2006
Games _ to lower the cost, Bak said.
	   An IOC committee evaluating bid cities spent three days in
Zakopane in early November. During the visit, committee chairman
Chiharu Igaya declared Zakopane fit to host the games, but stressed
that it must resolve a controversy over access to its Tatra
mountain reserve.
	   Environmental groups, intellectuals and some political leaders
have criticized the Polish bid, saying the construction and
alterations needed to stage the Olympics would permanently damage
the pristine Tatra mountains in violation of environmental laws.
	   Organizers of the games in Zakopane planned to hold 39 events in
the Tatra National Park, noted Wojciech Byrcyn, director of the
park designated a natural reserve by the United Nations
Educational, Scientific and Cultural Organization in 1992.
	   He called the devastation associated with hosting the Olympics
``crazy.''
	   But Bak said experts would evaluate the environmental effects
and proposals deemed harmful would be changed. Polish officials
previously have suggested holding some skiing events at Poprad to
prevent alterations in the Tatra National Park.
	   Other competitors for the 2006 Games are Poprad-Tatry in
Slovakia; Sion, Switzerland; Turin, Italy; a joint bid by Helsinki,
Finland, and Lillehammer, Norway; and Klagenfurt, Austria, making a
three-country bid that includes regions of Slovenia and Italy.
	   The IOC will choose the winner in June.
	   (bp-tsc)
</TEXT>
