r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EuroAdvisory     12-22 0278
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Euro Advisory,,0284 </SLUG>


<TEXT>
	   EDITORS
	   The introduction of the euro, a common currency for 11 countries
in Europe, on Jan. 4 will bring several changes to two AP financial
market fixtures. Here's a rundown:
	    &UR; FOREIGN CURRENCY TABLES &QC; 
	   Starting with tables produced Monday, Jan. 4, quotes for the ECU
and its forward contracts will be listed as euro. This item is
slugged BC-US-Foreign Exchange and moves to all points.
	   The currencies from the 11 participating countries will still
appear in the table. There will be a three-year transition period
during which euros and the existing national currencies will both
be recognized as legal tender.
	   However, during this time, the national currencies from the 11
countries will be locked to the euro, meaning that they will move
in unison against the dollar and other currencies as the euro does.
	   The 11 countries launching the euro are Austria, Belgium,
Ireland, Italy, Finland, France, Germany, Luxembourg, the
Netherlands, Spain and Portugal.
	    &UR; FOREIGN STOCK TABLES &QC; 
	   Starting Jan. 4, tables that show the prices of stocks traded in
the 11 countries using the euro will be quoted in euros. This item
is slugged BC-Europe Markets, which moves to subscribers in Europe
and Latin America.
	   The list that moves Dec. 31 will contain the current stock price
and the previous stock price in the existing currency. The list
that moves Jan. 4 will have both prices in euros.
	   The exchanges affected are: Amsterdam, Brussels, Frankfurt,
Madrid, Milan, Paris. Exchanges in the list that won't be changing
are: Johannesburg, London, Stockholm and Zurich.
	    &UR; The AP
</TEXT>
