<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Argentina-Obit-Mignone,0207 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Argentine human rights activist, Emilio Mignone, dead at 76
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) _ Emilio Fermin Mignone, an
Argentine human rights activist who fought to reveal the abuses
suffered under past military dictatorship, has died. He was 76.
	   Mignone died Monday night, said a spokesman for the Center of
Legal and Social Studies, a human rights group Mingone helped
found.
	   The May 1976 disappearance of his daughter, Monica, motivated
Mignone to begin his tireless crusade in defense of human rights in
Argentina.
	   Under a military junta which ruled Argentina from 1976-83, some
9,000 people disappeared, the government has said. Human rights
groups insist the number is closer to 30,000.
	   Two years after the military's fall, in 1985, Mignone was an
important witness in the public trials of the junta's former
leaders.
	   He later founded the Center of Legal and Social Studies, one of
Argentina's leading human rights organizations. He also wrote
several books about the country's darkest chapter, including ``The
Church and the Dictatorship'' and ``The Violation of Human Rights
in Argentina.''
	   He is survived by his wife, Angelica Paula Sosa, and four
daughters.
</TEXT>
