<SLUG> BC-Greece-Mother's Mission,0201 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Woman's body exhumed after mother tracks down alleged killers
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo SAL101 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   SALONICA, Greece (AP) _ The body of a Greek student was exhumed
for tests Tuesday after her mother claimed to have tracked down her
alleged killers by disguising herself as a prostitute.
	   Case files on 20-year-old Paraskevi Fotiadou, who a coroner said
died of a heroin overdose in June, were reopened this month as a
result of her mother's investigation.
	   Eleni Fotiadou, 44, posed as a hooker and a drug addict to delve
into this northern port city's underworld in an effort to find out
how her daughter died.
	   She said that with the help of a private investigator, she spent
weeks among prostitutes, drug dealers and addicts to gather video
and audio tapes as evidence.
	   As a result, authorities announced on Dec. 3 that eight people
were indicted in connection with the case and face charges
including gang rape and murder.
	   Fotiadou believes her daughter did not die of a heroin overdose,
but was brutally raped, murdered and then injected with drugs to
make the death appear drug-related.
	   The forensic tests on the exhumed body could take weeks.
</TEXT>
