<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Turkey-Bugging Scandal </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Former Turkish minister implicated in wiretapping scandal
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By SELCAN HACAOGLU &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) _ A small party has asked the prosecutor's
office to investigate a former interior minister for allegedly
illegally eavesdropping on the country's top-selling newspaper, a
party official said Tuesday.
	   The bid by the leftist Freedom and Solidarity Party came after
the former minister, Meral Aksener, disclosed transcripts of
telephone conversations between a prominent writer of daily
Hurriyet and a minister.
	   ``This is Turkey's Watergate,'' said Atilla Aytemur, a party
official. ``Aksener has to resign immediately as a deputy and be
brought before justice.''
	   Aksener presented the tapes last week with a claim that Hurriyet
maintained close business ties with the government.
	   In the tapes, Hurriyet's editor-in-chief Ertugrul Ozkok and
state minister Gunes Taner were discussing a state loan the paper
asked for a cardboard factory.
	   Ozkok, who confirmed the conversation, was interrogated on
Tuesday in an investigation ordered by Premier Mesut Yilmaz.
	   Ozkok has also petitioned the prosecutor's office for the trial
of Aksener.
	   Aksener is a deputy chairperson of former premier Tansu Ciller's
center-right True Path Party.
	   Conviction for wiretapping without a court order can bring a
sentence of up to three years in prison.
	   Aksener has claimed the tapes, including other conversations by
Hurriyet officials, were given to her by a ``patriot.'' But
newspapers charged that she had her own telephone taping gang
within the interior ministry.
	   Ozkok has contended his responsibilities required him to deal
with the trade affairs of the paper as a highest-ranking official
as well.
	   (sh-fd)
</TEXT>
