<HEADLINE>
Guardians, inmates injured in Turkish prison unrest
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   IZMIR, Turkey (AP) _ A group of leftist inmates on Tuesday
attacked prison wards with water pipes dismantled from a ward in a
second day of clashes at a prison in this Aegean port city, the
Anatolia news agency reported.
	   Four prison guards and three inmates, belonging to the outlawed
Turkish Revolutionary Communists Union, were slightly injured.
	   The attack was staged in support of another group of leftist
prisoners who on Monday assaulted prison guards with broken glass
after setting their ward on fire to protest the arrest of some of
their comrades. Eight guards were slightly injured in the fighting
and the small blaze was quickly extinguished.
	   The rioting erupted when a group of supporters were taken away
by police Monday for chanting obscenities at security officials
outside the gates of Izmir's Buca prison.
