</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NIreland-Omagh's Last Victim </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Against the odds, last of Omagh's 370 wounded finally goes home
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With AP Photo XBFT101
 &UR; By SHAWN POGATCHNIK &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) _ She lost her baby girl and
nearly her own life.
	   But against the odds of medical science a Catholic homemaker
finally walked out of hospital Tuesday _ more than four months
after being caught in ground zero of Northern Ireland's worst-ever
terrorist attack.
	   Tracey Devine, 27, suffered a slashed face and burns all over
her body when Irish Republican Army dissidents detonated a car bomb
in Omagh, a religiously mixed market town 60 miles (100 kms) west
of Belfast. In all, 29 people died and 370 were wounded in the Aug.
15 blast.
	   Mrs. Devine spent six weeks in a coma in Belfast's Royal
Victoria Hospital. When she awoke, her husband Paul had to tell her
their youngest child, 21-month-old Breda, was among the dead.
	   ``It was one of the hardest things I ever had to do,'' he said,
holding hands with his wife, whose head remains tightly bound with
a plastic face guard, neck brace and bandages. ``She did cope with
it quite well.''
	   Mrs. Devine retains clear memories of the day she traveled from
her village of Donemana to Omagh, accompanied by Breda, her brother
Gary and fiancee Donna Marie. Like so many others, they were
shepherded nearer the bomb by police responding to a misleading
phoned warning.
	   ``The bomb went off right beside us. Wee Breda disappeared in a
flash of light,'' she said, noting that her brother and future
sister-in-law also suffered serious burns.
	   The breakaway IRA faction responsible later called a cease-fire,
though none of its members has been directly charged in connection
with the atrocity.
	   ``I hope somebody forgives them because I never will,'' she
said.
	   Her plastic surgeon, Dr. Mohammed Riaz, said she had stood less
than 30 percent chance of survival but ``proved to be a fighter.''
	   Although she had already endured more than 30 hours of
operations to reconstruct parts of her face and body torn by
shrapnel, Riaz said, ``She's going to require a lot more to get
these scars settled down. It's a long way to go yet.''
	   But those worries are for another day, Mrs. Devine said.
	   ``It's really great to be getting home _ home for Christmas with
the other children,'' she said of Anne, 6, Niamh, 4 and Shay, 2.
``They know Breda won't be coming back, but they're glad they're
going to get their mummy back for Christmas.''
	   (sp-rs)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-NIreland-Omagh's Last Victim; CT:i; 
