expected, demonstrating again the ECB's capacity to surprise
markets.
	   Markets were taken by surprise by coordinated rate cuts on Dec.
3 by the 11 euro nations launching the euro.
	   The ECB hopes markets will interpret the bank's ability to
spring surprises as a sign of strength.
	   With just over a week remaining to the begin of the historic
project of currency union, Duisenberg called on governments
launching the euro to stick to promised budgetary discipline.
	   ``Continue to exude ... the political impetus to achieve over
the medium-term balanced budgets and even a small surplus,''
Duisenberg said.
	   ``What I would advise governments to do is to inspire that
feeling of continuity and stability - sooner rather than later.''
	   Calling the euro-zone's core interest rate of 3 percent ``very
low by historical standards,'' Duisenberg said further cuts were
unlikely.
	   ``Markets _ don't expect a change of interest rates in the near
future.''
	   Europe's economy, burdened by instability in the global economy,
has grown by just 2.4 percent in the third quarter over the
previous quarter, about half a percent lower than the average
growth in the first six months compared to 1997's first six months.
	   ``The outlook for the euro area economy is still very much
influenced by the uncertainties surrounding the evolution of the
world economy in 1999,'' Duisenberg said, with industrial
confidence down. He said the ECB would monitor rising wage demands
in some countries as they could create inflation.
	   Despite the uncertain international situation, Duisenberg said
he was optimistic.
	   ``As far as Europe is concerned, (the euro) is being launched
under optimal economic conditions.''
	   From Jan. 1, the 11 national currencies will become
sub-divisions of the euro. Only the ECB will have the authority to
issue national bank notes and approve the volume of coins.
	   By spring, the ECB would have in place prodecures for the 11
national central banks to request authorization to issue national
bank notes.
	   The euro will be phased in slowly. National currencies will
circulate until Jan 1, 2002, when they will be replaced by the new
currency.
 &UR; dkt-gb
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
