<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Iraq-Germany </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
German minister supports U.S. and Britain over Iraqi airstrikes
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-Iraq, BC-Germany-Iraq
 &UR; With AP Photo LON104, LON105

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ The Ministry of Defense on Tuesday detailed some
of the sites targeted by last week's four-day U.S.-British
airstrike against Saddam Hussein's Iraqi regime, as Germany's
defense minister repeated his country's backing for the military
action.
	   ``The German government has made clear we are supporting the
United States and the United Kingdom because military action,
regrettably, was necessary,'' Rudolf Scharping said at a news
conference after talks with his British counterpart, George
Robertson.
	   Scharping's opinion differed from that of German Foreign
Secretary Joschka Fischer, who said in a German TV interview late
Monday that efforts to tame Iraq were a ``no-win situation'' that
war would not solve, and called for ``a combination of continuing
disarmament controls in Iraq with humanitarian measures and a
step-by-step lifting of sanctions.''
	   Scharping, however, called Saddam Hussein a ``political
gangster.''
	   ``Such a state as Iraq has to respect the decisions of the
(United Nations) Security Council. If not, military action is
necessary,'' Scharping said. ``We hope after that military action,
Iraq is ready to act in full compliance with the United Nations.''
	   At a Ministry of Defense briefing, Air Marshall John Day, deputy
chief of Britain's defense staff, said that 85 of the 100 sites
targeted by the airstrikes were hit, with 74 percent classified as
successful missions.
	   Day said that 16 of the strikes were against surface-to-air
missile sites, and 18 were against integrated air defense systems.
In both cases, the Royal Air Force carried out three of the
attacks.
	   Day said that 18 sites providing security for Iraqi attempts to
develop weapons of mass destruction were hit, as were 12 industrial
sites connected to the weapons program.
	   The U.S.-British airstrikes also targeted 20 command and control
sites, six airfields, nine Republican Guard sites, and one economic
target, Day said.
	   Eleven out of the 100 missions were flown by Royal Air Force
Tornado GR1 fighter-bombers stationed 35 miles from the southern
Iraqi border in Kuwait, Day said, adding that the British success
rate in missions was similar to that of the United States.
	   Day said that British bomb damage assessments were deliberately
conservative, ``because it is important the results are right,
particularly where subsequent action depend on those results.''
	   ``For instance, we would wish to be very sure of an assessment
that a surface-to-air missile system had been destroyed before
permitting aircrew to ignore that site during subsequent mission
planning,'' said Day.
	   Day said the action had significantly damaged Saddam's ability
to produce and repair ballistic missiles, and had also hit his L29
unmanned aircraft program.
	   ``As a consequence of our attacks on his military capability,
and particularly on those forces closely associated with his
weapons of mass destruction concealment program, those close to
Saddam will realize that we have the ability to target the regime
as distinct from the Iraqi people,'' Day said.
	   Iraq's refusal to cooperate fully with United Nations inspectors
searching for weapons of mass destruction prompted the United
States and Britain to attack last week, both nations have said.
President Bill Clinton and British Prime Minister Tony Blair
declared a halt to the effort Saturday evening.
	   (rs)
</TEXT>
