<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Poland-Miners, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Talks on ending miners' protest fail to reach agreement
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs; UPDATES with talks ended, comments from participants;
ADDS details; changes byline &QL; 
 &UR; By TOM COHEN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   WARSAW, Poland (AP) _ Talks intended to resolve a growing labor
dispute in Poland failed to reach agreement Tuesday, and a union
official said workers' protests would continue.
	   Hundreds of coal miners have joined an underground sit-in at
more than 50 mines in southern Poland to demand that their early
retirement pension plan for working in dangerous conditions should
remain intact.
	   In a separate protest, scores of miners gathered Tuesday in
Warsaw to urge President Aleksander Kwasniewski to veto pension law
changes passed by parliament and awaiting his signature.
	   Miners also staged a warning strike Monday, during which they
voted overwhelmingly for a national strike on an undetermined date,
probably in mid-January, if their demands remain unmet.
	   The bill passed by parliament this month changes pension rules
to make the retirement age 65 for men and 60 for women. Current
rules pay full pensions to miners and others working in dangerous
conditions who have 25 years of duty, no matter their age.
	   Prime Minister Jerzy Buzek said before Tuesday's talks between
government, employer and labor officials that he expected an
agreement. He said his government never intended to eliminate the
early retirement pensions.
	   But after the meeting, which lasted more than two hours,
management and union officials provided differing versions of what
happened.
	   Wojciech Kornowski, head of the Confederation of Polish
Employers, said miners would receive so-called ``bridge'' pensions
of 70 percent of their monthly wages if they retire with 25 years
of service before the legal age, the PAP state news agency
reported. They would receive the regular full pension when they
reach the legal retirement age.
	   Details of the plan _ such as who will pay for the bridge
pensions _ still needed to be worked out, with more talks scheduled
between the government and employers in early January, Kornowski
said. He added that the offer should end the miners' protests.
	   But Henryk Nakonieczny, leader of the Solidarity union's
National Hard Coal Mining section, said the talks produced no
written agreement.
	   ``Tomorrow we shall determine how to continue the protest,'' he
said, according to the PAP report.
	   Solidarity miners, who began the sit-in Dec. 10, also oppose a
mining restructuring plan that would cut jobs and production.
	   Buzek's Solidarity-led governing coalition, which took power in
October 1997 from a leftist government, has been working on
widespread social and economic reforms expected to complete
Poland's transition from communism to a market economy.
	   The reforms include restructuring ailing industries such as
mining and steel. Coal mining restructuring calls for reducing
production from 137 million tons last year to 110 million tons in
2002, as well as cutting jobs by more than 40 percent _ from
245,000 now to 138,000 in three years.
	   Coal mining, once the country's leading hard-currency earner
during communist times, is still heavily subsidized under Poland's
market reforms that began in 1989.
	   (ajs-tsc)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Poland-Miners, 2nd Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
