w1968 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Russia-PulpMill     12-22 0237
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Pulp Mill </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Official urges closure of Russian pulp mill to save Lake Baikal
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ A major Siberian pulp mill must be closed or
rehauled to save the environment around Lake Baikal, where toxic
waste is killing animals and plants, a government official said
Tuesday.
	   A recent inspection of the Baikal Pulp and Paper Mill revealed
``systematic violations of environmental laws,'' the ITAR-Tass news
agency quoted Viktor Kutsenko, head of the safety department of the
State Environment Committee, as saying.
	   The plant is spilling highly toxic waste directly into Lake
Baikal and contaminating the ground water with other waste
products, he said.
	   The lake is home to nearly 1,000 animal species found nowhere
else in the world and holds about 20 percent of the world's supply
of fresh water.
	   Kutsenko recommended that the mill be shut down or redesigned to
be environmentally safe, ITAR-Tass said. It was unclear what
influence Kutsenko's recommendation would have.
	   The plant insists such a conversion would cripple it
financially.
	   The mill was built 30 years ago, and mainly supplied the Soviet
aircraft industry.
	   Environmental groups have been calling for the its shutdown for
years. Last year, dozens of Lake Baikal's unique species of
freshwater seals died mysteriously, and environmentalists blamed it
on chemical waste from the mill.
	   (adc)
</TEXT>
