w1992 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Italy-KurdishRebel 2ndLd-Writethru   12-22 0374
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Italy-Kurdish Rebel, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Prosecutor requests new arrest warrant for Kurdish rebel
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDs: UPDATES with Italian premier's office declining to comment on
Ukraine angle &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ A day after saying it might be possible for an
Italian court to rule in favor of extraditing Kurdish rebel leader
Abdullah Ocalan to Turkey on some charges, a Rome magistrate was
pushing Tuesday to put him back in jail so he couldn't flee Italy.
	   Italy has so far refused to extradite Ocalan, citing laws that
forbid it from extraditing suspects to countries where they face
the death penalty. But Rome prosecutor Giovanni Malerba indicated
on Monday that Ocalan could be extradited for crimes that do not
carry the death penalty.
	   Turkey considers Ocalan a terrorist and is the country's No. 1
fugitive.
	   Ocalan, who heads the Kurdistan Workers Party, or PKK, was
arrested Nov. 12 when he flew into Rome from Moscow. He was ordered
set free a week later but also ordered not to leave Rome.
	   Last week, Rome's appeals court lifted all restrictions on the
Kurdish rebel after Germany withdrew an international arrest
warrant it had issued against him for its own terrorism charges.
	   It is now up to Italy's justice minister to decide whether to
take up Malerba's request for a new arrest warrant.
	   Ocalan has requested political asylum in Italy, but Premier
Massimo D'Alema's center-left government is split over what to do.
	   The possibilities mentioned in both Italian and Turkish media
include sending Ocalan to a third-country. In recent days, South
Africa, Libya, Pakistan or North Korea have been mentioned as
possibilities.
	   On Tuesday, Turkey's private television station TGRT reported
that Italy planned to expel Ocalan to Ukraine and had allegedly
already found him an apartment there. The station said Italian
Industry Minister Pierluigi Bersani had informed Turkish officials
about this during a recent trip to Turkey.
	   The Italian premier's office on Tuesday night declined to
comment on the Ukraine angle, which it called the latest rumor.
	   Close to 37,000 people have been killed since Ocalan's rebel
group began fighting for autonomy in southeast Turkey in 1984.
	   (vg-fd) 	   
</TEXT>
