<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Italy-Telecom Rates </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Italy lowers some phone rates
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ The Italian telecommunications regulator said
Tuesday that it will leave local telephone tariffs unchanged and
reduce regional and long-distance rates in the first stage of
repricing.
	   As of Feb. 1, regional rates will drop by 7 percent and
international rates will fall by 9.6 percent.
	   The first phase of repricing will be followed by moves in March
and July.
	   In that second phase, the authority will switch many calls to
local tariffs from regional tariffs.
	   Measurement of phone calls in seconds instead of usage units
will be phased in between April 1 and June 30.
	   The regulator also aims to switch tariff setting for mobile
phone calls to mobile operators from fixed-line operators.
	   As part of a European Union agreement, Italy is to complete the
necessary repricing of long distance and local phone tariffs by
July.
	   (dj-fd)
</TEXT>
