<SLUG> BC-Egypt-Libya </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Egyptian, Libyan foreign ministers discuss Lockerbie, Iraq
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ The foreign ministers of Egypt and Libya on
Tuesday discussed the possible trial of two Libyan suspects in the
1988 Lockerbie bombing, and the U.S.-Britain airstrikes on Iraq.
	   Egypt's Middle East News Agency said Foreign Minister Amr Moussa
and his Libyan counterpart, Omar al-Muntasser, discussed the
Lockerbie issue in the light of the Libyan Parliament's approval
for trying the suspects in a third country.
	   It gave no other details.
	   The two ministers also discussed the Iraq crisis and the U.N
sanctions imposed on Iraq after it invaded Kuwait in 1990, the
agency said. Al-Muntasser arrived in Cairo Monday.
	   Libya already has accepted in principle to the trial of the two
suspects before a panel of Scottish judges in the Netherlands but
demanded that, if convicted, they should be jailed in Libya.
	   The Dec. 21, 1988 bombing of the Pan Am jet over Lockerbie,
Scotland, killed 270 people.
	   The General People's Congress, Libya's parliament, also gave its
conditional approval last week for the trial of the two men in a
country other than the United States or Britain.
	   The United States and Britain insist that the two men should
spend the jail term in Britain.
	   U.S. President Bill Clinton, speaking at a memorial service
Monday on the bombing's 10th anniversary, warned that the United
States would seek even stronger measures against Libya if the
suspects were not turned over.
	   Libya is under U.N. air sanctions aimed at forcing its
government to hand over the suspects.
