<HEADLINE>
Mohamed Al Fayed to judge Miss Universe 1999, Oprah Winfrey maybe
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ROBERT HOFFMAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   CHAGUARAMAS, Trinidad (AP) _ Mohamed Al Fayed _ owner of
London's famed Harrods department store and father of the late
Princess Diana's beau, Dodi _ will be one of the judges at the 1999
Miss Universe Pageant.
	   Prime Minister Basdeo Panday said he also hoped American
television celebrity Oprah Winfrey would join Al Fayed on the
judge's dais for the beauty contest here on May 26.
	   Panday made the announcement Tuesday at a ``sod-turning''
ceremony to launch the renovation of a 55,000-square-foot
(5,000-square-meter) former U.S. Navy hangar into a Hollywood-style
stage for the event.
	   The pageant will be broadcast live to about 2.5 billion people
from the hangar, near Chaguaramas Bay on the lush northwestern
peninsula of the Caribbean island.
	   ``This marks the start of one of the largest promotional
projects ever embarked on by this country,'' Panday said. ``We seek
to brand Trinidad and Tobago as a destination with a favorable
climate for major investment, tourism and export of goods and
services.''
	   His government is pushing to promote tourism and and help shift
the economy from its almost total dependency on petroleum, natural
gas and manufacturing.
	   Dodi Fayed died along with the princess in a Paris car crash
last year.
