<SLUG> BC-Finland-Mobile Mania,0197 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cellular phones more common than household lines in Finland
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HELSINKI, Finland (AP) _ Finns have indulged their famed
infatuation with technology so deeply that there are now more
cellular phones than regular telephone subscriptions in the
country.
	   The Ministry of Transport and Communications said Tuesday that
56 out every 100 people in the country own cellular phones, and
more are buying every day. An estimated 60,000 new subscribers come
every month, the ministry said.
	   That puts the number of mobile subscriptions slightly above the
2.9 million fixed-line phone subscriptions, which includes both
business and private users, the ministry said.
	   ``In 1997, we made a cautious prediction to cross 50 percent
coverage by the year 2000 - but it happened in August this year.
The growth has been incredibly strong,'' said Mikael Akermarck, a
researcher at the ministry.
	   Mobile phone maker Nokia, which claims to be the world's
largest, is based in Finland.
	   The growth in fixed phone line subscriptions has leveled off
completely and many households now own several mobile phones, he
added.
</TEXT>
