<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-Notes,1002 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Another O'Meara feat: king of the silly season
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By DOUG FERGUSON &QC; 
 &UR; AP Golf Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ORLANDO, Florida (AP) _ Already the Masters and British Open
champion, winner of the World Match Play Championship and PGA Tour
player of the year, Mark O'Meara's sensational season comes to a
close with yet another honor: king of the silly season.
	   The silly season _ now referred to by the PGA Tour as the
``challenge season'' _ includes limited field events (Million
Dollar Challenge) that use different formats (Skins Game, Shark
Shootout) and don't always count toward the world rankings (Grand
Slam).
	   Of players who took part in at least two such events, O'Meara
was the top money-earner with dlrs 730,000. That was enough to
finish ahead of _ who else? _ Tiger Woods, who won dlrs 650,000.
	   Nick Price actually won more, but his dlrs 1 million came from
one tournament, the Million Dollar Challenge in Sun City, South
Africa.
	   O'Meara pocketed dlrs 150,000 from the PGA Grand Slam of Golf, a
record dlrs 430,000 from the Skins Game and dlrs 150,000 from Sun
City. Woods won dlrs 400,000 by beating Vijay Singh in the Grand
Slam, then picked up another dlrs 250,000 from his playoff loss to
Price in Sun City.
	   In third place was Tom Lehman, who made dlrs 480,000. That's
nearly half of what he made during his injury-plagued regular
season. Lehman picked up the bulk of his money from the Skins, and
also got dlrs 60,000 from winning the Pebble Beach Invitational.
	   ___ &QC; 
	    &UR; BIG MONEY: &LR;  Finishing in the top 64 in the world rankings by
Feb. 15 will be worth at least dlrs 25,000.
	   The International Federation of PGA Tours has completed the
distribution of the dlrs 5 million purses for the three World Golf
Championships events next year, starting with the Andersen
Consulting Match Play Championship at La Costa Resort.
	   The winner of each event gets dlrs 1 million, while last place
is guaranteed at dlrs 25,000.
	   Runner-up at the Match Play and the NEC Invitational, for Ryder
Cup and Presidents Cup players, will be dlrs 500,000, while second
place for the Stroke Play Championship will be a meager dlrs
400,000.
	   Other payoffs for the Match Play in February: dlrs 400,000 for
third place, dlrs 300,000 for fourth, dlrs 150,000 for
quarterfinalists, dlrs 75,000 for making the third round, dlrs
50,000 for the second round.
	   Prize money is official, but counts only toward a player's
designated home tour.
	   ___ &QC; 
	    &UR; USGA AWARDS: &LR;  The USGA has chosen 1981 Senior Amateur champion
Edgar Updegraff to receive its top honor _ the Bob Jones Award,
presented annually since 1955 to recognize distinguished
sportsmanship in golf.
	   ``This was entirely unexpected and a little wondrous,'' said
Updegraff, 76, a retired urologist from Tucson, Ariz.
	   Updegraff completed in 17 U.S. Amateurs, six Masters and three
Walker Cup matches during his amateur career. Among his golf
highlights are making his first Walker Cup team in 1963 and a long
chat he had with Jones during the 1962 Masters. His best Masters
finish was a tie for 44th in 1966.
	   Frank Aglim of Dallas, a longtime rules official involved in
golf administration for nearly 50 years, won the Joseph C. Dey
Award for meritorious volunteer service. Noel Jackson of Kingston,
Rhode Island won the Green Section Award for his work with turf.
	   The awards will be presented Feb. 6 at the USGA's annual meeting
in Clearwater, Florida.
	   ___ &QC; 
	    &UR; MASTERS DOWN UNDER: &LR;  Add another Masters to Greg Norman's
schedule _ the Australian Masters.
	   Norman, who has won the event six times but has refused to play
since his breakup with International Management Group, has agreed
to play in it for the first time since 1994. IMG organizes a number
of Australian tournaments.
	   The Australian Masters is the second week in February, right
after Norman's Holden International, which he won last year. In a
statement released by IMG, Norman said he was ``proud of his
Australian Masters'' record and looking forward to returning to
Huntingdale.
	   He reportedly will get an appearance fee of about dlrs 300,000.
	   ___ &QC; 
	    &UR; FANTASY LEAGUE FILE: &LR;  Sal Johnson knew his massive Pro Golf
guide was successful when he started work on the second edition and
found there wasn't much on which to improve.
	   Pro Golf '99, published by Golfweek and released this month, is
a 204-page look at everything there is to know about PGA Tour
events and 201 players, from David Duval and Tiger Woods to Scott
Gump and Spike McRoy.
	   Johnson, the statistics and information editor for Golfweek,
designed Pro Golf primarily as a comprehensive guide for fantasy
golf leagues. It has a five-year history of a player's performance
on tour and breaks down his career by the month, season, location
of the tournament and kind of course, among other things.
	   It also reviews the last three years of each event and
highlights trends of the winner.
	   Pro Golf '99 can be ordered by calling 1-800-996-4653.
	   ___ &QC; 
	    &UR; DIVOTS: &LR;  Ernie Els, a two-time U.S. Open champion and a
three-time winner of the World Match Play Championship, received a
lifetime membership on the European tour. The only other non-Euros
to get that privilege are Arnold Palmer, Gary Player and Bob
Charles. ... Highland Oaks in Dothan, Ala., part of the Robert
Trent Jones Golf Trail, will be the site of the Nike Tour
Championship Oct. 21-24. ... John Daly has entered the Murphy's
Irish Open, which comes two weeks before the British Open at
Carnoustie. ... A federal court in California has set an October
trial date for Callaway's lawsuit against Spalding and its ``System
C'' golf ball.
	   ___ &QC; 
	    &UR; STAT OF THE WEEK: &LR;  No one has ever won the season-ending Tour
Championship and the following year's season-opening Mercedes
Championship. Tom Lehman came the closest, losing the 1997 Mercedes
in a playoff to Tiger Woods.
</TEXT>
