<SLUG> BC-Britain-GEC </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GEC splits military, civilian business amid merger rumors
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ British electrical giant, The General Electric
Company PLC, said Tuesday that it will separate its civil and
defense businesses, ahead of a rumored dlrs 39 billion merger with
British Aerospace PLC.
	   The separation may take one of several forms, the company said
in a statement, but it ``will enhance the ability of GEC to create
value for its shareholders by leading the international defense
industry consolidation.''
	   The Sunday Times reported this week that GEC and British
Aerospace were close to creating a dlrs 39 billion defense group.
Such an alliance would be the first big-scale union in the European
defense industry.
	   GEC said Tuesday it was talking to a number of defense industry
parties, but didn't give names. The company said that the
discussions were ``proceeding well and have confirmed the
considerable value to be generated from participating in the global
consolidation process.''
	   Paul Beaver, defense analyst with Jane's Information Group, said
that the announcement was part of a restructuring to fulfill
monopoly requirements and ensure the linkup with British Aerospace.
	   GEC's defense operations produce defense equipment ranging from
torpedoes to electronics for British and U.S. warplanes. British
Aerospace produces the Harrier jump jet and will also build part of
the new Eurofighter.
	   The merger, Beaver said ''would create a business combining
British Aerospace platforms with GEC electronics, creating a one
stop shop, whether it is in aircraft, ships or armored vehicles.''
	   On the London Stock Exchange, GEC closed down 18.5 pence (dlrs
0.29) to 537.5 pence (dlrs 8.60), and British Aerospace fell 4
pence (dlrs 0.06) lower at 527 pence (dlrs 8.43).
	   Beaver said that a series of continent-wide mergers between
European defense companies was likely early in the new year,
possibly to include U.S. defense giants.
	   (rs)
</TEXT>
