<SLUG> BC-Palestinian-Israel </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Palestinians plan to release Hamas leader this week
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By IBRAHIM BARZAK &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   GAZA CITY, Gaza Strip (AP) _ The Palestinian leadership is
likely to order the release this week from house arrest of a
prominent Muslim militant leader, officials said Tuesday.
	   Yasser Arafat would probably order the release of Sheik Ahmed
Yassin by Saturday, an official close to Arafat told The Associated
Press.
	   The Hamas leader's case was put to Arafat by Arafat's own Fatah
faction, said the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
	   Hamas officials said they were aware of the appeals on their
blind, wheelchair-bound leader's behalf.
	   ``We have been informed by some of out brothers from Fatah
regarding this issue, and we hope their recommendations will be
accepted,'' said Hamas spokesman Ismail Haniye.
	   The release of the Hamas leader _ placed under house arrest in
October after a Hamas activist killed himself in an unsuccessful
attempt to blow up a school bus full of Israeli children _ would be
a sign of deteriorating Israeli-Palestinian relations.
	   The attack on the bus came immediately after the U.S.-brokered
accords achieved in Wye River, Maryland.
	   Yassin's house arrest prevented the scuttling of the accord, but
since then, there has been an outbreak of anti-Israel violence
sparked by a refusal to release Palestinians jailed for killings,
and Israel has frozen a planned troop withdrawal from the West
Bank.
	   Among other conditions for going ahead with the withdrawal,
Israel wants the Palestinians to contain incitement by Hamas _ a
popular militant movement that has called for Israel's destruction.
	   Yassin's release would be ``very much in line with the revolving
door policy which we are so upset about,'' said David Bar-Illan, a
senior adviser to Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
	   ``The less contact the Hamas leaders have with the press, the
less incitement there seems to be,'' Bar-Illan said.
	   Palestinians say they have fulfilled their commitments to Wye.
	   ``We have implemented our part of the agreement, and now it's
their turn to implement their part of the agreement,'' said Nabil
Abourdeneh, a top Arafat adviser.
	   The Americans agree.
	   The U.S. State Department called Netanyahu's conditions new, and
credited the Palestinians with having ``worked hard to implement
many of their commitments'' under the agreement.
	   ``It's our expectation that the Wye River memorandum will be
implemented as signed, and without new conditions,'' State
Department spokesman Lee McClenny said.
	   Palestinians are increasingly worried that Netanyahu's decision
this week to go to early elections will further cripple the
already-ailing peace process.
	   ``The early elections do not cancel the agreement we signed with
the Israeli government,'' Abourdeneh said.
	   (strs/rk) 	   
</TEXT>
