<SLUG> BC-UN-Iraq,0617 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Security Council starts discussing steps to map new Iraq policy
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With AP Photos NYR106-107, NYR111 &QL; 
 &UR; By EDITH M. LEDERER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Putting aside deep divisions over
sanctions and weapons inspections, the U.N. Security Council on
Tuesday started discussing two less contentious steps to help map a
new policy on Iraq after the U.S.-British bombing campaign.
	   On the table was a revised Russian proposal calling for
Secretary-General Kofi Annan to submit ``an overall assessment of
the current situation on the ground in Iraq'' and a meeting of the
executive board that oversees the weapons inspectors.
	   ``Most members supported this approach today,'' said Russia's
U.N. Ambassador Sergey Lavrov, expressing hope that the council
would reach agreement soon ``in order to get the ball rolling.''
	   The council scheduled another meeting on Iraq for Wednesday.
	   Crucially, the United States did not oppose either step although
diplomats said Washington had some questions about exactly who
would carry out the assessment.
	   Deputy U.S. Ambassador Peter Burleigh said the United States
believes ``there could well be some merit'' in a meeting of the 22
commissioners who oversee the U.N. Special Commission, known as
UNSCOM, which is charged with verifying the destruction of Iraq's
chemical and biological weapons and long-range missiles.
	   The commissioners usually meet once or twice a year and ``it
seems like one of those steps that the council will probably want
to take,'' Burleigh said.
	   At a news conference in Washington, Undersecretary of State
Thomas Pickering said an assessment of Iraq's compliance with
Security Council resolutions, the role of the council, and the
probability of UNSCOM resuming inspections, ``might be germane and
useful.''
	   ``We are looking at that,'' Pickering said.
	   Lavrov said he envisions an assessment from the
secretary-general and from members of the Special Commission
covering Iraq's humanitarian problems, disarmament and political
situation after the bombing campaign.
	   This will help the council ``decide how we can implement all the
resolutions (on Iraq) further,'' he said.
	   The revised Russian draft resolution ``encourages'' the
secretary-general to continue playing a role ``in promoting
humanitarian relief and healing diplomacy.''
	   Annan has spent much of the year trying to defuse tensions
between Iraq and the council, and helped avert U.S.-British
airstrikes in February and November.
	   Some U.S. diplomats are worried over Annan's stated concern
about the long-term impact of sanctions on Iraq's 22 million
people.
	   The five permanent council members _ the United States, Britain,
France, Russia and China _ remain divided over the future of
UNSCOM, the future of its director Richard Butler, and the future
of sanctions.
	   The United States and Britain want UNSCOM and Butler to remain
on the job.
	   France is floating a still murky proposal for a modified version
of UNSCOM that would prevent Iraq from acquiring banned weapons,
include long-term monitoring, and lift sanctions which Paris
contends cause unintended hardship on the Iraqi people.
	   Russia and China, the most vocal opponents of the bombing, have
also called for the lifting of sanctions and are demanding Butler's
ouster.
	   The Russian draft includes one statement which is unacceptable
to the United States: It would have the council express regret over
the use of force against Iraq.
	   ``We certainly regret the fact that force had to be used in Iraq
_ and it's clear in the council that there will be, I think, lots
of suggestions for changes,'' Burleigh said.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-UN-Iraq; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(REG:INDI;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:ASIA;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
