<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iraq, 6th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Iraq claims U.S.-British planes fired missiles at Basra
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with arrival of humanitarian aid workers &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos BAG101, 103-104
 &UR; By LEON BARKHO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ Iraq on Tuesday accused U.S.-British
warplanes of firing two missiles toward the southern city of Basra,
saying the renewed aggression was part of a policy ``to harm
Iraq.''
	   The Pentagon and the British Defense Ministry denied the claim,
which was reported by the official Iraqi News Agency.
	   Iraq also warned Tuesday that it won't forgive the oil-rich
emirate of Kuwait for allowing the United States and Britain to use
its military bases to mount last week's airstrikes against the
country.
	   Quoting an unnamed spokesman for the Ministry of Culture and
Information, the Iraqi News Agency dismissed Kuwaiti statements
that the emirate was not involved in the Dec. 16-19 airstrikes.
	   ``This justification does not vindicate the (ruling) family ...
of such treacherous and criminal acts it perpetrated against the
Iraqi people,'' INA said.
	   Meanwhile, INA also reported that three children were killed and
20 others wounded in the southern province of Wasit as a result of
the U.S-British assault. It did not elaborate.
	   The casualties would be in addition to the 62 soldiers and an
unspecified number of civilians that Iraq says were killed in the
strikes. The United States says the air raids and 425 Tomahawk
cruise missile strikes targeted defense sites to reduce Iraq's
ability to build weapons of mass destruction.
	   Tensions that had subsided following the end of the punishing
strikes rose again briefly when INA reported that aircraft from the
``criminal aggressors'' came in two waves and violated Iraqi
airspace.
	   It quoted an unnamed military spokesman as saying that ``four
formations of aircraft'' flew over Iraq Tuesday morning and
returned in the direction from which they came.
	   The agency said five more formations entered Iraq about five
hours later, at 2:17 p.m. (1117gmt) ``and approached southern Basra
out of range of our weapons and fired two stray missiles before
fleeing.''
	   ``This violation is part of the policy to harm Iraq,'' the
agency added.
	   The Iraqi report did not define what it meant by ``stray
missiles'' or say if they hit anything.
	   A Pentagon spokesman, Lt. Col. Patrick Sivigny, said ``U.S.
forces have not fired any missiles.'' Britain also said there was
no evidence that any British plane had fired a missile over Iraq
Tuesday.
	   ``As far as we are aware, there is nothing to suggest that this
took place,'' a Defense Ministry spokesman said on customary
condition of anonymity.
	   The conflicting reports could not be immediately reconciled.
	   Western jets patrolling a no-fly zone over southern Iraq have in
the past fired if approached by Iraqi aircraft or if Iraqi
anti-aircraft batteries locked their targeting radar on the
aircraft.
	   Following the recent bombing campaign, Iraq demanded an end to
no-fly zones in the north and south of the country. The exclusion
zones cover about two-thirds of the country.
	   Also Tuesday, four U.S. peace activists staged a demonstration
at Saddam Medical City _ a hospital complex in Baghdad _ to protest
against the attacks and strong U.S. support for economic sanctions
against Iraq.
	   The members of the Voices in the Wilderness group lit a lamp
using Iraqi oil that they purchased in violation of the U.N.
embargo. The sanctions were imposed following Iraq's 1990 invasion
of Kuwait.
	   ``We bought the oil from Iraq in an open and public defiance of
U.S.-U.N. sanctions,'' said the group's leader, Kathy Kelly of
Chicago, Illinois.
	   The sanctions cannot be lifted until a U.N. weapons inspection
commission certifies that Iraq no longer possesses or has the
ability to produce nuclear, chemical and biological weapons and
long-range missiles. U.S. Undersecretary of State Thomas Pickering
reiterated that Tuesday.
	   But following the airstrikes, Iraq declared it will not allow
the U.N. commission to work again in the country.
	   On Tuesday, the government said reconstruction teams were
repairing damage from the strikes, and state television showed
pictures of masons and other workers rebuilding a destroyed house
in Baghdad.
	   Civil defense teams collected unexploded missiles and bombs, the
Iraqi News Agency said. It said the teams defused 65 cluster bombs
and two missiles in the southern province of Wasit.
	   Also, more than 100 U.N. relief workers, who were evacuated to
Amman amid the bombing campaign, arrived in Baghdad late Tuesday.
	   The aid workers arrived at a Baghdad hotel in three buses and
made no comments to the press.
 &UR; pvs-lm
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
