r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  PM-US-Israel     12-22 0486
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> PM-US-Israel,0486 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ambassador blames Palestinians for stalemate
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By BARRY SCHWEID &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ Israel's ambassador to the United States says
the Palestinians are to blame for the delay in a pullback on the
West Bank.
	   Insisting Israel had not raised new conditions, ambassador
Zalman Shoval said Tuesday all that Israel demands is Palestinian
compliance with terms of the Wye River accords.
	   ``Let us hope they will, so as not to miss another opportunity
for peace,'' Shoval told a gathering of American business leaders
here.
	   The Wye River accords were not ``a one-way ticket,'' the Israeli
diplomat said. ``Unless the Palestinians comply with their part of
the deal and fulfill all their commitments, it will be their fault
if the process is stalled.''
	   The U.S. State Department took another view. It said Israel
should turn over the territory promised to the Palestinians in the
accords in October,
	   And Saeb Erekat, the chief Palestinian negotiator, told The
Associated Press in Jerusalem that Israel was bound to honor the
Wye accords despite internal political turmoil.
	   Similarly, State Department spokesman Lee McClenny said, ``It's
our expectation that the Wye River memorandum will be implemented
as signed, and without new conditions.''
	   President Bill Clinton, on a trip to Gaza last week, praised
Yasser Arafat and told the Palestinians they were free to
``determine their own destiny on their own land.''
	   While giving statehood a boost, the administration also has
eased up on Arafat's statehood declarations, saying people should
be free to express their aspirations.
	   The State Department called the prime minister's conditions new,
and credited the Palestinians with having ``worked hard to
implement many of their commitments'' under the agreement.
	   These included annulling clauses in the 1964 charter of the
Palestine Liberation Organization that called for dismantling
Israel as a Jewish state, and ``stepping up the fight against
terror,'' McClenny said.
	   ``We're working with both sides to urge them to complete
implementation as quickly as possible so that the second phase can
be carried out,'' he said.
	   But Shoval said the Israeli government had not suspended the Wye
accords. ``The opposite is true,'' he said.
	   In the Wye accords, Israel agreed to relinquish another 13
percent of the West Bank to the Palestinian Authority if it took
stronger measures to root out terrorists who attack Israel from
Palestinian-controlled areas.
	   The accords provide for matching steps by Arafat on security
before each phase of an Israeli pullback. Israel surrendered 4
percent in a first phase.
	   Clinton and Sandy Berger, his national security adviser, both
said on their trip to the region last week that there was likely to
be a delay in the second phase, but that they hoped it would not be
a long one.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:PM-US-Israel; CT:i; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
(REG:MEST;)
(REG:AFRI;)
(REG:INDI;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(REG:ASIA;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
