<SLUG> BC-Canada-Ice Storm Book,0382 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hottest best-seller in Canada: The ice-storm book
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By DAVID CRARY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TORONTO (AP) _ Back in January, a devastating ice storm was
inflicting misery on millions of people in Quebec and Ontario. Now
that storm is revisited in a coffee-table book that is atop
Canada's holiday bestseller lists.
	   Called ``The Ice Storm'' in English and ``Le Grand Verglas'' in
the French edition, the book has sold almost 100,000 copies since
it was published last month.
	   A Montreal Gazette reporter, Mark Abley, wrote the text, and the
Gazette coordinated an effort by nine regional newspapers to
contribute photographs of the storm.
	   Canadian authorities have ranked the ice storm as the most
disruptive and destructive storm of any sort in national history.
	   Thick coats of ice formed by a week of freezing rain toppled
more than 1,000 power transmission towers and 30,000 wooden utility
poles. More than 3 million people were seriously affected, and even
a month after the storm about 700,000 people were still without
power.
	   Photographs in the book show the extent of the destruction, as
well as the strange beauty of streets cluttered with ice-covered
wires and branches. There are shots of families huddling together
for candlelit meals, and refugees finding comfort in emergency
shelters.
	   Seeking to avoid any impression that they are profiting from
others' misery, the newspapers involved in producing the book are
contributing their share of royalties to charities which have
assisted ice-storm recovery efforts.
	   The publisher, McClelland and Stewart, also is making a donation
of 50 cents per copy.
	   ``This is not an ordinary book,'' McClelland and Stewart
president Douglas Gibson said in an interview Tuesday. ``For anyone
who was exposed to the ice storm, it's something they have to have
in the same way they have to have their high school year book.''
	   The ice storm hit upstate New York and northern New England as
well as Canada, and Gibson said the book would be marketed starting
in March in the northeastern United States.
	   Though only Canadian newspapers contributed photographs, the
pictures include shots of U.S. utility crews which came to Canada
to help with emergency power-line repairs. 	   
</TEXT>
