<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Palestinian-Israel,0465 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Palestinians plan to release Hamas leader this week
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By IBRAHIM BARZAK &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   GAZA CITY, Gaza Strip (AP) _ The Palestinian leadership is
likely to order the release this week of a prominent Muslim
militant leader placed under house arrest after a suicide bombing
attempt by a Hamas activist, officials said Tuesday.
	   The release of Hamas leader Sheik Ahmed Yassin would be a sign
of deteriorating Israeli-Palestinian relations already strained by
the delay in implementing the latest land-for-peace deal.
	   Yasser Arafat would probably order Yassin's release of by
Saturday, an official close to Arafat told The Associated Press.
	   Hamas officials said they were aware of the appeals on their
blind, wheelchair-bound leader's behalf. ``We have been informed by
some of our brothers from Fatah (Arafat's faction) regarding this
issue, and we hope their recommendations will be accepted,'' said
Hamas spokesman Ismail Haniye.
	   Yassin was placed under house arrest in October after a Hamas
activist killed himself in an unsuccessful attempt to blow up a
school bus full of Israeli children.
	   The attack came immediately after the U.S.-brokered accords
achieved in Wye River, Maryland.
	   Yassin's house arrest prevented the scuttling of the accord, but
there has been an outbreak of anti-Israel violence since then.
Israel has refused to release Palestinians jailed for killings and
has frozen a planned troop withdrawal from the West Bank.
	   Among other conditions for going ahead with the withdrawal,
Israel wants the Palestinians to contain incitement by Hamas _ a
popular militant movement that has called for Israel's destruction.
	   Yassin's release would be ``very much in line with the revolving
door policy which we are so upset about,'' said David Bar-Illan, a
senior adviser to Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu.
	   ``The less contact the Hamas leaders have with the press, the
less incitement there seems to be,'' Bar-Illan said.
	   Palestinians say they have fulfilled their commitments to Wye.
	   ``We have implemented our part of the agreement, and now it's
their turn to implement their part of the agreement,'' said Nabil
Abourdeneh, a top Arafat adviser.
	   The Americans agree. The U.S. State Department called
Netanyahu's conditions new, and credited the Palestinians with
having ``worked hard to implement many of their commitments'' under
the agreement.
	   Palestinians are increasingly worried that Netanyahu's decision
this week to go to early elections will further cripple the
already-ailing peace process.
	   ``The early elections do not cancel the agreement we signed with
the Israeli government,'' Abourdeneh said.
</TEXT>
