<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Auto Racing-Vancouver-Indy,0485 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Vancouver gets go-ahead for CART race
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) _ It took almost three months
to satisfy safety and hospitality concerns, but organizers have
convinced Championship Auto Racing Teams to return in September for
the Vancouver Molson Indy.
	   ``We're ecstatic,'' Stuart Ballantyne, the Molson Indy's general
manager, said Tuesday. ``It's a Christmas present for the fans, the
staff, for the sponsors, for everybody involved with the CART
community.
	   ``Clearly this is a good day.''
	   Both drivers and team officials were vocal in their condemnation
of this year's race, won by Dario Franchitti.
	   The drivers complained about the track, saying it didn't allow
enough passing room and questioned its safety. Owners were furious
to find used syringes and condoms in the downtown areas set aside
for hospitality and sponsor entertainment.
	   Tim Mayer, CART's senior vice-president, said Molstar Sports and
Entertainment, which stages the Vancouver race and the Molson Indy
in Toronto, have made proposals to alleviate these problems.
	   ``What we have gone through with Molstar is a pretty exhaustive
process of working on some changes to the facility,'' Mayer said
from Detroit.
	   ``When we received sufficient details from them it made us
confident the changes would meet our requirements.''
	   Ballantyne wasn't specific on the changes. A news conference has
been planned for January to unveil the altered track and other
improvements.
	   ``CART was not satisfied with their overall experience and there
were some issues with the track and with the amenities that have
been changed or there's an agreement to have some changes,''
Ballantyne said. ``That's what's got us today's announcement.''
	   As late as last week Andrew Craig, CART's chairman of the board,
said while he was encouraged by proposals to upgrade the Vancouver
facility the race remained a provisional date on CART's 1999
calendar.
	   Both Ballantyne and Mayer were cautious when asked how important
this year's event will be to the race's future in Vancouver.
Molstar has a contract with CART and the city of Vancouver through
2001.
	   ``Certainly having CART's agreement and the level of detail
we've gotten to today goes a long way toward resolving any issues
that we could have in the future,'' Ballantyne said.
	   Drivers lambasted the new, 14-turn temporary street circuit for
its lack of passing and overtaking areas. They also expressed
concerns about safety in several areas, especially a flat-out turn
directly in front of the pits.
	   Drivers feared they could lose control and crash into a massive
concrete pylon supporting an elevated train track.
	   ``I wouldn't say the track was unsafe but it did not meet our
standards,'' Mayer said. ``I think all of these have been
addressed.''
</TEXT>
