w2187 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Football-Dolph     12-22 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Football-Dolphins-Playoffs,0550 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Defense will give Miami a chance in playoffs
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By STEVEN WINE &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   DAVIE, Florida (AP) _ As John Elway and Terrell Davis can
attest, the National Football League's stingiest defense will make
the Miami Dolphins dangerous in the playoffs.
	   The point was hammered home Monday night against the Denver
Broncos, whose high-powered offense sputtered in a 31-21 defeat at
Miami.
	   The Dolphins (10-5) earned the final AFC playoff berth as a
wild-card entry. They'll need three postseason wins to play at home
in the Super Bowl, but a defense that has allowed the fewest points
in the NFL gives Miami a chance against anybody.
	   The Broncos lead the AFC in scoring, but Miami allowed them just
219 yards and one offensive touchdown _ on a recovered fumble.
	   ``You're not going to see a defensive performance like that very
often, because that was a talented, talented bunch we went up
against,'' coach Jimmy Johnson said Tuesday. ``Appreciate it.''
	   The speedy, swarming Dolphins held Davis to a season-low 29
yards in 16 carries.
	   ``There just wasn't much running room out there,'' he said.
	   Elway went 13-for-36 for 151 yards, including 6-for-20 in the
second half for 61 yards with two interceptions.
	   ``A very long night,'' Elway said. ``They're no slouches.
Whenever you cover the receivers tightly and put pressure on the
quarterback, you're doing the job defensively.''
	   The Dolphins must hope that defense and Dan Marino are enough in
the playoffs. Their running game was again abysmal Monday, and
Miami has averaged just 2.7 yards per rush in the past month.
	   But Marino enjoyed his best performance of the year, throwing
for 355 yards and four scores in his first matchup against Elway
since 1985.
	   ``Dan played great,'' Elway said. ``That's why he is who he
is.''
	   Johnson termed the victory the biggest in his three seasons with
Miami. He bristled at the suggestion that the Broncos (13-2) had
little incentive because they had already clinched the home-field
advantage through the playoffs.
	   ``If you look at the expression on John Elway's face when he's
scrambling and running for yards and trying to pick up first downs
_ I think they were giving a pretty good effort,'' Johnson said.
	   The Dolphins, upset last week to have just one Pro Bowl
selection _ defensive tackle Tim Bowens _ beat a team with nine of
them.
	   ``We proved to the Denver Broncos and the whole NFL that they
missed out on some of our good players in the Pro Bowl,'' said
cornerback Jerry Wilson, who had an interception. ``We wanted to
make a statement this game, and that's what we did.''
	   The statement was that the Dolphins are difficult to score
against, especially at home, where they've allowed six touchdowns
in eight games.
	   Miami's dominance at Pro Player Stadium underscores the
importance of Sunday's final regular-season game at Atlanta. The
Dolphins will clinch a home game in the first round of postseason
if they win, or if New England loses to the New York Jets.
	   The Dolphins' first-round opponent will be one of two AFC East
rivals, New England or Buffalo. Miami beat both at home this season
and lost to both on the road.
</TEXT>
