<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Egypt-Libya, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Minister: Libya does not want to delay Lockerbie trial
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with Libyan minister's comments &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ Libya does not want to delay the trial of
the two Lockerbie bombing suspects but only wants to ensure the
``honesty'' of the trial court, the Libyan foreign minister said
Tuesday.
	   Libya is also not worried about U.S. threats of more sanctions
as a tool to get custody of the two Libyan suspects, the minister,
Omar al-Muntasser, told reporters.
	   He was speaking after meeting with Egypt's Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa. Al-Muntasser arrived in Cairo Monday.
	   The Dec. 21, 1988 bombing of a Pan Am jet over Lockerbie,
Scotland, killed 270 people. The prime suspects are two Libyan
intelligence agents and Libya is under U.N. air sanctions aimed at
forcing it to hand over the men for trial.
	   ``We are sure of their innocence. Our sons have not done it and
there is no proof of that,'' al-Muntasser said.
	   Libya already has accepted in principle to the trial of the two
men before a panel of Scottish judges in the Netherlands but their
hand over has been held up over a Libyan demand that if convicted,
the suspects should be jailed in Libya.
	   ``There is no procrastination on our part and the only thing is
that we want to be sure of the honesty of the court and the
guarantees,'' al-Muntasser said without elaborating.
	   The General People's Congress, Libya's parliament, also gave its
conditional approval last week for the trial of the two men in a
country other than the United States or Britain.
	   The United States and Britain insist that the two men should
spend the jail term in Britain.
	   U.S. President Bill Clinton, speaking at a memorial service
Monday on the bombing's 10th anniversary, warned that the United
States would seek even stronger measures against Libya if the
suspects were not turned over.
	   Al-Muntasser said the U.S. threat ``does not worry me, because
we cannot work on the threats.''
	   In any case, imposing more sanctions is the U.N. Security
Council's job and ``I am sure there will be no more sanctions,'' he
said.
	   Egypt's Middle East News Agency said al-Muntasser and Moussa
also discussed the Iraq crisis and the U.N sanctions imposed on
Iraq after it invaded Kuwait in 1990.
 &UR; my/vj
</TEXT>
