u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Cuba-Christmas     12-22 0437
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cuba-Christmas,0444 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cardinal says church must work to restore Christmas as religious
</HEADLINE>
holiday &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos HAV101,104 &QL; 
 &UR; By ANITA SNOW &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   HAVANA (AP) _ The Roman Catholic church must strive to restore
the religious traditions of Christmas now that it has been declared
a permanent government holiday, Cardinal Jaime Ortega said Tuesday.
	   While Cubans have embraced the communist government's decision,
few understand that Dec. 25 commemorates the birth of Jesus Christ,
Cuba's leading Catholic churchman told a news conference.
	   ``The people accept with enthusiasm any day off,'' the prelate
added. ``Now there is curiosity on the part of the new generations
about what Christmas is.''
	   The Catholic church hoped to refresh the Cuban people in the
Christmas traditions of the past later Tuesday evening with the
first outdoor religious Christmas concert celebrated here since the
holiday was abolished in 1969.
	   A church choir that performed during Pope John Paul II's visit
to Cuba early this year was to sing Christmas music rarely heard
outside a church.
	   The government granted a Christmas holiday last year as a
one-time favor to the pope before his January visit and decided
last month to make it permanent.
	   Thus far, most of the holiday trappings in this formerly
atheistic nation are secular, such as small plastic trees with
twinkling lights.
	   ``There is a great work that the church must undertake,'' Ortega
said. ``It is a job that I think will take many years.''
	   Despite increasing tensions between Cuban churches and a
government that declared itself atheist in 1962, Christmas remained
an official holiday in Cuba until 1969, when the government was
throwing much of the country's resources into an unsuccessful
effort to harvest 10 million metric tons of sugar.
	   The government argued that holidays interfered with the harvest
and also canceled the New Year's holiday that year. The New Year's
holiday _ which also marked the triumph of the revolution led by
Fidel Castro _ soon returned. But Christmas remained a day of work.
	   In November, the Communist Party said mechanization had reduced
the need for manpower in the sugar harvest and declared that
Christmas once again would be a holiday.
	   In 1976, Cuba's constitution guaranteed freedom of religion and
in 1991, the Communist Party dropped its ban on religious
believers. A year later, Cuba declared itself a secular rather than
an atheist state.
	   Restrictions on believers have fallen away and church-state
relations have warmed, especially since the papal visit.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
