<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP News Summary,0721 </SLUG>


<TEXT>
	   A summary of news from The Associated Press. Some items have
moved on this circuit in expanded form with ``i'' or ``f'' category
codes:
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ On the first day of what's likely to be a long
and bruising electoral campaign, Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
braced for an onslaught from all sides _ but expressing confidence
he would win ``utmost, massive'' voter support. It was a notable
show of bravado from a leader who only a day earlier had been
handed a stinging rejection of his peace policies by lawmakers, who
then voted overwhelmingly to hold early elections. It will be
several more days before the lineup against Netanyahu becomes
clear, but at least half a dozen Israeli politicians have announced
candidacies or are weighing bids to become prime minister.
Balloting is expected by the end of April in what's likely to be
the last direct election for the post. (ISRAEL-POLITICS).
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ After miscalculating in the House, President
Bill Clinton's defenders have moved legalistic maneuvers to the
background for now in favor of an aggressive lobbying effort to
stop a Senate impeachment trial and promote censure instead. And
like Monica Lewinsky, who shelved her first lawyer last summer for
two Washington insiders who won her an immunity deal with
prosecutors, the White House is likely to turn to senior statesmen
in both parties to make a case that senators will heed, advisers
say. ``You have to have the wise men go up _ people with the
stature and instant credibility to be heard by 100 senators,'' said
one adviser to the White House involved in the emerging strategy
discussions. The Senate's leading authority on history and
protocol, Democratic Robert Byrd said Monday he believed the
Constitution allows for a censure, but he also warned that any such
deal must not originate with the White House by the Senate.
(US-CLINTON-IMPEACHMENT).
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ Iraq accused U.S. and British warplanes of
firing two missiles toward the southern city of Basra on Tuesday,
saying the renewed aggression was part of a policy ``to harm
Iraq.'' The Pentagon and the British Defense Ministry denied the
claim, which was reported by the official Iraqi News Agency. Iraq
also warned Tuesday that it won't forgive the oil-rich emirate of
Kuwait for allowing the United States and Britain to use its
military bases to mount last week's airstrikes against the country.
Quoting an unnamed spokesman for the Ministry of Culture and
Information, the Iraqi News Agency dismissed Kuwaiti statements
that the emirate was not involved in the Dec. 16-19 airstrikes.
(IRAQ)
	   LONDON (AP) _ Three round-the-world balloonists drifted high
over the Himalayas on Tuesday, hoping to catch a jet stream out of
prohibited Chinese airspace as quickly as possible. British tycoon
Richard Branson, American millionaire Steve Fossett and Per
Lindstrand of Sweden, aloft in the ICO Global balloon heading
eastward around the globe, had received permission to cross China
below 26 degrees north latitude. But they drifted further north
Monday. The project ground crew said the Chinese had asked the
balloonists to land at the Lhasa airfield Tuesday morning, but that
the balloon overshot the field and it was impossible to come down
anywhere else. After Prime Minister Tony Blair intervened, the
Chinese government granted permission to cross the country, on
condition the balloon leave Chinese airspace as soon as possible.
(BALLOON QUEST)
	   BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) _ Against the odds of medical
science, a Catholic homemaker finally walked out of the hospital
Tuesday _ more than four months after being caught in ground zero
of Northern Ireland's worst-ever terrorist attack. Tracey Devine,
27, suffered a slashed face and burns all over her body when Irish
Republican Army dissidents detonated a car bomb in Omagh, a
religiously mixed market town 60 miles (100 kms) west of Belfast.
In all, 29 people died and 370 were wounded in the Aug. 15 blast.
Mrs. Devine spent six weeks in a coma in Belfast's Royal Victoria
Hospital. When she awoke, her husband Paul had to tell her their
youngest child, 21-month-old Breda, was among the dead. On Tuesday,
she left the hospital _ the last of the wounded to go home.
(NIRELAND-OMAGH'S LAST VICTIM) 	   
</TEXT>
