<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP Top Financial News,0751 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   A summary of financial and business news from The Associated
Press at 0000 GMT. Stories carry ``f'' or ``i'' category codes and
move on this circuit in expanded form:
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ Blue-chip stocks lifted the S-and-P 500 index to
a second straight record, but the broad market was weighed down by
profit-taking in the technology group and another dismal showing by
smaller-company shares. The Dow Jones industrial average rose 55.61
points _ of by 0.6 percent _ to 9,044.46, pushing its winning
streak to four sessions and about 250 points. (US-CLOSING STOCKS)
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ With the U.S. economy demonstrating continued
strong growth despite a world slump, Federal Reserve policy-makers
opted Tuesday to leave short-term interest rates unchanged. The
decision, leaving the benchmark rate on overnight loans between
banks at a four-year low of 4.75 percent, follows three rapid-fire
rate cuts this fall. The Fed cut the rate by a quarter-point on
Sept. 29, Oct. 15 and Nov. 17, calming Wall Street, raising stock
prices and loosening the flow of credit to business borrowers,
which had threatened to freeze up in the world financial turmoil
that followed the collapse of the Russian economy in August. After
the last reduction, policy-makers signaled they were done cutting
for a while by saying ``financial conditions can be expected to be
consistent with fostering sustained economic expansion.''
(US-ECONOMY-INTEREST RATES)
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) _ In a novel approach reflecting the
uncertainties of the Jan. 1 launch of Europe's new currency, the
euro, European Central Bank President Wim Duisenberg said Tuesday
the bank had decided on an especially narrow corridor for two money
market rates _ for the first three weeks of the euro's existence.
After Jan. 21, the rates would revert to a broader corridor. The
euro-zone's key interest rate, the securities repurchase rate, was
fixed at 3 percent at the beginning of December, removing early
uncertainty about the setting of the key rate for the euro area.
But in a surprise move, Duisenberg announced two other rates - the
marginal lending and deposit rates - would be set at just 3.25 and
2.75 percent respectively until Jan. 21, when they would broaden to
4.5 and 2 percent. (GERMANY-EURO)
	   LONDON (AP) _ British electrical giant, The General Electric
Company PLC, said Tuesday that it will separate its civil and
defense businesses, ahead of a rumored dlrs 39 billion merger with
British Aerospace PLC. The separation may take one of several
forms, the company said in a statement, but it ``will enhance the
ability of GEC to create value for its shareholders by leading the
international defense industry consolidation.'' The Sunday Times
reported this week that GEC and British Aerospace were close to
creating a dlrs 39 billion defense group. Such an alliance would be
the first big-scale union in the European defense industry.
(BRITAIN-GEC)
	   BUCHAREST, Romania (AP) _ France's oil giant Elf Aquitaine
signed an agreement Tuesday with Romania's national oil company
Petrom for oil exploration and drilling in the Black Sea. ``This is
another important step in Romanian-French bilateral relations,''
said Radu Berceanu, Romanian trade and industry minister. It was
the second important French investment here in the last month.
Societe Generale paid dlrs 200 million for a 51 percent stake in
the Romanian Development Bank. French auto manufacturer Renault is
in negotiations to buy the Romanian Dacia car maker. Under the oil
contract, Elf and Petrom will explore a surface of 10,000 square
kilometers (4,000 sq. miles) in Black Sea for the next 30 years.
(ROMANIA-OIL DEAL)
	   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) _ Anglo American Corp., the
South African mining and investment conglomerate, says it is still
negotiating to take over Zambia copper mines despite a statement to
the contrary by a Zambian official. Anglo American said Monday it
is concerned about current low copper prices, and that it has not
been able to attract partners, it said. The company said it has a
memorandum of understanding with the Zambian government, but the
memorandum hasn't yet been ratified by the government or the
company. Zambian Finance Minister Edith Nawakwi said Saturday that
Anglo American would take over Nchanga, Nkana and Konkola mines,
the remaining major assets of Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines.
(SOUTH AFRICA-ZAMBIA-COPPER)
</TEXT>
