<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Bosnia-War Crimes,0345 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tribunal indicts two Bosnian Croats for persecuting Muslims
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) _ The Yugoslav war crimes tribunal
indicted two Bosnian Croats for a vicious campaign of terror that
drove tens of thousands of Muslims from their homes.
	   The two men, connected to a paramilitary group called the
Convicts Battalion, were allegedly involved in a string of
atrocities in and around Mostar between May 1993 and March 1994,
prosecutors said Tuesday.
	   The U.N. court indicted Mladen Naletilic, 52, on 17 war crimes
counts for allegedly commanding the Convicts Battalion.
	   Naletilic faces four charges of crimes against humanity, six of
breaches of the Geneva Conventions and seven of breaches of the
laws and customs of war.
	   Also charged was Vinko Martinovic, 35, who prosecutors say
commanded a sub-unit of the Convicts Battalion called the
Anti-Terrorist Group. Martinovic faces 22 charges, including five
of crimes against humanity.
	   The city of Mostar in southern Bosnia in 1993 was scene of some
of the most savage fighting of the 3 1-2-year war and the city
remains divided between Bosnian Croats and Muslims.
	   Both men face maximum life sentences if convicted.
	   Both are Bosnian Croats but also hold Croatian citizenship, the
tribunal said in a press release. They are believed to have been
arrested by Croat authorities and to be in custody in Zagreb.
	   The tribunal did not say if plans had been made for their
transfer to its high-security holding cells in The Hague.
	   According to a summary of their indictment released late
Tuesday, the two men used ``killings, beatings, torture, evictions,
destruction of cultural and religious heritage, looting, ... mass
expulsions, detentions and imprisonment'' to drive Muslims from
their homes.
	   All of the acts followed ``a pattern of systematic ethnic
discrimination,'' the indictment added.
	   Set up in 1993, the tribunal has indicted more than 50 war
crimes suspects and has more than 20 in custody.
</TEXT>
