<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Helicopter Crash,0378 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Three confirmed dead in Mexico helicopter crash
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Mexican Navy personnel searching the wreckage
of a helicopter that crashed on a sparsely inhabited island in the
Gulf of California recovered the bodies of of three New Zealanders.
	   The three apparently died Saturday when the helicopter they were
using to locate and collar Cimarron sheep crashed on Tiburon
Island, about 10 miles (16 kms) off Mexico's coast.
	   The craft, owned by the U.S. Western Slope Helicopter, was
working on a Mexican government contract to collect and relocate
the big-horn sheep on the island, a New Zealand news agency
reported.
	   A Navy helicopter was able to locate the wreckage of the Hughes
500 chopper Monday after U.S. experts used radio detection gear to
locate signals emitted by collars the New Zealanders had carried to
track the sheep.
	   But seamen were unable to recover the cadavers because of bad
weather and the extremely steep slope where the wreckage was found.
	   The searchers finally climbed up a 3,300-foot (1,000 meter) rock
face Tuesday to get to the bodies, which were partially burned and
thrown out of the cockpit, investigators said.
	   ``It was apparently a high-speed crash, but the causes and
circumstances of the accident won't be known until the Civil
Aeronautics Office finishes its investigation,'' Marco Antonio
Ochoa, an official at the airport in the nearby city of Hermosillo,
told the government news agency Notimex Tuesday.
	   Cloud cover over the island had delayed search efforts and could
have contributed to the crash.
	   Ochoa identified the men as Adam Travor, Mark Williams and
Daniel Innis, but no hometowns were immediately available and
officials at the New Zealand embassy in Mexico City were not
available to confirm that report.
	   Very few people live on Isla Tiburon year round. The Sierra
Menor and the Sierra Kunkaak mountains run across the island,
roughly from north to south. However, the island is very rich in
vegetation and wildlife.
	   Tiburon is a special biosphere reserve, Mexico's biggest island
but with only a small transient population of people, but 39
species of reptiles and 52 species of land mammals.
</TEXT>
