w2248 &Cx1f; wstm-
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EuropeanRates     12-22 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-European Rates,0558 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
In bid for stable currency launch, Europe sets interest rates in
</HEADLINE>
narrow range &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: Stands for Germany-Euro recap promised on the 0000 GMT digest
to UPDATE with analyst reaction. &QL; 
 &UR; With US-Economy-Interest Rates &QL; 
 &UR; By DIDI KIRSTEN TATLOW &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) _ The European Central Bank has set an
extremely narrow range for short-term interest rates in a move
aimed at smoothing the Jan. 1 launch of Europe's new currency, the
euro.
	   Wim Duisenberg, the president of the central bank, also said
Tuesday that it was highly unlikely that the bank's key short-term
rate would be lowered from its current 3 percent, which he called
``very low by historical standards.''
	   ``Markets don't expect a change of interest rates in the near
future,'' he said.
	   The European Central Bank will set monetary policy for the 11
nations initially participating in the euro _ Austria, Belgium,
Ireland, Italy, Finland, France, Germany, Luxembourg, the
Netherlands, Spain and Portugal. The decision Tuesday on interest
rates was announced in the bank's last news conference before the
euro is inaugurated and on the same day the U.S. Federal Reserve
left its key short-term rates unchanged.
	   The key European securities refinance interest rate, the
interest on short-term loans by the central bank where securities
are pledged as collateral, was fixed at 3 percent at the beginning
of December.
	   On Tuesday, Duisenberg announced two related rates would be set
very closely to the key rate for at least the first three weeks of
the euro's introduction. The deposit rate, the interest banks earn
on overnight deposits with the European Central Bank, was set at
2.75 percent. The marginal lending rate, the interest on overnight
loans by the European Central Bank, was set at 3.25 percent.
Duisenberg said that the narrow range would prevail until Jan. 21.
when the gap between those rates would widen to 2 percent for the
deposit rate to 4.5 percent for the marginal lending.
	   In effect, the European Central Bank set a very limited ceiling
and a floor on short-term rates for the launch of the euro to limit
volatility, said Pierre Ellis, senior international economist at
Primark Decision Economics in New York.
	   ``Clearly, they want to keep things as stable as possible as
they introduce this currency,'' said Nariman Behravesh, chief
international economist at Standard and Poor's DRI in Lexington,
Massachusetts.
	   Stability is important because big swings in the euro could
result if European rates gyrate. Higher rates would lift the euro
against the dollar and make it harder for European manufacturers to
compete in terms of price when selling their goods on world
markets.
	   Duisenberg said that by limiting the range of short-term rates
initially to one-half percentage point was aimed at smoothing the
way for implementing the new currency.
	   With just over a week remaining to the begin of the historic
project of currency union, Duisenberg called on governments
launching the euro to maintain fiscal restraint and continue ``the
political impetus to achieve over the medium-term balanced budgets
and even a small surplus.''
	   ``What I would advise governments to do is to inspire that
feeling of continuity and stability _ sooner rather than later,''
he said.
</TEXT>
