<SLUG> BC-Sports-Sailing-Around Alone,0194 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Strong winds, torn sails force American skipper out
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   CHARLESTON, South Carolina (AP) _ One of three American skippers
left in the Around Alone around-the-world yacht race has turned his
battered boat back toward South Africa after pulling out of the
race.
	   Skipper George Stricker was fighting gail-force winds Tuesday
with all of his sails torn but one. The Kentucky native told race
officials he was being tossed about and blown away in the Indian
Ocean.
	   Stricker and 13 other sailors left Cape Town, South Africa, last
week on the second leg of the race. The race started in Charleston
on Sept. 27 and will end there this spring.
	   ``It was the boat that broke. It wasn't the skipper,'' said
Charleston resident Jeff Shattuck, who helped Stricker with onboard
computer problems before the race's start.
	   Those who have talked to Stricker, 63, say he is in good spirits
despite having to pull out of the race.
	   Winds of over 60 mph (96 kmph) are forecast as the remaining
skippers sail toward New Zealand to finish the 7,000-mile
(11,200-kilometer) second leg of the race.
</TEXT>
