<SLUG> BC-Latin American Briefs,0379 </SLUG>

 &UR; Eds: Contains items from Mexico and Brazil. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) _ A former naval admiral from
Argentina's 1970s dirty war, facing charges of child kidnapping,
benefited from a former underling's testimony on Tuesday.
	   Eduardo Massera, a member of the military junta that ruled in
1976-83, went to court to face testimony from former navy Capt.
Jorge Perren in the case of two children born to parents in
captivity.
	   Recanting from earlier testimony, Perren ``said clearly he had
not received orders for the kidnapping of children,'' Massera's
lawyer, Miguel Arce Aggeo, told reporters.
	   Human rights groups say that children born to dissidents held in
captivity during the ``dirty war'' were frequently adopted by
military officials. Massera's case involves the children of
Patricia Roisinblit and Cecilia Vinas, two women who disappeared in
1976 from the Navy Mechanics School.
	   Vinas family lawyer Alcira Rios said that Perren ``behaved like
an underling facing his superior officer.''
	   Eight years after they received a presidential pardon, charges
of child kidnapping have landed Massera and fellow junta member
Jorge Videla back in court.
	   The Argentine government says nearly 9,000 people disappeared
during the military regime's war on leftists and dissidents. Human
rights groups say the figure is closer to 30,000.
	   ___
	   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) _ The Civil Aviation Board has
announced it will require Brazil's four largest airlines to pay
special credits to passengers who miss domestic flights because of
overbooking.
	   Starting Wednesday, bumped passengers will get a credit of
between $105 and $350, depending on the flight and the length of
the delay, board director Marco Antonio Oliveira said.
	   The credit is only good for tickets, upgrades or other airline
services. The airline also must pay for meals, phone calls,
transportation and hotels for longer delays.
	   Oliveira said the aviation board had received 716 complaints
this year from victims of overbooking and had issued 138 fines to
the airlines.
	   He added that the plan was an ``emergency measure'' for the
summer vacation season, which starts this month in Brazil.
</TEXT>
