<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-The Euro-India,0343 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indian software poised for business in euro currency conversions
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-FEA-The Euro-Asia &QL; 
 &UR; By HEMA SHUKLA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ Flush with success from lucrative Y2K
projects for American companies, Indian software firms are poised
to do big business with Europe as it switches to the new single
currency.
	   ``Euro currency is a major opportunity for us,'' said Dewang
Mehta, executive director of the National Association of Software
and Services Companies.
	   The group estimates that by 2002, earnings will be close to dlrs
2 billion for Indian companies helping European banks and financial
institutions change to the common currency. Currently, India's
total earnings from software exports is dlrs 2.3 billion.
	   For the last few years, major Indian software companies like
Bangalore-based Infosys and Microland and Satyam Computers in
Hyderabad made their fortunes offering year 2000 solutions to
foreign clients, mainly in the United States. Today, almost a fifth
of 40,000 software professionals are concentrating on the Y2K
problem. Unless reprogrammed or replaced, computers won't be able
to figure out what year it is in 2000.
	   Mehta said many Indian software firms are offering overseas
clients package deals designed to address both the euro and Y2K
conversions.
	   Currently, as many as 158 of the Fortune 500 companies get
software from India. The euro opportunity is likely to extend over
several years as only 11 of the European Union's 15 members will
participate in the Jan. 1 launch of the euro. The other countries
may join later on, keeping the channels open for Indian software
firms.
	   When the world first awoke to Indian software professionals in
the late 1980s, 95 percent of India's earnings came from flying
engineers to service clients abroad. Today, many companies offer
``offshore'' services, meaning that work is done in India and is
linked by high-speed optic fiber to clients abroad.
	   ``Confidence has built up abroad,'' said Seshagiri.
</TEXT>
