<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Massacre Anniversary,0533 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Marches mark first anniversary of massacre in Chiapas hamlet
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos SCC101-104 &QL; 
 &UR; By ALEJANDRO RUIZ &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ACTEAL, Mexico (AP) _ Carrying wooden crosses, flowers and
candles, about 4,000 rebel supporters marched in southern Chiapas
state to mark the first anniversary of the massacre of 45 Indian
villagers in the hamlet of Acteal.
	   Tuesday's ceremonies were by turns mournful _ when villagers
re-enacted the moments when pro-government gunmen burst into the
hamlet and shot its residents _ and angry, when marchers passed an
army outpost near the town.
	   ``Chiapas is not a barracks, army get out,'' the protesters
shouted at soldiers, who they accuse of having done nothing to stop
the massacre and of harassing survivors.
	   A government helicopter buzzed the demonstration four times as
it was taking place and security agents manned roadblocks into the
village, demanding that outsiders going by identify themselves. The
agents filmed outsiders with video cameras.
	   During a yearlong investigation, most of the suspected killers
identified themselves as supporters of Mexico's ruling party, while
the victims belonged to a group that sympathizes with the leftist
Zapatista rebels. Many of those at Tuesday's ceremonies wore masks
or bandanas covering their faces, a style used by the rebels.
	   Roman Catholic Bishop Samuel Ruiz, whose diocese includes
Acteal, called the massacre site _ where many survivors have still
not returned _ ``a monument to (hope for) peace nationally and
internationally, and to the hope for resurrection.''
	   In a ceremony near the spot where the victims _ most them women
and children _ are buried in a common grave, Antonio Gutierrez told
of the pain of the mainly Tzotzil Indian survivors.
	   ``They have squeezed us in and beat us down, but they have not
been able to crush us,'' Gutierrez said, referring to the state and
federal governments, and the paramilitary groups that survivors say
still operate in the hills near here.
	   Bishop Ruiz referred to the common grave when he said ``in this
trench is germinating a new, more peaceful, more just and worthy
Mexico.''
	   Earlier, residents of the hamlet kneeled in prayer as they did
the day of the massacre, while others with wooden rifles burst onto
the scene and re-enacted the killings.
	   The Zapatista rebels staged a brief armed uprising on New Year's
Day 1994, demanding greater democracy and Indian rights. Talks
between the government and rebels have been stalled since 1996.
	   About 135 people have been arrested in connection with the
massacre, but only one has been convicted in the last year. None of
the upper-level state officials in office at the time _ most of
whom have since resigned _ were ever charged in the case.
	   Residents of Acteal say they continue to be harassed and run off
their small parcels of land by pro-government villagers and troops
stationed nearby. Activists estimate that 10,500 Indians from
Chiapas and dozens from other hamlets have fled their homes in
recent years to escape similar threats and harassment.
</TEXT>
