<HEADER>
w2290 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-1998-Athletics     12-22 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-1998-Athletics ,1011 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Jones, Gebrselassie, El Guerrouj highlight season's performances
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By BERT ROSENTHAL &QC; 
 &UR; AP Track Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ Ten years ago, Florence Griffith Joyner dazzled
the world with her sensational sprint speed. This year, when
Griffith Joyner died suddenly, Marion Jones dazzled the world with
her sensational sprint speed.
	   In only her second full season on the track and field circuit,
Jones went unbeaten in both the women's 100- and 200-meter dashes,
and produced the world's fastest times in both events. Her
clockings of 10.65 seconds in the 100 and 21.62 in the 200 _ both
at the season-ending World Cup in Johannesburg, South Africa _ made
her the No. 2 all-time performer in both dashes, right behind
Griffith Joyner's 10.49 and 21.34, respectively.
	   Griffith Joyner, winner of three gold medals and one silver
medal at the 1988 Olympics, died Sept. 21 when she suffered a
seizure in her sleep and suffocated at her home in Mission Viejo,
California.
	   Jones missed a perfect year, indoors and outdoors, when she was
beaten by 33-year-old Heike Drechsler of Germany in the long jump,
her final competition, in the rain at the World Cup. Drechsler also
won the event in 1985. The loss left Jones with a record of 36
victories in 37 events for the year. She finished with a record
18-sub 11-second clockings and a record nine consecutive sub-10.90s
in her 19 victories in the 100.
	   Her two sprint victories and second-place finish in the long
jump helped the United States women win their first World Cup
title, by 2 points over the European team. Africa won the men's
title for the third straight time.
	   Africa did not get any help from Haile Gebrselassie of Ethiopia
or Hicham El Guerrouj of Morocco in its World Cup victory _ neither
competed _ but the two distance runners were the year's most
dominant male athletes.
	   Gebrselassie and El Guerrouj, both of whom went through the
season unbeaten, shared the new dlrs 1 million Golden League
jackpot with Jones. All three each won their events in all six
Golden League competitions, then won at the IAAF Grand Prix Final
in Moscow.
	   Gebrselassie also regained the world 10,000-meter record in
Hengelo, Netherlands, June 1 with a time of 26:22.75. Twelve days
later in Helsinki, Finland, he reclaimed the world 5,000-meter
record with a clocking of 12:39.36.
	   El Guerrouj set the world 1,500-meter record of 3:26.00 in Rome
July 14, then two days later missed the world mile record by .21
seconds with 3:44.60 at Nice, France, and six days afterward missed
the world 2,000-meter best by .47 seconds with 4:48.35 in
Gateshead, England.
	   While the men's 2,000-meter record survived, the women's did
not, as Ireland's Sonia O'Sullivan lowered it to 9:19.56 in Cork,
Ireland, June 28.
	   One of the year's most dramatic records was set by the United
States 1,600-meter relay team at the Goodwill Games in Uniondale,
New York in July. The foursome of Jerome Young, Antonio Pettigrew,
Tyree Washington and Michael Johnson was timed in 2:54.20.
	   That capped a meet which also included world record-holder
Jackie Joyner-Kersee's victory in her final heptathlon, the year's
top score; world record-holder Dan O'Brien's triumph in his first
decathlon since the 1996 Olympics with 8,755 points, the year's
highest score; Jones' sweep of the 100 and 200 with Goodwill record
times of 10.90 and 21.80, and Johnson's win in the 400 in 43.76,
his fastest time in two years (he ran 43.68 later in the year).
	   Three days after winning her fourth Goodwill title with 6,502
points, the weary Joyner-Kersee _ a six-time Olympic medalist and
world record-holder in the heptathlon _ ended her illustrious
career by placing sixth in the long jump at the U.S. Open at
Edwardsville, Illinois.
	   Marathon world bests also were set this year. Brazil's Ronaldo
da Costa, competing in only his second marathon, slashed 45 seconds
off the men's mark with 2:06:05 in Berlin Sept. 20, and Kenya's
Tegla Loroupe clipped 19 seconds off the women's best with 2:20:47
in Rotterdam April 19. Loroupe also won the World Half-Marathon
title for the second straight year and set a one-hour track race
record.
	   Other outstanding men's performers were Ato Boldon of Trinidad
and Tobago, the world leader in the 100 and 200, with nine times
under 10.00 in the 100, and Paul Tergat of Kenya, winner of the
world cross country title for the fourth time, the world
record-setter in the half-marathon and second-best in the world
over 10,000 meters.
	   Australian Emma George became the first women pole vaulter to
clear 15 feet, raising the record to 15-0 3/4 (4.59 meters), while
Mihaela Melinte of Romania set the women's world hammer throw
record of 239-11 (73.12 meters).
	   Indoors, numerous records were broken. The men's record-breakers
included Gebrselassie in the 2,000 (4:52.86), Kenya's Daniel Komen
in the 3,000 (7:24.90) and 5,000 (12:51.48) and American Maurice
Greene in the 60 (6.39).
	   Women setting records included Mozambique's Maria Mutola in the
800 (1:56.36), Britain's Astia Hansen in the triple jump (49-9),
Romania's Gabriela Szabo in the 2,000 (5:30.53) and American Stacy
Dragila and the Czech Republic's Daniela Bartova in the pole vault
(14-8\). Szabo also was the world outdoor leader in the 1,500,
mile, 3,000 and 5,000, and won the World Cup 3,000.
	   The year was marred by several drug suspensions, including
American Randy Barnes, the world indoor and outdoor record-holder
in the shot put; American Dennis Mitchell, 1992 Olympic bronze
medalist in the 100; Germany's Uta Pippig, three-time winner of the
Boston Marathon; British shot putter Paul Edwards, and Sri Lanka's
Susanthiker Jayasinghe, the 1997 World Championship silver medalist
in the women's 200.
	   Polish Olympic gold medalists Wladyslaw Komar and Tadeusz
Slusarski were killed in a car crash in Warsaw. Komar won the shot
put in 1972 and Slusarski the pole vault in 1976.
</TEXT>
