w2308 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SKorea-BuddhistDisput 1stLd-Writethru   12-22 0655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKorea-Buddhist Dispute, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police storm Buddhist temple to end leadership struggle
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with police gaining control of building; ADDS byline,
photo numbers &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos SEL 101-105 &QL; 
 &UR; By PAUL SHIN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ Police, acting on a court order,
stormed a temple in Seoul on Wednesday, ending a 40-day standoff
between rival monks fighting for leadership of South Korea's
largest Buddhist order.
	   About 20 police and monks were injured, some seriously, during
the 30-minute raid on a five-story administrative building inside
Chogye temple, the spiritual home to 8 million South Korean
Buddhists in a nation of 44 million people.
	   About 100 monks and followers were arrested.
	   The temple in downtown Seoul has been the scene of frequent
violent clashes between rival monks since November. Both sides have
since fought viciously for control over the order's administrative
building. In one clash early this month, more than 60 people were
injured, many seriously.
	   Wednesday's police action came after court officials had twice
failed to serve an expulsion notice to about 100 dissident monks
who had been in control of the building since Nov. 11.
	   Nearly five hours after moving inside the temple before dawn,
hundreds of helmeted riot police, firing tear gas and using water
cannons, moved into the building.
	   Dozens of gray-robed monks, some wearing yellow construction
helmets, vehemently fought back, pouring water from hoses and
throwing firebombs, rocks, furniture and other items.
	   A shaven-headed monk came out on a third-floor balcony, took off
his shirt and slashed his belly with a knife to protest the police
action. The monk, bleeding, was taken inside.
	   Another monk, also bare-chested, poured petroleum over his body
and threatened to set himself on fire.
	   Firefighters quickly put out fires apparently set by monks.
	   Five riot police were injured, two seriously, when they fell
from a mechanically driven ladder transporting them to the roof of
the building.
	   ``We need to end this standoff quickly. For social stability, we
can't allow this standoff to go on too long,'' police lieutenant
Kim Sung-ho said.
	   Religion experts said the police action was not expected to
resolve chronic internal conflicts in the order. For years, Chogye
has been plagued by leadership struggles between rival monks.
	   A Seoul civil court, acting on a lawsuit filed by ousted
mainstream monks, ordered the renegades to move out of the temple
by Saturday. The occupants, however, refused to heed the order.
	   The trouble began after the order's head, Song Wol-ju, sought a
third four-year term. Opponents occupied his office inside the
Chogye temple in early November, effectively blocking his
re-election.
	   The rule stating the order's chief monk cannot serve more than
two terms was enacted in 1994 in an attempt to prevent the office
from wielding too much power.
	   Song claimed that he was not subject to the rule, because he
could not complete his first four-year term in 1980 because of a
disagreement with South Korea's then military government.
	   Song later resigned under pressure, but the renegade monks
refused to leave the temple. Instead, they stepped up their
struggle, occupying a major temple near the southeastern city of
Taegu on Monday. Police there were also poised to intervene.
	   Many religion experts agree that power and money are at the
center of the struggle.
	   The victorious faction gets to control an annual budget of dlrs
10 million, millions of dollars in property and appoint 1,700 monks
to various duties. In the past, those on the losing side were
accused of corruption and deprived of their status as monks.
	   The Chogye Order emphasizes meditative practices and its
traditions date back some 1,000 years to the early Koryo period
(917-1392) of Korean history. 	   
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-SKorea-Buddhist Dispute, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
