<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-Cyprus,0468 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. urges both sides to refrain from using force in Cyprus
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ The U.N. Security Council urged both sides
in Cyprus to refrain from using force and extended the mandate of
the U.N. peacekeeping force on the divided island for six months.
	   Two council resolutions, which were unanimously adopted, make no
mention of the planned deployment of Russian S-300 missiles later
this month on Cyprus. Turkey has said it will use force to stop
them, which would probably lead to a war with Greece.
	   Calling for restraint, the council on Tuesday reiterated ``its
grave concern at the continuing excessive levels of military force
and armaments in the Republic of Cyprus and the rate at which they
are being expanded, upgraded and modernized, including by the
introduction of sophisticated weaponry.''
	   Cyprus has been divided since a 1974 Turkish invasion sparked by
an abortive coup by supporters of union with Greece. A breakaway
Turkish Cypriot state in the north is recognized only by Turkey.
	   The 2,500-member U.N. peacekeeping force, whose mandate was
extended until June 30, patrols the division between the two sides.
	   The Security Council reiterated its previous position that a
Cyprus settlement must be based on a single, independent state
comprising two politically equal communities which are not linked
with any other country.
	   It called the current status quo ``unacceptable'' and said
``negotiations on a final political solution of the Cyprus problem
have been at an impasse for too long.''
	   The Security Council gave strong backing to efforts by Ann
Hercus, the U.N. representative in Cyprus, to restart direct
negotiations to reunite the divided island.
	   It called for a reduction of tensions along cease-fire lines,
renewed efforts to achieve a comprehensive settlement, and a staged
process to limit and then substantially reduce the level of troops
and arms on Cyprus.
	   The council urged all parties to reduce defense spending and
stressed the importance of eventual demilitarization in an overall
settlement.
	   Turkey maintains 35,000 troops in the northern breakaway state.
	   The council noted continuing restrictions on the movement of
peacekeeping troops and reminded both sides of their obligation to
ensure free movement and prevent violence against the soldiers.
	   Calling the Cyprus issue ``very contentious,'' Britain's U.N.
Ambassador Jeremy Greenstock said ``the United Kingdom is very
pleased that in these two resolutions we have good grounds for
moving forward.''
	   ``These are sensitive areas, and of course nobody is getting
everything that they want. We have to go on negotiating, use
diplomacy to the full,'' he said.
</TEXT>
