<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Canada-Swissair Crash,0529 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Remains of all Swissair 111 victims identified
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS previous; ADDS that money was on its way to a Swiss
bank &QL; 
 &UR; By DAVID CRARY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TORONTO (AP) _ Sixteen weeks after the crash of Swissair Flight
111 shattered the bodies of those on board, police said remains of
all 229 victims have been identified using state-of-the-art DNA
techniques.
	   Police also said Tuesday that more than dlrs 1 million in U.S.
currency destined for a Swiss bank has been recovered from the
wreckage on the ocean floor off Nova Scotia. Still missing is a
shipment of diamonds.
	   The impact of the Sept. 2 crash was so great that traditional
identification methods, including dental and X-ray records, were of
minimal use in identifying the remains retrieved from the Atlantic.
	   Blood samples were collected from relatives of those on board,
and the Royal Canadian Mounted Police coordinated an operation at
several forensic laboratories around Canada to match the samples
with the recovered remains.
	   RCMP officers, at a news briefing Tuesday in Halifax, Nova
Scotia, said DNA techniques had never before been used to such an
extent following an air disaster. They said recent technological
advances enabled them to complete tasks in days that might
previously have taken weeks.
	   By comparison, the vast majority of remains from TWA Flight 800,
which crashed off the New York coast in 1996, were identified by
dental records, either alone or in combination with other methods.
Only a few dozen of the 230 remains were identified through DNA.
	   The RCMP recommended that airlines henceforth keep fingerprint
and DNA records of crew members to make identifications easier.
	   About 85 percent of the wreckage of the MD-11 jumbo jet has been
recovered from the seabed, and a scallop dragger is being used to
try to scoop up the rest.
	   Investigators, who will take a 10-day holiday break starting
Wednesday, still don't know what caused the crash, but their
efforts are focused on determining the source of a fire in the
front of the jet.
	   There is evidence of heat damage inside and just outside the
cockpit, where the two pilots reported smoke about 16 minutes
before the plane crashed en route from New York to Geneva.
	   Vic Gerden, chief investigator for the Transportation Safety
Board of Canada, said small pieces of aluminum from the front of
the plane got so hot they melted moments before the crash.
	   Temperatures in some areas hit at least 1200 degrees Fahrenheit
(650 degrees Celsius), the point at which that type of aluminum
melts, Gerden said. But investigators don't know where the fire
started.
	   Investigators have been examining hundreds of segments of
electrical wire from the front of the jet for signs of heat damage.
In all, more than 1 million pieces of wreckage have been recovered.
	   Investigators are trying to reconstruct the forward section of
the fuselage, but the process is complicated because many of the
pieces are small and were damaged by the crash.
	   ``It is a pretty challenging puzzle,'' Gerden said.
</TEXT>
