<SLUG> BC-India-Flights Disrupted,0189 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Fog disrupts flights in India
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ Heavy fog stretching across northern
India forced authorities to shut down New Delhi's airport
indefinitely, disrupting international and domestic flights, local
newspapers reported Wednesday.
	   Several international airlines diverted flights to Bombay or
Calcutta and dozens of flights out of New Delhi were canceled after
authorities shut down the airport Tuesday night, the reports said.
No immediate date was set for resumption of operation.
	   The fog has enveloped a large swathe of northern India for the
last eight days. The weather office said it could last a few more
days.
	   Thousands of passengers were stranded in airports across
northern India, especially in New Delhi and the western metropolis
of Bombay, with airlines unable to find accommodation for them in
hotels.
	   Several Indian airports are only now updating equipment that
would allow pilots to fly even if visibility is poor. Domestic
airlines are only beginning to train their pilots in using such
equipment, The Times of India newspaper reported.
</TEXT>
